00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:32.000
[Amit Varma]: all my notions of what women of the

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Mughal era would have been like, with their

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:36.000
[Amit Varma]: opulence and their harems and their

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.000
[Amit Varma]: subservience to all-powerful emperors.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:40.000
[Amit Varma]: On the contrary, I discovered a complex

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:42.000
[Amit Varma]: world in which women were major players,

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.000
[Amit Varma]: jostling for power, shaping

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:46.000
[Amit Varma]: major events, and many in ways that

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.000
[Amit Varma]: would be invisible to foreign

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:50.000
[Amit Varma]: historians or even male historians

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.000
[Amit Varma]: from India. Ira's previous

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:54.000
[Amit Varma]: book, Heroines, was

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:56.000
[Amit Varma]: also about powerful women either

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.000
[Amit Varma]: forgotten or reshaped by historians.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.000
[Amit Varma]: But it's Daughters of the Sun

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:02.000
[Amit Varma]: and its remarkable Mughal women that

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:04.000
[Amit Varma]: we'll be focusing on today, after

