00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Ira, welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.000
[Amit Varma]: Thank you for having me here. Ira, tell me

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:08.000
[Amit Varma]: a little bit about yourself. How did you, sort of,

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:10.000
[Amit Varma]: where did you study? What did you do?

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.000
[Amit Varma]: How did you get to where you are?

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
[Guest]: So, I'm a little bit of an

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.000
[Guest]: accidental writer of history

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:18.000
[Guest]: because I'm not an historian.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:20.000
[Guest]: I'm actually a

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.000
[Guest]: scientist by training, all those

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.000
[Guest]: many years ago. And it was just

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.000
[Guest]: something that, you know, I did

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.000
[Guest]: because in those days, when

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
[Guest]: you were a capable student, you were kind of

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.000
[Guest]: and you were alright in the sciences, you were

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
[Guest]: pushed towards that. And literature,

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.000
[Guest]: which I was also interested in, was not

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:38.000
[Guest]: considered a suitable or serious

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:40.000
[Guest]: enough career option.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
[Guest]: So I did sciences, I did it for quite a while

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:44.000
[Guest]: and then it just so happened that

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.000
[Guest]: nothing in it really interested me as a career

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:48.000
[Guest]: to continue in. And then

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.000
[Guest]: as is the case, I think,

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.000
[Guest]: for many women, especially, and

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:54.000
[Guest]: especially of my generation,

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
[Guest]: things took maybe a backseat

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:58.000
[Guest]: and other things take over. Your life, you know,

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.000
[Guest]: family responsibilities and

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
[Guest]: just other things that you have to do.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.000
[Guest]: And I didn't work for a while.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:06.000
[Guest]: And then when my children were born and they were

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.000
[Guest]: slowly growing up, I had this idea of

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.000
[Guest]: getting back to literature because I had always really loved

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.000
[Guest]: writing. So I wrote a

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
[Guest]: manuscript, which was

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.000
[Guest]: on mythology. And I

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.000
[Guest]: approached a publisher who was at that time more

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:20.000
[Guest]: interested in writing history. So though he liked

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.000
[Guest]: my writing a lot, he

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:24.000
[Guest]: suggested that I write a book on history.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:26.000
[Guest]: And that is completely

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.000
[Guest]: how it happened, completely accidentally.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
[Guest]: And I found out that it was something that

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.000
[Guest]: I enjoyed doing. And strangely

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.000
[Guest]: enough, it's something in which I can use

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.000
[Guest]: both my skills, my scientific

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
[Guest]: background, because it requires a lot of research,

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.000
[Guest]: being extremely thorough

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:42.000
[Guest]: with things like sources and understanding

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:44.000
[Guest]: primary material, and as well

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.000
[Guest]: as my writing skills and, you know,

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:48.000
[Guest]: my fondness for literature. So the

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.000
[Guest]: writing of history or narrative history became

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:52.000
[Guest]: something that I was very

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:54.000
[Guest]: lucky enough to find that I could

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:56.000
[Guest]: combine the skills that I had and do

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
[Guest]: something which was so amazingly

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:00.000
[Amit Varma]: rewarding for me. And did you also read history

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:02.000
[Amit Varma]: at this time? At the time of

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:04.000
[Amit Varma]: starting to write, do you mean? Yeah, I mean,

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
[Guest]: did you read history for leisure also? I

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.000
[Guest]: wasn't reading history for

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
[Guest]: leisure per se before I started

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.000
[Guest]: writing about it, though I was

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.000
[Guest]: reading around it. You know,

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
[Guest]: I suppose what happened

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
[Guest]: is that as you, you know,

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.000
[Guest]: grow up in life, as you go through various

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
[Guest]: changes and various phases

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
[Guest]: of your life, you get interested in various

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:26.000
[Guest]: things. So, you know, initially

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:28.000
[Guest]: perhaps I would view things

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
[Guest]: as a young woman, and then as a young

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
[Guest]: woman out in the world, and then maybe

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.000
[Guest]: as a young Asian woman, you know.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
[Guest]: And then things change, and I saw things

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:38.000
[Guest]: as a parent, and then as a parent of

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.000
[Guest]: young girls. And so at each

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:42.000
[Guest]: stage of my life, I was interested in different

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
[Guest]: readings. And so one of the things

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.000
[Guest]: that I started to get interested in, before history

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
[Guest]: even, was the way in

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
[Guest]: which we have been colonized in

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
[Guest]: our imagination, in the way we view the

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
[Guest]: world, in our memories even,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
[Guest]: you know, to the extent where many of

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
[Guest]: my memories, like the way I grew up reading

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.000
[Guest]: things like Enid Blyton,

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.000
[Guest]: my memories and my nostalgia were

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.000
[Guest]: for things that I had no physical

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.000
[Guest]: experience of. So whether it was

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
[Guest]: for soft summer sunshine, or cucumber

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:10.000
[Guest]: sandwiches, or Wordsworth's

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.000
[Guest]: poetry, which I could quote, but I couldn't

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.000
[Guest]: quote Mir or Ghalib, you know.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.000
[Guest]: So these were things that started

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:18.000
[Guest]: bothering me, and things that I started thinking

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
[Guest]: about. You know, I read Pankaj Mishra,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
[Guest]: Roy Moxton,

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.000
[Guest]: The Theft of India, various things around these

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
[Guest]: issues. And that was something

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
[Guest]: which was in my background as I

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.000
[Guest]: started to think about writing

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.000
[Amit Varma]: about history. And who

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.000
[Amit Varma]: are the sort of thinkers who

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.000
[Amit Varma]: have been a big influence on you? Like one question

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:38.000
[Amit Varma]: I sometimes ask my guests is

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:40.000
[Amit Varma]: if they can name books which change the way

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
[Amit Varma]: they look at the world. And not necessarily specific

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
[Amit Varma]: books, but even thinkers, or

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.000
[Guest]: you know. Well, I would say

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
[Guest]: there has been a three-fold

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
[Guest]: sort of influence on me. So on

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.000
[Guest]: the one hand, there are

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
[Guest]: as I was saying, the writers who have pointed

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.000
[Guest]: out the

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
[Guest]: colonization of our history.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
[Guest]: So people like Pankaj Mishra and many others, you know,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
[Guest]: even Naipaul, the way he talks about identity,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
[Guest]: and the way he talks about Indianness

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
[Guest]: outside India,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
[Guest]: rootlessness. These are all things, people who

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.000
[Guest]: have had an influence on me.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
[Guest]: And then the second sort of phase

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
[Guest]: of influence has been the women

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
[Guest]: writers, the women who talk about gender.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.000
[Guest]: So whether it's Ira Vethikarve

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
[Guest]: and Uganta, you know, I found her

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
[Guest]: essays startling about the way in which she

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
[Guest]: writes about women of the Mahabharata.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
[Guest]: And one writer who has

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.000
[Guest]: been extremely influential for

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
[Guest]: me has been Dr. Rubilal,

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
[Guest]: who is, she defines herself as a

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
[Guest]: feminist historian. She's a

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
[Guest]: professor and a writer of history. She's written

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
[Guest]: about Noor Jahan, but her

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.000
[Guest]: most groundbreaking book was about

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:42.000
[Guest]: the early Mughal harem,

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
[Guest]: domesticity and power.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
[Guest]: And so she, for the first time I came across

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.000
[Guest]: a woman scholar who was

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
[Guest]: writing about the way in which

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
[Guest]: the harem existed

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
[Guest]: in a completely different way in which

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
[Guest]: I had thought about it. So her

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:58.000
[Guest]: writing for me was extremely important.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:00.000
[Guest]: I have based a lot of my writing on

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.000
[Guest]: what she has already discovered.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.000
[Guest]: And there's also

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
[Guest]: people like Chimamanda Adichie,

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
[Guest]: at a different level, the way she talks about

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
[Guest]: the importance of a single

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.000
[Guest]: narrative, how that can be so harmful

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
[Guest]: for us if we see the world

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
[Guest]: and our past and our present

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
[Guest]: through only one filter.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
[Guest]: So these are some of the people. And then

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
[Guest]: the very third and last aspect, which

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.000
[Guest]: was useful for me, is stylistic.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
[Guest]: Now we often don't talk about that

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
[Guest]: very much because I suppose writing of

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
[Guest]: history, the material itself is so

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
[Guest]: interesting that people mostly ask

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
[Guest]: me about the material itself, but stylistically

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
[Guest]: speaking, people who have been influential

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
[Guest]: are people like Hilary Mantel, even though she writes

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
[Guest]: fiction, fictionalized

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
[Guest]: history, but still, her style is

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
[Guest]: so arresting that when I read Wolf Hall

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
[Guest]: and her trilogy, I thought

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
[Guest]: this is the way I want to write history for

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
[Guest]: India as well. I want people to

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
[Guest]: feel like they have been caught by the scruff

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
[Guest]: of the neck and thrown into that century,

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
[Guest]: whichever century I'm writing about, and to

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
[Guest]: feel the reality of it, the geographical

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
[Guest]: reality, the noises, the smells, everything

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
[Guest]: in three dimensions. So these

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
[Guest]: are some of the influences that have

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
[Amit Varma]: shaped my writing. And one of the things

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
[Amit Varma]: I've sort of realized in the last few years,

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
[Amit Varma]: thanks partly to writers like you, is that

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
[Amit Varma]: so much of history

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
[Amit Varma]: has been captive to and

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
[Amit Varma]: colonized by the male gaze,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.000
[Amit Varma]: which is, you know, the history of humanity

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
[Amit Varma]: has been treated as a history of men who are

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
[Amit Varma]: going out and doing big things,

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
[Amit Varma]: invading kingdoms and they're

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
[Amit Varma]: setting up dynasties and all of that,

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
[Amit Varma]: and also they've been looked at,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
[Amit Varma]: most of this history has been

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
[Amit Varma]: written by male historians, and that's

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
[Amit Varma]: the perspective you see, and the women are largely

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
[Amit Varma]: invisible. And is that something

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
[Amit Varma]: which sort of influenced,

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
[Amit Varma]: because you were already thinking

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
[Amit Varma]: about these issues, like you mentioned,

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
[Amit Varma]: is that something that influenced

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
[Amit Varma]: what you chose your subject

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
[Guest]: to be when you actually started writing history?

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
[Guest]: Yes, yes, definitely. You know,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
[Guest]: I read a

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
[Guest]: statistic which said that

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
[Guest]: 99.5% of the

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
[Guest]: written history that we see around us,

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
[Guest]: starting from 5000 BC

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
[Guest]: onwards, you know, whatever there is,

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
[Guest]: the sculptures, the writing,

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.000
[Guest]: the calligraphy, everything,

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
[Guest]: 99.5% deals with men,

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.000
[Guest]: and 0.5% tells the

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.000
[Guest]: stories of women. So that statistic

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
[Guest]: sort of stopped me in my tracks. It was a very

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
[Guest]: startling statistic. And when I

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:18.000
[Guest]: stopped to think about what I knew about women's

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
[Guest]: history, I think that's very true.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
[Guest]: So it definitely,

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
[Guest]: starting from the fact that I have

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
[Guest]: two, as I said, two daughters,

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
[Guest]: I wanted them to see the

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
[Guest]: world around them in a less biased way,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
[Guest]: that history need not

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
[Guest]: necessarily be about the fighting of

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
[Guest]: battles, about the conquest of territories,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
[Guest]: and there are many, many other aspects

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.000
[Guest]: that form a civilization, maybe

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.000
[Guest]: so-called soft power, you know,

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
[Guest]: the music, the creation of music, the creation

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
[Guest]: of art, architecture, politics,

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
[Guest]: behind the scenes, who controls things,

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
[Guest]: sexual politics, these are all

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
[Guest]: things that contribute to a culture.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
[Guest]: And very often, women are absolutely

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
[Guest]: instrumental in that aspect of it.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
[Guest]: So for 100%, this was something that

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
[Guest]: I thought that whatever I write,

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
[Guest]: even if it's the history of a man, or

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
[Guest]: you know, whichever aspect I'm going to cover,

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
[Guest]: I'm going to bring in all the women involved,

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:08.000
[Guest]: because they really tend to be written out

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.000
[Guest]: of the stories of men,

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
[Guest]: and history ends up being the story of men told

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
[Amit Varma]: by men.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And how difficult

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
[Amit Varma]: is it then to

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
[Amit Varma]: start researching into that kind of history, because

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
[Amit Varma]: most history is written by male historians

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
[Amit Varma]: who tend to, you know,

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.000
[Amit Varma]: whitewash the women or recast them in

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
[Amit Varma]: acceptable ways, and so, I mean, this is

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
[Amit Varma]: really a dual question, in the sense

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
[Unknown]: as someone who's not a trained historian,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
[Amit Varma]: how, what is it like to do

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
[Amit Varma]: history? How did you learn that?

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And also then going beyond that,

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
[Amit Varma]: what do you do about this essential limitation

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
[Amit Varma]: that you are broadening the gaze

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
[Amit Varma]: by which you're looking at history, but

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
[Guest]: the voices don't have that same gaze?

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
[Guest]: That's right. To answer the first part

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
[Guest]: of your question, I think

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
[Guest]: the way you can teach yourself history is go to

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
[Guest]: the primary sources, you know, that's the most

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
[Guest]: important aspect

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
[Guest]: of writing history.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
[Guest]: And there is a lot of primary sources,

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.000
[Guest]: even, of course, much less

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
[Guest]: where women are concerned, so I always make an

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
[Guest]: effort to find the women's

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
[Guest]: voices. So, for example, in one of, in my first

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
[Guest]: book, I've written the story of

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
[Guest]: Amrapali, who was a Buddhist nun at the time

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
[Guest]: of the Buddha, 6th century BCE.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
[Guest]: And you would think, okay, there's nothing

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
[Guest]: written about women in the 6th century BCE,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
[Guest]: but luckily there is, because she lived

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
[Guest]: at the time of the Buddha, and

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
[Guest]: the Buddhist monks were one of the

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
[Guest]: first great writers

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
[Guest]: of history, you know, and they wrote everything

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
[Guest]: around the Buddha. And so we have the story

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
[Guest]: of the nuns, and their poems,

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
[Guest]: they wrote poetry, and very luckily for us,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
[Guest]: we have the voice of this woman from 2000

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
[Guest]: years ago, even today.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
[Guest]: Her story, her longings,

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
[Guest]: her desires, the way she talks

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
[Guest]: about the evanescence of her beauty,

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.000
[Guest]: how it has faded, and this is so poignant

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
[Guest]: to us even today. So, there are

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
[Guest]: ways women's voices are there,

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
[Guest]: it just takes a little bit more effort,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
[Guest]: a little bit more diligence and searching

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
[Guest]: to get to them. Like, for example,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
[Guest]: if we have Lakshmibai, the story

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
[Guest]: of Lakshmibai has been written by many different

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.000
[Guest]: men.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
[Guest]: And you have the Europeans who are

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
[Guest]: writing about her, and they're writing from their point

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
[Guest]: of view, with their European gaze,

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
[Guest]: so they talk about her as being like an

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
[Guest]: Amazon, and immediately there as well,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
[Guest]: there's a texturing of Rani Lakshmibai,

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
[Guest]: which is very different from when

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
[Guest]: a Brahmin writes about her,

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
[Guest]: and writes about her as this great

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
[Guest]: widow, this great, you know, almost

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
[Guest]: a holy woman, Mother India. So you have

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
[Guest]: Mother India on one side, the Amazon woman

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
[Guest]: on the other side. You see some men look

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
[Guest]: at the same, very same woman, in many

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.000
[Guest]: different ways. And then it is my

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.000
[Guest]: job to sort of see the intersection

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
[Guest]: of these many gazes, and to see

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
[Guest]: where does the humanity

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
[Guest]: of this woman lie. What made

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
[Guest]: her an Amazon? Her fearlessness,

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
[Guest]: her amazing bravery, yes.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
[Guest]: What made her Mother India? The fact that

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
[Guest]: she adopted this child, but also

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
[Guest]: the fact that she nurtured her city.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
[Guest]: And for me, that is the crux of this woman.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
[Guest]: This nurturing aspect of her.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
[Guest]: That she didn't want to die in battle.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
[Guest]: We are always told, you know, Lakshmibai, Khob Ladi

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
[Guest]: Madani, you know, that is the line we remember.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
[Guest]: But what makes her a heroine for me

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
[Guest]: is the fact that she wanted to live,

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
[Guest]: and she wanted her people to live,

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
[Guest]: and she fought very hard for her right

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
[Guest]: to rule her people, and for them to be

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
[Guest]: safe under her care. She eventually

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
[Guest]: lost, and she died in battle. But

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
[Guest]: these are the aspects of women's stories

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.000
[Guest]: that I want to bring up. Not necessarily the dying

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
[Guest]: in battle, which is, at the end of the

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.000
[Guest]: day, a very male way of showing heroism.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.000
[Guest]: But there is a different way of being heroic,

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
[Guest]: and that is something that I wanted to

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
[Guest]: look at in my first book.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
[Guest]: So those stories are

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
[Guest]: there, that literature is there.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
[Guest]: It takes maybe a different gaze,

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
[Guest]: a different interpretation to get at it.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And one of the interesting things

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned in Heroines,

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
[Amit Varma]: we'll talk more about Daughters of the Sun today, but

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
[Amit Varma]: I found Heroines very interesting, and

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
[Amit Varma]: in fact, it actually reminded me

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
[Amit Varma]: of Yogantha, which is why I brought it up

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
[Amit Varma]: in our conversation earlier, and I mean that entirely

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
[Amit Varma]: as a compliment, because I think Yogantha is a masterpiece.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
[Amit Varma]: And one of the interesting things you said

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
[Amit Varma]: at the start of Heroines is

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
[Amit Varma]: you spoke about how

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
[Amit Varma]: there is this sort of interplay

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
[Amit Varma]: between history and myth,

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
[Amit Varma]: and how a lot of women in history

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
[Amit Varma]: are recast in convenient

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.000
[Amit Varma]: ways that are palatable to men,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.000
[Amit Varma]: like what you just described about

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Lakshmibai, and often they're almost sanitized

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
[Amit Varma]: and they're made to fit into these roles.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And equally,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
[Amit Varma]: how myths can also, you know,

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
[Amit Varma]: the same sort of interplay works the

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
[Amit Varma]: other way, and I was very fascinated by

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
[Amit Varma]: the chapter on Draupadi in that,

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
[Amit Varma]: because what we find

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
[Amit Varma]: with many of our myths is

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
[Amit Varma]: that those myths are shaped

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
[Amit Varma]: to fit social norms. So you look at someone like

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Sita, she is the ideal Hindu

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
[Amit Varma]: woman in terms of being pativrata,

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
[Amit Varma]: being devoted to her husband,

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
[Amit Varma]: virtuous, and so on and so forth.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
[Amit Varma]: But Draupadi is like this

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
[Amit Varma]: incredibly feisty character who just

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
[Amit Varma]: goes against everything you would think

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
[Amit Varma]: of as, you know, the ideal Hindu

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
[Amit Varma]: nari. And

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, why do you think Draupadi was even

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
[Guest]: conceived and imagined?

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
[Guest]: Draupadi is

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
[Guest]: one of my all-time favorite characters,

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
[Guest]: I have to say, because she's in a way the antithesis

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
[Guest]: of Sita, you know. What I love

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
[Guest]: about her is her fierce

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
[Guest]: erudition and her

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
[Guest]: outspokenness and her anger.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
[Guest]: Now, you know, anger is something that we don't

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
[Guest]: see encouraged in Indian women. You know,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
[Guest]: Indian women are encouraged to be quieter, to keep

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
[Guest]: their anger internalized. And in a way,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
[Guest]: Sita, I feel, internalized her feelings,

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
[Guest]: her anger, and she combusts

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
[Guest]: in a way. You know, she dies, she commits suicide.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
[Guest]: Draupadi doesn't do that.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
[Guest]: She externalizes her anger.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
[Guest]: In fact, she carries it on her own body

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
[Guest]: by keeping her hair loose for those 12 years

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
[Guest]: in exile, you know, and said,

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
[Guest]: I will not tie up my hair till it is drenched in blood,

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.000
[Guest]: in the blood of my enemy. So I find this

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
[Guest]: a very powerful thing that she

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:40.000
[Guest]: has said, which is why I start my book with Draupadi,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
[Guest]: because I want today's women to remember

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
[Guest]: this for their daughters and

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.000
[Guest]: for themselves. You know, we call our daughters Sita,

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
[Guest]: we never call them Draupadi. Why is that?

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
[Guest]: You know, I really want to challenge that and say,

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
[Guest]: let's go back. So people have imagined

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
[Guest]: this woman all these thousands of years

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
[Guest]: ago. As you say, why did

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
[Guest]: this happen and how did it happen?

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
[Guest]: How did it happen that she was allowed to say these

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.000
[Guest]: things, right? She even challenges Yudhishthira

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
[Guest]: oftentimes. She calls him

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
[Guest]: less than a man, almost a eunuch for not

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
[Guest]: standing up for her, for not fighting for her.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
[Guest]: She says some very damaging things

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.000
[Guest]: for, you know, as a queen to her husband.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.000
[Guest]: But she's allowed to say this.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
[Guest]: So what is it

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
[Guest]: in our time in the past

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
[Guest]: that women were given this voice, this agency,

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
[Guest]: and in fact, such a powerful

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
[Guest]: woman who is, they say, the cause of the

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
[Guest]: war itself and who brings about, you know,

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
[Guest]: the end of that era. What is

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
[Guest]: it that allowed this woman to be the way

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.000
[Guest]: she is, that society accepted

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
[Guest]: her and loved her in her own time

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
[Guest]: as this woman? But if you, you know,

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
[Guest]: when I explain it in my chapter, through the years,

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.000
[Guest]: through the centuries, she has been sanitized

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
[Guest]: progressively.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
[Guest]: So that in the end, finally, she is almost

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
[Guest]: a Sita-like character. If you look at,

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
[Guest]: you know, the actors who are playing her today on

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
[Guest]: television, they are the same

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
[Guest]: fair-skinned, you know,

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
[Guest]: patirat women, clearly

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
[Guest]: upper-caste, brahminical, you know,

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
[Guest]: part of the patriarchy, very much in,

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
[Guest]: you know, part of the system.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
[Guest]: So why has that happened? Why are we

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
[Guest]: today almost more regressive

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
[Guest]: and having to make our women conform

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
[Guest]: to certain standards, to

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
[Guest]: shut down their anger, to stamp

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
[Guest]: down their voices? What is it that in us

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
[Guest]: as a society, that so many thousands

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
[Guest]: of years ago, this woman was allowed

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
[Guest]: to be angry, to be fierce

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
[Guest]: and to question the men in her life,

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
[Guest]: whereas today, she has been sanitized

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
[Guest]: to such an extent that she is almost

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
[Guest]: indistinguishable. So often when I

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
[Guest]: talk about heroines, I show a slide

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
[Guest]: which shows the eight women

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
[Guest]: as they are portrayed in popular culture today

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
[Guest]: and there's hardly any difference between them.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
[Guest]: They're all the same, very fair-skinned

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
[Guest]: with their, you know, full jewellery.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
[Guest]: And the jewellery is a symbol in Indian society

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
[Guest]: of marriage status, which means that your sexuality

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
[Guest]: is allowed only within

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
[Guest]: this sanctified arena of marriage.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
[Guest]: You know, and the aim is to procreate,

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:50.000
[Guest]: to have children. Why is it

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
[Guest]: that all these women must

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
[Guest]: conform to this standard, whereas earlier

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
[Guest]: on in their own times, whether it's 2000 years

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
[Guest]: ago, 500 years ago, you know, Mirabai,

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
[Guest]: etc., they were allowed to have

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
[Guest]: agency, they were allowed to have

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
[Guest]: freedom of expression. Mirabai too

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
[Guest]: said some very shocking things. If we look

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
[Guest]: at her padas today, she says

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
[Guest]: things like, this

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
[Guest]: habit that we have, I'm just paraphrasing,

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
[Guest]: but this habit that we have of sending

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
[Guest]: young women away to get

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
[Guest]: married and severe all connection

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
[Guest]: with their natal homes, so that there's

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.000
[Guest]: no support structure for them. She questions

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.000
[Guest]: this. She says, why do we do this? Why do

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.000
[Guest]: we send young girls so far away?

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.000
[Guest]: Why are they abused by their in-laws? Why do

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:30.000
[Guest]: we allow this to happen? These are such

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.000
[Guest]: powerful things for women to say.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:34.000
[Guest]: And yet, with time, what happened

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
[Guest]: to Mirabai was, it was, slowly

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
[Guest]: her story was altered, so that she

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:40.000
[Guest]: became this married woman who

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
[Guest]: waited conveniently and

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
[Guest]: quietly, submissively for her husband to die.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:46.000
[Guest]: Then once he died, she stepped

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.000
[Guest]: out of the house as a good widow, and

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.000
[Guest]: she was allowed to go and sing her songs. Whereas

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
[Guest]: that is probably not what happened. She probably

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.000
[Guest]: left home because she was fed up of being

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:56.000
[Guest]: abused by her in-laws and by her husband.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
[Guest]: She left her husband as a married

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.000
[Guest]: woman, and as a single married woman

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.000
[Guest]: she was alone on the roads,

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:04.000
[Guest]: accompanied by other singers, other devotees,

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
[Guest]: by men and women. So she was

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
[Guest]: in a sexually vulnerable position.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.000
[Guest]: And yet, she went out and she sang

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.000
[Guest]: these amazing songs, which

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
[Guest]: I think, the single most

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:16.000
[Guest]: recognizable

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:18.000
[Guest]: figure, maybe the female figure, is Mirabai.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.000
[Guest]: Everybody knows her songs. So she

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:22.000
[Guest]: tapped into a certain longing in

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
[Guest]: people, unlike anybody else

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:26.000
[Guest]: before, you know. But yet

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:28.000
[Guest]: today, all these 100-500 years later,

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.000
[Guest]: we have made her into this very

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:32.000
[Guest]: sanitized figure. And if you ask Rajput ladies

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
[Guest]: today, they will say, yes, Mirabai is a wonderful

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
[Guest]: heroine, but we will not encourage

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.000
[Guest]: her behavior in our daughters. Again,

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.000
[Guest]: this difference between what we will

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.000
[Guest]: allow our daughters today, and

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.000
[Guest]: what the figures have stood for in the past.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
[Guest]: So this is something that I want people to

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:48.000
[Guest]: think about, that why is it? Why has

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:50.000
[Guest]: that happened? And what can we do?

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.000
[Guest]: Can we look back upon these women as

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:54.000
[Guest]: heroic figures for daughters today?

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.000
[Guest]: For young women in India today?

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:58.000
[Guest]: You know, let us challenge this

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.000
[Guest]: very fair

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:02.000
[Guest]: and sanitized vision that we are being

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:04.000
[Guest]: offered time and again, and it sort of force-fed

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:06.000
[Guest]: these women's images. Let us challenge that

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:08.000
[Guest]: and look back to what we have in our

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:10.000
[Guest]: culture. Sometimes I'm told, oh,

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.000
[Guest]: feminism is a Western construct.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:14.000
[Guest]: It is not. We have had women who are

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:16.000
[Guest]: fiercely feminists, you know, from Gargi

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:18.000
[Guest]: onwards, who have spoken their mind.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:20.000
[Guest]: So our society has accepted

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
[Guest]: and fostered this spirit. Why has it

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:24.000
[Guest]: gone? So these are some of the thoughts that I

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:26.000
[Guest]: want people to have and to think about.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
[Amit Varma]: That's a great insight. In fact, I have a

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:30.000
[Amit Varma]: couple of digressions, and you know, what you said

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:32.000
[Amit Varma]: about what Mirabai said, that why are women

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:34.000
[Amit Varma]: sent away to their husbands without anything, blah, blah,

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:36.000
[Amit Varma]: reminds me of a recent episode

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.000
[Amit Varma]: I did with the economic

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:40.000
[Unknown]: historian Chinmay Tumbe, who wrote a book

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:42.000
[Unknown]: called India Moving on Migration.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And one of the points he made, and to my

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:46.000
[Amit Varma]: shame, this point had never struck me,

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:48.000
[Amit Varma]: is that a very large

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:50.000
[Amit Varma]: part of migration is simply

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:52.000
[Amit Varma]: women getting married and going.

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:54.000
[Amit Varma]: And we don't think of that. We think of migration as men

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:56.000
[Amit Varma]: going, or families going, or whatever, but

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:58.000
[Guest]: so much of migration is women getting married and going.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:00.000
[Amit Varma]: That's right, yes. And the other thought

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:02.000
[Amit Varma]: that sort of struck me was, I'd also done an episode

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:04.000
[Amit Varma]: with Tony Joseph, who's written a book

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:06.000
[Amit Varma]: Early Indians, and one of the points he made

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.000
[Amit Varma]: in that was that they were, you know,

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:10.000
[Amit Varma]: a couple of millennia ago, you had

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
[Amit Varma]: competing strands within Hinduism,

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:14.000
[Amit Varma]: and they were different, and they were competing,

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:16.000
[Amit Varma]: and not all of them

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
[Amit Varma]: were this particular fixed strand

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.000
[Amit Varma]: which looks at a woman in a particular way

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:22.000
[Amit Varma]: like we look at Sita today.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
[Amit Varma]: And it just so happens that one of those

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.000
[Amit Varma]: strands kind of won out, and it was a

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.000
[Amit Varma]: political victory, and that strand then dominated

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
[Amit Varma]: our culture, and all of these women

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.000
[Amit Varma]: and now this is me speaking,

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.000
[Amit Varma]: sort of got, you know, recast

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
[Amit Varma]: into it. But the fact

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:38.000
[Guest]: is that these strands were there. Yes.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:40.000
[Guest]: Absolutely. And

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:42.000
[Guest]: to come to your first point,

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:44.000
[Guest]: this whole point

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:46.000
[Guest]: about the alienation of women from their natal

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:48.000
[Guest]: homes, it's something which we have exoticized

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.000
[Guest]: and wrongly so. You know, this

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:52.000
[Guest]: whole bidai genre which has come up,

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.000
[Guest]: which talks about the saying

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:56.000
[Guest]: goodbye to the bride,

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.000
[Guest]: it's a terrible thing. We, you know, we must

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
[Guest]: not exoticize it. It is a terrible thing to cut

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.000
[Guest]: off a young woman from her

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
[Guest]: family, from her mother, from her

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
[Guest]: natal family, from the support of her brothers, her sisters,

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:08.000
[Guest]: everything she has known. She's thrown

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:10.000
[Guest]: into a new place where she's automatically

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:12.000
[Guest]: a second citizen because she doesn't know anything

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
[Guest]: about that new household.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:16.000
[Guest]: So this is something that

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:18.000
[Guest]: has been, you know, very much praised

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:20.000
[Guest]: in folk literature,

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.000
[Guest]: and Mirabai challenges that, and so it is

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.000
[Guest]: something very refreshing. When I read that, I said,

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:26.000
[Guest]: yes, this is something, today I can

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:28.000
[Guest]: absolutely understand what she's saying

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:30.000
[Guest]: and I would say the same thing for my daughters. I would

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.000
[Guest]: not want them to be cut off from their families,

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:34.000
[Guest]: you know. So this is an

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.000
[Guest]: interesting point that women were always,

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:38.000
[Guest]: endogamy has been practiced for so long,

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:40.000
[Guest]: sending women upwards and onwards and

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:42.000
[Guest]: away from their family, which was in effect

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:44.000
[Guest]: in a way almost castrating them

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:46.000
[Guest]: because then they have no power to fall back on, right?

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.000
[Guest]: So they have to do what they must do in their

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:50.000
[Guest]: in-laws' family. And

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:52.000
[Guest]: the second point about them, there have been many

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:54.000
[Guest]: different strands, and it is a point that I make

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:56.000
[Guest]: as well, is that there are very

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:58.000
[Guest]: many different ways of being

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:00.000
[Guest]: feminine, of being a woman, and being a

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:02.000
[Guest]: heroic woman in India. What does it mean to be

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.000
[Guest]: a heroic woman, right? There are many

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:06.000
[Guest]: many different ways of doing that, and

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.000
[Guest]: every woman in the book that I have written

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:10.000
[Guest]: does it in a different way, whether it is

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.000
[Guest]: through her music, whether it is

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:14.000
[Guest]: in a more manly way, in quotes,

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:16.000
[Guest]: on the battlefield, whether it is

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.000
[Guest]: you know, leading men

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:20.000
[Guest]: in battle, or whether it is just

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.000
[Guest]: shaping society around her

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:24.000
[Guest]: in whatever way she can. These

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:26.000
[Guest]: are all heroic ways, and these were

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.000
[Guest]: very accepted ways, and there was no one

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.000
[Guest]: single way. When I came across these, you know,

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.000
[Guest]: the writings on these women, they were never

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:34.000
[Guest]: criticized and told, it would be better

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:36.000
[Guest]: for you to be this other way, you know,

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.000
[Guest]: rather than being the way you are. They were allowed to be

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:40.000
[Guest]: that different way, and it is only in more recent

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:42.000
[Guest]: times, I think, that we have

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:44.000
[Guest]: drawn these strictures around these women and

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:46.000
[Amit Varma]: wanted them to be a certain way.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:48.000
[Amit Varma]: And what both your books also demonstrate is that

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:50.000
[Amit Varma]: that heroism is something that you

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:52.000
[Amit Varma]: have to look in the context of each individual

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:54.000
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, what are the restraints

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:56.000
[Amit Varma]: on them and so on. And we often

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:58.000
[Amit Varma]: tend to think of heroism as

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.000
[Amit Varma]: just marching out to battle holding a sword,

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.000
[Amit Varma]: which is why, you know, the point you made earlier about Lakshmi Bai

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:04.000
[Unknown]: and, you know, that's a typical

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
[Amit Varma]: image of her, and heroism

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.000
[Amit Varma]: amounts to a lot more than that.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on to your second book now,

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:12.000
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, where did, given

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:14.000
[Amit Varma]: that everything that I had read

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:16.000
[Amit Varma]: of Mughal history before this,

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:18.000
[Amit Varma]: most of it was centered around these men

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:20.000
[Amit Varma]: and there was this notion that women

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.000
[Amit Varma]: are just, you know, stuck in their imperial

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:24.000
[Amit Varma]: harems or desirannas or whatever and they're not important

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:26.000
[Amit Varma]: characters. What brought you

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:28.000
[Amit Varma]: to the notion of writing this book? When did you

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:30.000
[Amit Varma]: realize that this material is really

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.000
[Guest]: rich and someone needs to tell this story?

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.000
[Guest]: I think it was, you know, when I wrote Heroines,

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:36.000
[Guest]: one of the heroines that I write about

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:38.000
[Guest]: is Jahanara Begum.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:40.000
[Guest]: And it was when I found out how much

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:42.000
[Guest]: she had done, you know, and her accomplishments,

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:44.000
[Guest]: it was a very visceral

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:46.000
[Guest]: and personal reaction that I had

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
[Guest]: because I'm a Delhi woman, I was brought up in Delhi.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:50.000
[Guest]: Jahanara is a Delhi woman

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:52.000
[Guest]: to the extent that she has created great

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.000
[Guest]: extents of old Delhi, and yet

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:56.000
[Guest]: growing up, I was never taught about her.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:58.000
[Guest]: So I had this sort of visceral

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
[Guest]: reaction to this, a sort of anger

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
[Guest]: and a sort of, you know,

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.000
[Guest]: feeling that enough is enough

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:06.000
[Guest]: and what lies

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.000
[Guest]: behind all these stories that we have not been

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:10.000
[Guest]: told? So there was this questioning

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:12.000
[Guest]: of the given sort of history

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:14.000
[Guest]: that had been taught, Mughal history,

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:16.000
[Guest]: in very bullet form, you know, in a very dry

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:18.000
[Guest]: way, and about the men, because they have

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:20.000
[Guest]: been amazing Mughal men, definitely.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:22.000
[Guest]: But where are the women

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:24.000
[Guest]: and why were they written out of the stories?

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:26.000
[Guest]: Was there possibly more to them?

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:28.000
[Guest]: And that was when I started researching them

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:30.000
[Guest]: and I found Ruby Lal's book, and where I

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.000
[Guest]: realized that the very idea of the harem,

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:34.000
[Guest]: which to my mind, like to yours,

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:36.000
[Guest]: was something very exotic, was

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.000
[Guest]: actually something that we had inherited from the

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:40.000
[Guest]: European gaze, because in parallel

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:42.000
[Guest]: there was the, the Europeans were coming

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:44.000
[Guest]: to India at the same time, and they wrote extensively

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:46.000
[Guest]: about the Mughals, because they were fascinated

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:48.000
[Guest]: by this culture. So we

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
[Guest]: have all this writing about the Mughals and the

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.000
[Guest]: harem, and they were fascinated by the

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:54.000
[Guest]: harem because they had no access to it.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:56.000
[Guest]: And yet they could sense that the women in the

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:58.000
[Guest]: harem had power, they had money,

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:00.000
[Guest]: and they had influence. So it fascinated

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:02.000
[Guest]: them and horrified them in equal measure,

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:04.000
[Guest]: because at the same time in Europe,

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:06.000
[Guest]: Victorian Europe, and before that,

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:08.000
[Guest]: women had no power, they were not allowed

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.000
[Guest]: to control their own money. They were meant

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:12.000
[Guest]: to be rather, you know, quiet and

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:14.000
[Guest]: hold their opinions to themselves.

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:16.000
[Guest]: So this was something very contrary to what the

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:18.000
[Guest]: men had experienced in their own country. So they

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:20.000
[Guest]: came here with this mixture of abhorrence

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:22.000
[Guest]: and excitement. And they created

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:24.000
[Guest]: this fantasy world of the harem.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:26.000
[Guest]: And it is a fantasy because

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:28.000
[Guest]: they had no access to this harem.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.000
[Guest]: Nor were they physically allowed

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:32.000
[Guest]: to enter that space, nor could they speak

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.000
[Guest]: the language. So there were many layers of

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:36.000
[Guest]: obstruction between them and these Mughal women,

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:38.000
[Guest]: but that did not stop them from fantasizing,

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:40.000
[Guest]: from listening to bazaar gossip,

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:42.000
[Guest]: from gleaning bits and pieces of information,

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.000
[Guest]: and bringing out these

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:46.000
[Guest]: novels and novellas of exotic

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:48.000
[Guest]: life, which became

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:50.000
[Guest]: extremely popular back home

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:52.000
[Guest]: in Europe, and which in a way

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:54.000
[Guest]: then percolated down to us

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:56.000
[Guest]: till today, where we sort of have in the

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:58.000
[Guest]: back of our mind this idea that

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.000
[Guest]: women in a Mughal harem, all they did

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:02.000
[Guest]: was one woman was there in the middle of

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:04.000
[Guest]: the room waiting for the Pacha all day,

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:06.000
[Guest]: she's trying to attract his attention,

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:08.000
[Guest]: she's gossiping and bitching about her other co-wives,

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.000
[Guest]: and her whole life is

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:12.000
[Guest]: spent in this decadence of

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:14.000
[Guest]: beautifying herself and waiting

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:16.000
[Guest]: for the sexual favors of

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:18.000
[Guest]: the Pacha. And this

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:20.000
[Guest]: is an entirely false view,

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.000
[Guest]: which we can see from Rubi Lal's work

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.000
[Guest]: and from the other readings that I've done around it.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:26.000
[Guest]: And the Mughal harem, as I've

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.000
[Guest]: written in my book, was a place of

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:30.000
[Guest]: in fact, it was a place of great solidarity

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:32.000
[Guest]: amongst women. Most of the

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:34.000
[Guest]: women in a harem were not sexually available

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:36.000
[Guest]: to the Pacha at all. It was

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:38.000
[Guest]: a huge space, with

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:40.000
[Guest]: people like the Pacha's sisters,

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:42.000
[Guest]: his unmarried cousins, his aunts,

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:44.000
[Guest]: his grandmothers, his

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:46.000
[Guest]: foster mothers, milk mothers, his milk sisters,

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:48.000
[Guest]: there were so many people, there were

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:50.000
[Guest]: visitors, and then there was all the

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:52.000
[Guest]: retinue around these individual women.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:54.000
[Guest]: His wives brought their retinues with them, so

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:56.000
[Guest]: when they came in from a different place, they brought their own

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:58.000
[Guest]: cooks, they brought their masseuses, they brought their

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
[Guest]: priests, they brought so many other women,

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.000
[Guest]: none of whom were sexually available

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:04.000
[Guest]: to the Pacha. So this idea

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:06.000
[Guest]: of all these women being sexually available

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.000
[Guest]: is something completely false.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:10.000
[Guest]: And on the other hand, these women had

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:12.000
[Guest]: productive, interesting lives,

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:14.000
[Guest]: they earned a salary,

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:16.000
[Guest]: they had jobs, fixed jobs, for which they

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:18.000
[Guest]: had a salary. So they were

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:20.000
[Guest]: carrying out a function. And the

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.000
[Guest]: ones at the top, obviously, had

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.000
[Guest]: an enormous amount of money as

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:26.000
[Guest]: the Mughal empire grew richer,

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:28.000
[Guest]: the individual women grew richer as well.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:30.000
[Guest]: And it's very interesting because

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:32.000
[Guest]: if you look at the way the men write about

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:34.000
[Guest]: it, like the way I was telling you, the Jesuit

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:36.000
[Guest]: missionaries, for example, they had

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:38.000
[Guest]: only one idea, which was to proselytize

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:40.000
[Guest]: and to convert. So obviously for them

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:42.000
[Guest]: all these women were just in the

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:44.000
[Guest]: way of the Pacha and trying to lure him into

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:46.000
[Guest]: temptation, and they write about them like that.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:48.000
[Guest]: On the other hand, if you look at

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:50.000
[Guest]: the writings of women, there are some women who have written

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:52.000
[Guest]: about the harem, and they write about it

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:54.000
[Guest]: very differently. For example,

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:56.000
[Guest]: if you look at Lady Molly Montague,

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:58.000
[Guest]: she was the wife of the ambassador to

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:00.000
[Guest]: the Ottomans in Turkey

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:02.000
[Guest]: in the 18th century.

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:04.000
[Guest]: And she writes about them

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.000
[Guest]: and she says, you know, she had access to the

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:08.000
[Guest]: harem, obviously, as being a woman, and she

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.000
[Guest]: goes with them to their baths.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:12.000
[Guest]: And she writes about this incident in

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.000
[Guest]: which she is taken to the baths and the women want

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:16.000
[Guest]: to help her remove her clothes.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:18.000
[Guest]: So they remove her clothes and then

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:20.000
[Guest]: all those Turkish ladies step back in horror

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:22.000
[Guest]: and they gasp and they say, what are you

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:24.000
[Guest]: wearing? Because she was wearing stays.

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:26.000
[Guest]: You know, those are made out of whale bones and they were

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:28.000
[Guest]: made to keep women's waist very tiny

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:30.000
[Guest]: and narrow so that you could barely breathe.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:32.000
[Guest]: And they told her, you tell us that

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:34.000
[Guest]: our husbands are cruel with us, but look how

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:36.000
[Guest]: cruel your husband is with you and making you

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:38.000
[Guest]: wear these horrible clothes where you cannot even

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.000
[Guest]: move and breathe. So it's a very

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:42.000
[Guest]: interesting, you know, view we

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:44.000
[Guest]: have into this harem of how

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:46.000
[Guest]: the other women were viewing her and

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.000
[Guest]: how she was viewing those other women, you know.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:50.000
[Guest]: So she had come with her

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:52.000
[Guest]: preconception that these women are all debased and

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:54.000
[Guest]: they're degraded and she writes saying actually

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:56.000
[Guest]: no, they have this freedom, they don't

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:58.000
[Guest]: have to wear stays like I do.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:00.000
[Guest]: They have money. She says, who in England

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:02.000
[Guest]: controls, which woman controls her own

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:04.000
[Guest]: money? They don't. When they get married

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:06.000
[Guest]: they hand over their money to their husband. So she

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:08.000
[Guest]: was amazed that these women,

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:10.000
[Guest]: Muslim women, were able to control,

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:12.000
[Guest]: they were financially independent, which was a huge

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:14.000
[Guest]: thing. She writes about this to her friends.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:16.000
[Guest]: So there are these many ways

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.000
[Guest]: where the voices of the women

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:20.000
[Guest]: writing about the harem completely

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:22.000
[Guest]: contradicts the voices of the men.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:24.000
[Guest]: And so when you put the two together

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:26.000
[Guest]: you get a very different picture

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:28.000
[Guest]: of the harem and how it really was.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:30.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, reading about the harems, it just kind

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:32.000
[Amit Varma]: of struck me that, my God,

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:34.000
[Amit Varma]: not only is it not the simplistic

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:36.000
[Amit Varma]: notion of a harem that I had in my head,

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:38.000
[Amit Varma]: but the term that

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:40.000
[Amit Varma]: struck me was political economy. It's so deeply

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:42.000
[Amit Varma]: complex, you know, they have

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:44.000
[Amit Varma]: money, they have power, they have

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:46.000
[Amit Varma]: webs of influence and

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:48.000
[Amit Varma]: it's a question that I

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:50.000
[Amit Varma]: often ask the historians on my show

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:52.000
[Amit Varma]: and I'll ask a more

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:54.000
[Amit Varma]: elongated version of it to you.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:56.000
[Amit Varma]: The question I ask is that

00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:58.000
[Amit Varma]: given that we tend to suffer

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:00.000
[Unknown]: from the hindsight bias, because

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:02.000
[Amit Varma]: everything that has happened seems inevitable.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Number one, how do we

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:06.000
[Amit Varma]: remove our knowledge of what has already

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:08.000
[Amit Varma]: happened to look at a specific event

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:10.000
[Amit Varma]: at a current time in a fresh way?

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And the question is even more

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:14.000
[Amit Varma]: complicated for someone like you who's writing about

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:16.000
[Amit Varma]: this period, being that

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:18.000
[Amit Varma]: one also has all those

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:20.000
[Amit Varma]: prior impressions and biases

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:22.000
[Amit Varma]: that have come from firstly the European

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:24.000
[Amit Varma]: gaze which you spoke about

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:26.000
[Amit Varma]: and also even the male local

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:28.000
[Amit Varma]: gaze, like you've mentioned that Abu Fazal

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:30.000
[Amit Varma]: for example, wrote very

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:32.000
[Amit Varma]: very differently about the same

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:34.000
[Unknown]: emperor and the same happenings and someone like

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:36.000
[Unknown]: Gulbadan did, who is bringing

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:38.000
[Amit Varma]: in all those nuances and the rounded picture.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:40.000
[Amit Varma]: So mentally, did you have to

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:42.000
[Amit Varma]: take that step back and recast

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:44.000
[Guest]: everything and look, how do you do that?

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:46.000
[Guest]: Yes, that's an interesting point

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:48.000
[Guest]: and

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:50.000
[Guest]: I think the only way

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.000
[Guest]: to do that is

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:54.000
[Guest]: like you said for Abu al-Fazal

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:56.000
[Guest]: Abu al-Fazal in a way

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:58.000
[Guest]: does as much harm to the

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:00.000
[Guest]: women as the Europeans do

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:02.000
[Guest]: because even though his idea and

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:04.000
[Guest]: his motivation was very different. He wanted

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:06.000
[Guest]: to create in Akbar the semi-divine

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:08.000
[Guest]: king, you know, who was above

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:10.000
[Guest]: all reproach and so his women

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:12.000
[Guest]: had to be also above all reproach

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:14.000
[Guest]: and therefore they had to be completely chased

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:16.000
[Guest]: and to be completely chased you had to

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:18.000
[Guest]: be completely hidden. So he hides them

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:20.000
[Guest]: away in this elaborate

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:22.000
[Guest]: framework and he says they are all, he gives

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:24.000
[Guest]: them titles and they are all chased, whether they are

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:26.000
[Guest]: newborn babies or whether they are

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:28.000
[Guest]: old ladies, everybody is the same, they

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:30.000
[Guest]: are all chased, you know, and they have

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:32.000
[Guest]: no individuality, they are completely hidden. So

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:34.000
[Guest]: in a way he does as much disservice

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:36.000
[Guest]: to us today trying

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:38.000
[Guest]: to find out about women as the European

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:40.000
[Guest]: men did. But luckily

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:42.000
[Guest]: as always happens in history

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:44.000
[Guest]: you know, you cannot control things no matter

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:46.000
[Guest]: how hard or how much money you have at your disposal

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:48.000
[Guest]: and luckily for us there is somebody like Badawni

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:50.000
[Guest]: who wrote an illicit biography

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:52.000
[Guest]: of Akbar who was very critical, who

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:54.000
[Guest]: was an extremely erudite and learned

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:56.000
[Guest]: man himself but he was just critical of

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:58.000
[Guest]: Akbar's religious policies, that's

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:00.000
[Guest]: the only thing he held against Akbar and

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:02.000
[Guest]: so he wrote this illicit biography of

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:04.000
[Guest]: Akbar and through his words

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:06.000
[Guest]: inadvertently we find out

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:08.000
[Guest]: so much about the women because he blames

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:10.000
[Guest]: the Hindu wives of Akbar

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:12.000
[Guest]: for all these terrible changes that

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:14.000
[Guest]: he is seeing in his beloved Muslim Padshah

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:16.000
[Guest]: and he says, you know, Akbar is like this

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:18.000
[Guest]: today, he is worshipping the sun,

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:20.000
[Guest]: he is wearing a tilak, he is wearing a rakhi

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:22.000
[Guest]: these terrible customs, he has

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:24.000
[Guest]: brought dogs into the place, you know

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:26.000
[Guest]: he is horrified and he clearly says

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:28.000
[Guest]: it is because from his early

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:30.000
[Guest]: age he has been in the company

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:32.000
[Guest]: of lousy Hindus, Brahmins

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:34.000
[Guest]: and Hindu women, his wives.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:36.000
[Guest]: So we have here in black and white

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:38.000
[Guest]: and writing, we see the influence

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:40.000
[Guest]: of people like Harkabai, the Rajput

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:42.000
[Guest]: woman that Akbar married, so

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:44.000
[Guest]: it is very interesting for me because

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:46.000
[Guest]: I am setting out to find this connection

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:48.000
[Guest]: now perhaps if somebody had not set out

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:50.000
[Guest]: to look for this, you would just slip over it

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:52.000
[Guest]: and you would be like, okay, there is nothing on the women

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:54.000
[Guest]: but because I am always looking

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:56.000
[Guest]: out for any reference which

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:58.000
[Guest]: ties in the women to influence, which

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:00.000
[Guest]: ties in the women to the way the men

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:02.000
[Guest]: thought and what the men did, so

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:04.000
[Guest]: that is how I am able to pick out these things

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:06.000
[Guest]: I think because I am looking at it

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:08.000
[Guest]: in a way from my own filter.

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:10.000
[Guest]: So then I have Badawni, then I have Gulbadan

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:12.000
[Guest]: luckily, as you know I was telling you

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:14.000
[Guest]: earlier, we could so easily have

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:16.000
[Guest]: lost Gulbadan's voice because Akbar

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:18.000
[Guest]: when he was, when the empire was

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:20.000
[Guest]: finally settled and he said okay now

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:22.000
[Guest]: I must create a history for myself

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:24.000
[Guest]: because that was how Mughal emperors

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:26.000
[Guest]: you know sort of created legitimacy

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:28.000
[Guest]: for themselves. He asked Abul Fazal

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:30.000
[Guest]: to write a biography but wonderfully

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:32.000
[Guest]: for us he also asked the people who

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:34.000
[Guest]: had first hand knowledge of Humayun

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:36.000
[Guest]: and Babur to write about their memories

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:38.000
[Guest]: so he asked Johar, the

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:40.000
[Guest]: water carrier for Humayun

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:42.000
[Guest]: he asked other people and he asked his aunt

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:44.000
[Guest]: for whom he had a great deal of respect

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:46.000
[Amit Varma]: and Gulbadan wrote her wonderful biography

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:48.000
[Amit Varma]: and she is of course Babur's daughter, Humayun's sister

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:50.000
[Amit Varma]: that's right, Humayun's sister

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:52.000
[Guest]: she has experience, she came to India

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:54.000
[Guest]: at the age of six with Babur

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:56.000
[Guest]: then Babur died, she was with

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:58.000
[Guest]: Humayun through all his travails

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:00.000
[Guest]: you know when he was thrown out of India

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:02.000
[Guest]: by Sikandar Lodi, she was with him

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:04.000
[Guest]: in Kabul for all those years, she was

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:06.000
[Guest]: with him back when he came to India, she was

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:08.000
[Guest]: here when he finally died, she was in

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:10.000
[Guest]: India when Akbar became Padshah and then

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:12.000
[Guest]: for the rest of her very long life

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:14.000
[Guest]: she saw Akbar become a king

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:16.000
[Guest]: establish himself and establish the Mughal Empire

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:18.000
[Guest]: so an extraordinary woman who lived through

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:20.000
[Guest]: three different Padshahs

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:22.000
[Guest]: so we have her wonderful first hand account

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:24.000
[Guest]: of what all this

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:26.000
[Guest]: peripatetic journeying, what this

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:28.000
[Guest]: adventure, what this adventure

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.000
[Guest]: of forming the Mughal Empire

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:32.000
[Guest]: in India with these timid people

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:34.000
[Guest]: what it was like, we have through her eyes

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:36.000
[Guest]: and we could easily have lost that

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.000
[Guest]: because there was one copy of it

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.000
[Guest]: only one copy made, yes, 500

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:42.000
[Guest]: years ago and immediately

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:44.000
[Guest]: after she had written it, it was lost

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:46.000
[Guest]: nobody referred to it,

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:48.000
[Guest]: nobody else, no further biographer

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:50.000
[Guest]: later in time ever referred to this

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:52.000
[Guest]: book so it disappeared from even our

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:54.000
[Guest]: memory, then sometime in the 19th

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:56.000
[Guest]: century, an Englishman with the

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:58.000
[Guest]: East India Company was buying up

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:00.000
[Guest]: manuscripts like you do in the local kabaddi

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:02.000
[Guest]: bazaar, you go and you buy whatever old objects

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:04.000
[Guest]: you like, so he had a collection of a thousand

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:06.000
[Guest]: manuscripts, some worthless, some

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:08.000
[Guest]: interesting, when he died his widow

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:10.000
[Guest]: went back to England and she had all

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:12.000
[Guest]: these manuscripts, she needed to raise money, she was a

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:14.000
[Guest]: widow, she sold them to the British Library

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:16.000
[Guest]: the British Library early in

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:18.000
[Guest]: the 20th century had some of these

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:20.000
[Guest]: translated into English by Beveridge

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:22.000
[Guest]: and she discovered that one

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:24.000
[Guest]: of these manuscripts was actually the

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:26.000
[Guest]: biography of Barber's daughter

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:28.000
[Guest]: herself, Gulbadan's biography, so that's

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:30.000
[Guest]: how 500 years later it came

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:32.000
[Guest]: back into India, into our public

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:34.000
[Guest]: consciousness and we realized that we have

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:36.000
[Guest]: this first hand account, but

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:38.000
[Guest]: so you see, it takes a little bit of putting

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:40.000
[Guest]: all these stories together

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:42.000
[Guest]: to get an idea of what I want to talk about

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:44.000
[Amit Varma]: which is what the women were up to

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:46.000
[Amit Varma]: And while there's sheer luck, it also strikes me that there must be

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:48.000
[Guest]: so much else that is lost

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:50.000
[Guest]: Exactly, I think, and this is only half

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:52.000
[Guest]: of the book, Gulbadan's biography

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:54.000
[Guest]: was broken into two, torn into two pieces

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:56.000
[Guest]: and we only have the first section

00:37:56.000 --> 00:37:58.000
[Guest]: so I'm always thinking, wow, who knows

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:00.000
[Guest]: in which Kabadi Bazaar, there may be the second section

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:02.000
[Guest]: somewhere lying around, the second half

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:04.000
[Guest]: of Humayun's life and that's still

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:06.000
[Guest]: undiscovered, maybe it's there somewhere, who knows

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:08.000
[Amit Varma]: Maybe one of the listeners of this show

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:10.000
[Guest]: will go to the nearest Kabadi Bazaar and find it

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:12.000
[Amit Varma]: I hope so! Make an attempt

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:14.000
[Amit Varma]: please tag us if you do find it

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:18.000
[Amit Varma]: look now at the start

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.000
[Amit Varma]: of your book, Daughters of the Sun, and the start

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:22.000
[Amit Varma]: of the Mughal dynasty

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:24.000
[Amit Varma]: itself, though of course as you point out that

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:26.000
[Amit Varma]: Babur would have been very upset

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:28.000
[Unknown]: that it was called the Mughal dynasty

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Yes

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Because obviously it's a hug back to the Mongol

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:36.000
[Amit Varma]: part of his legacy and he was more proud

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:38.000
[Unknown]: of the Timurid side of it

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And you'd spoken earlier about, you know

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:42.000
[Amit Varma]: peripatetic early Mughals

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:44.000
[Amit Varma]: but what really struck me was that it's not

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:46.000
[Amit Varma]: just the men

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:48.000
[Amit Varma]: who are peripatetic, wherever they go

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:50.000
[Amit Varma]: you know this Haraman

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:52.000
[Unknown]: is that the correct pronunciation? Yes, yes

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:54.000
[Unknown]: Wherever they go, this Haraman is travelling with them

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:56.000
[Amit Varma]: which is this retinue of women

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:58.000
[Amit Varma]: and these are not retinue of necessarily

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:00.000
[Guest]: wives or mistresses or whatever

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:02.000
[Guest]: these are aunts, grandmothers

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:04.000
[Amit Varma]: these are serious people who are making

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:06.000
[Amit Varma]: serious decisions

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:08.000
[Amit Varma]: and one of the really interesting characters

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:10.000
[Amit Varma]: his father of course died when he was 13

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:12.000
[Amit Varma]: I think, right? That's right

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:14.000
[Amit Varma]: And you point out about how a lot of his

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:16.000
[Amit Varma]: guidance in terms of politics

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:18.000
[Amit Varma]: strategy and all that came from his grandmother

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:20.000
[Amit Varma]: Ehsan Daulat Begum

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:22.000
[Amit Varma]: and she also has a very interesting story

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:24.000
[Guest]: from her youth which reveals a lot of character

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:26.000
[Guest]: Yes, there's just one episode

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:28.000
[Guest]: that describes her

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:30.000
[Guest]: Babur is very scathing when he writes

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:32.000
[Guest]: about his own father, you know, he writes about how

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:34.000
[Guest]: he drank too much and he was overweight because of

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:36.000
[Guest]: that, you know, so he writes with a pretty

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:38.000
[Guest]: jaundiced view about his father

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:40.000
[Guest]: but never about the women in his life

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:42.000
[Guest]: he writes only with respect and love about the women

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:44.000
[Guest]: in his life, whether it is his mother, his

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:46.000
[Guest]: grandmother, his elder sister Khanzada

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:48.000
[Guest]: these three women who were extremely

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:50.000
[Guest]: influential in his life and he writes about

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:52.000
[Guest]: Ehsan Daulat Begum that at one

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:54.000
[Guest]: point when she was a much younger woman

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:56.000
[Guest]: she was travelling with her husband and at

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:58.000
[Guest]: some point in some conflict

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:00.000
[Guest]: she was captured by a chieftain

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:02.000
[Guest]: and the chieftain was very happy and he

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:04.000
[Guest]: said, I'm going to offer you to one of my

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:06.000
[Guest]: amirs and that is

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:08.000
[Guest]: your fate and so she is like, okay, she

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:10.000
[Guest]: pretends to be very happy with the decision and she

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:12.000
[Guest]: says, fine, no problem and she gets ready to

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:14.000
[Guest]: receive this amir at night

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:16.000
[Guest]: but actually what happens is that when the

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:18.000
[Guest]: amir enters her quarters, she has posted

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:20.000
[Guest]: her women around the door and

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:22.000
[Guest]: they pounce upon him, they catch him and they throw him

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:24.000
[Guest]: out of the window and he breaks his neck and he dies

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:26.000
[Guest]: and so the next morning the chieftain

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:28.000
[Guest]: comes to her and says, what have you done, how dare you, you know

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:30.000
[Guest]: and she says, I am already

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:32.000
[Guest]: married and I have a husband and if this is

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:34.000
[Guest]: the way you treat honourable women then do with me

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:36.000
[Guest]: as you will and the man is so

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:38.000
[Guest]: impressed that obviously he sends her

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:40.000
[Guest]: back to her husband with honour

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:42.000
[Guest]: and these are the sort of

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:44.000
[Guest]: you know, brave

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:46.000
[Guest]: resolute women that Babur

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:48.000
[Guest]: luckily has around him

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:50.000
[Guest]: to show them the way when he is only a 13

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:52.000
[Guest]: year old boy really, you know

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:54.000
[Guest]: trying to find his way in the world, surrounded

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:56.000
[Guest]: by his bloodthirsty uncles who would

00:40:56.000 --> 00:40:58.000
[Guest]: kill him in an instant for the throne themselves

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:00.000
[Guest]: and it is because he has his mother and his

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:02.000
[Guest]: grandmother and Khanzada Begum around him

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:04.000
[Guest]: that he survives at all, you know, never mind

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:06.000
[Guest]: becomes the founder of the Mughal Empire

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:08.000
[Guest]: and he writes about this and he writes

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:10.000
[Guest]: eloquently about Khanzada

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:12.000
[Guest]: Begum, how much he owes to her because

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:14.000
[Guest]: when he is surrounded by Shabani Khan

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:16.000
[Guest]: Uzbek, who is his great foe

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:18.000
[Guest]: in Samarkand

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:20.000
[Guest]: Shabani Khan makes an offer

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:22.000
[Guest]: to Babur and he says

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:24.000
[Guest]: I will let you go, you can go with your

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:26.000
[Guest]: life and your small retinue but you leave

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:28.000
[Guest]: your sister with me and you know, leave her

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:30.000
[Guest]: as my captive and Babur is

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:32.000
[Guest]: forced to do that and it is a shameful thing

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:34.000
[Guest]: for him to do because it shows that he has

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:36.000
[Guest]: no power and he has to leave

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:38.000
[Guest]: Khanzada Begum but Khanzada Begum

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:40.000
[Guest]: herself is never blamed or any

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:42.000
[Guest]: way demeaned for having to become the

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:44.000
[Guest]: wife of an enemy. She lives there

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:46.000
[Guest]: for 10 years after Shabani Khan

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:48.000
[Guest]: Uzbek eventually divorces her because he gets

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:50.000
[Guest]: fed up of how much she keeps talking about her own

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:52.000
[Guest]: family which I find really

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:54.000
[Guest]: evocative and amazing which means even

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:56.000
[Guest]: in confinement, even as a prisoner

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:58.000
[Guest]: of the lord's enemy

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:00.000
[Guest]: she must have kept on

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:02.000
[Guest]: talking about Babur and the Timurids, you know

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:04.000
[Guest]: so he gets fed up of her and he

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:06.000
[Guest]: gives her to a more lowly person as that

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:08.000
[Guest]: person's wife. So you can imagine

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:10.000
[Guest]: how it must have been very

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:12.000
[Guest]: humiliating for Khanzada Begum but she never

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:14.000
[Guest]: loses her spirit and after 10 years

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:16.000
[Guest]: when Shabani Khan Uzbek is defeated

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:18.000
[Guest]: she is sent back to Babur

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:20.000
[Guest]: and Babur is delighted to have

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:22.000
[Guest]: her back and he makes her Patsha Begum

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:24.000
[Guest]: which is the most respected

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:26.000
[Guest]: woman of the harem

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:28.000
[Guest]: and all his descendants

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:30.000
[Guest]: equally respect her and

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:32.000
[Guest]: she is never in any way

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:34.000
[Guest]: maimed or made to feel guilty

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:36.000
[Guest]: for the fact that she was the wife of two other

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:38.000
[Guest]: men before she came to Babur's

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:40.000
[Guest]: court which I found so refreshing

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:42.000
[Guest]: when we think about her exact contemporaries

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:44.000
[Guest]: the Rajputs, you know who put

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:46.000
[Guest]: so much worth on a woman's sexual

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:48.000
[Guest]: chastity that they would prefer

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:50.000
[Guest]: them to commit sati and johar

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:52.000
[Guest]: at the time of facing an enemy

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:54.000
[Guest]: rather than you know to

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:56.000
[Guest]: take a chance on what might happen to their life

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:58.000
[Guest]: so their sexual chastity is placed above

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:00.000
[Guest]: everything else, above them being

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:02.000
[Guest]: brothers, above them being human beings, above them being

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:04.000
[Guest]: wives, it is about being sexually chaste

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:06.000
[Guest]: so it is the control of a

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:08.000
[Guest]: woman's sexuality which is so important

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:10.000
[Guest]: whereas the Timurids are very

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:12.000
[Guest]: pragmatic about the fact that they are constantly

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:14.000
[Guest]: travelling, they are constantly warring

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:16.000
[Guest]: therefore their women are sometimes captured

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:18.000
[Guest]: it is not their fault, indeed when they

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:20.000
[Guest]: are brought back they are always honoured

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:22.000
[Guest]: so this was something that I thought people might not

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:24.000
[Guest]: know about and that it's worth talking about

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:26.000
[Amit Varma]: This took me by surprise and what also took me

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:28.000
[Amit Varma]: by surprise about Khanzada was that

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:30.000
[Guest]: she marries again and you contrast

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:32.000
[Amit Varma]: that with the stigma on widow remarriage

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:34.000
[Amit Varma]: in India where once you are widowed

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:36.000
[Amit Varma]: if you don't immolate yourself

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:38.000
[Guest]: you basically wear white and you are pretty much done

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:40.000
[Guest]: Correct, in fact

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:42.000
[Guest]: the Timurids regularly encouraged

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:44.000
[Guest]: remarriage and many of the women we find

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:46.000
[Guest]: were remarried and Anbar

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:48.000
[Guest]: even talks about it clearly

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:50.000
[Guest]: and says you know I don't understand

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:52.000
[Guest]: why amongst the Hindus a woman

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:54.000
[Guest]: when she is widowed

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:56.000
[Guest]: she is not allowed to go to another man

00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:58.000
[Guest]: he says I don't understand this

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:00.000
[Guest]: and I don't understand that a man

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:02.000
[Guest]: finds virtue in making

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:04.000
[Guest]: his wife die when he dies

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:06.000
[Guest]: so he was actually puzzled by this

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:08.000
[Guest]: he could not understand this whole concept

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:10.000
[Guest]: of sexual chastity and he

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:12.000
[Guest]: finally forbade it and he said

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:14.000
[Guest]: especially if the woman is young when she gets

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:16.000
[Guest]: widowed and if she has

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:18.000
[Guest]: perhaps not even lain

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:20.000
[Guest]: with her husband because he died so young

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:22.000
[Guest]: she is absolutely not to

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:24.000
[Guest]: commit sati and in any case

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:26.000
[Guest]: she is never to be forced so you know

00:44:26.000 --> 00:44:28.000
[Guest]: he sent ministers out

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:30.000
[Guest]: into his empire to make sure that no woman

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:32.000
[Guest]: now how much that happened on the ground

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:34.000
[Guest]: I don't know but they were to check

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:36.000
[Guest]: every case of sati and make sure

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:38.000
[Guest]: that if the woman was determined only

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:40.000
[Guest]: then would she be allowed to commit sati

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:42.000
[Guest]: and no one was to force her so he was

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:44.000
[Guest]: very puzzled so clearly this was

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:46.000
[Guest]: a deeply entrenched aspect

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:48.000
[Guest]: of the Timurids or the Mughals

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:50.000
[Guest]: that there was no shame

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:52.000
[Guest]: in remarrying if you

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:54.000
[Guest]: are widowed it was not your fault unlike

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:56.000
[Guest]: the Hindus who thought it is your fate if you are

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:58.000
[Guest]: widowed that means it is something you have

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:00.000
[Guest]: perhaps some crime or punishment for

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:02.000
[Guest]: some past life misdeed and therefore

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:04.000
[Guest]: you lose your husband and you

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:06.000
[Guest]: must die. They felt they didn't

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:08.000
[Guest]: see things in the same way at all so a woman's

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:10.000
[Guest]: chastity was not valued

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:12.000
[Guest]: above everything else about above

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:14.000
[Guest]: her abilities above her

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:16.000
[Guest]: capacity to form a new relationship

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:18.000
[Guest]: so I found that very interesting

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:20.000
[Guest]: right from the time of Khandzada so that means

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:22.000
[Guest]: 500 years ago you know from the time

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:24.000
[Guest]: of Babur itself there was no

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:26.000
[Guest]: undue importance laid on a woman's

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:28.000
[Guest]: honor being related to her chastity

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:30.000
[Amit Varma]: no and you know we often sort

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:32.000
[Amit Varma]: of in our popular conception

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:34.000
[Amit Varma]: of those times today we think

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:36.000
[Amit Varma]: of them as invading barbarians

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:38.000
[Amit Varma]: who came into our very evolved

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:40.000
[Amit Varma]: culture and all of that and

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:42.000
[Amit Varma]: sort of spoilt it

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:44.000
[Amit Varma]: but here it strikes to me and even

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:46.000
[Amit Varma]: you know lot of what else is in your book

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:48.000
[Amit Varma]: also points out that they were actually fairly enlightened

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:50.000
[Guest]: in many ways towards their women

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:52.000
[Guest]: not as much as we would like today

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:54.000
[Guest]: of course but no but even

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:56.000
[Guest]: so for those times I find

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:58.000
[Guest]: that it was quite

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:00.000
[Guest]: refreshingly honest the way they

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:02.000
[Guest]: viewed their women that we always think

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:04.000
[Guest]: of them in purdah there was a very light

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:06.000
[Guest]: very porous purdah in fact

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:08.000
[Guest]: you know we forget that they are descendants

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:10.000
[Guest]: of Timur and that is whom they claim

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:12.000
[Guest]: as their forefather and if we look

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:14.000
[Guest]: at Timur's court for example there is the

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:16.000
[Guest]: writings of the

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:18.000
[Guest]: Spanish ambassador I think Rui Gonzalez

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:20.000
[Guest]: who writes about his encounters at

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:22.000
[Guest]: the Timur court he goes there as an ambassador he is

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:24.000
[Guest]: received very well he attends all these parties

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:26.000
[Guest]: and he writes about Timur's

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:28.000
[Guest]: wife and he can

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:30.000
[Guest]: the fact that he writes about her physically

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:32.000
[Guest]: he describes her that means he can see her

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:34.000
[Guest]: and her veil is very very light

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:36.000
[Guest]: so she can be easily seen by all the men

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:38.000
[Guest]: who are sitting there he describes

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:40.000
[Guest]: her complexion her hair everything so she is

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:42.000
[Guest]: clearly visible she comes and sits

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:44.000
[Guest]: between them there are men with her

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:46.000
[Guest]: there are women with her it is a mixed gathering

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:48.000
[Guest]: and she drinks and her friends the women

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:50.000
[Guest]: all drink and in fact he writes that they drink

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:52.000
[Guest]: sometimes a little too much so you see

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:54.000
[Guest]: this is a very different idea

00:46:54.000 --> 00:46:56.000
[Guest]: of what we think a harem

00:46:56.000 --> 00:46:58.000
[Guest]: may have been like here is a mixed company

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:00.000
[Guest]: they are singing and dancing he says for days

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:02.000
[Guest]: so this is something very different

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:04.000
[Guest]: the Timurs of course

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:06.000
[Guest]: they were conquerors also

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:08.000
[Guest]: and I am not going to gloss over that but they

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:10.000
[Guest]: were also great builders of city

00:47:10.000 --> 00:47:12.000
[Guest]: they were great admirers of

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:14.000
[Guest]: culture of poetry of

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:16.000
[Guest]: language of literature Babur wrote his own biography

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:18.000
[Guest]: as you know a very entertaining biography

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:20.000
[Guest]: so there are these other aspects

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:22.000
[Guest]: they were not at all just

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:24.000
[Guest]: this marauding entity that

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:26.000
[Guest]: we have been made to believe

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:28.000
[Guest]: that they were they brought with them

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:30.000
[Guest]: a lot of other influences which remain

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:32.000
[Guest]: with us too which is very much part of our

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:34.000
[Guest]: DNA I think it is in the molecule of

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:36.000
[Guest]: every at least North Indian today

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:38.000
[Guest]: whether it is the food the clothes the language

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:40.000
[Guest]: the etiquette the adab that we have

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:42.000
[Guest]: it is all Timurid and it has

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:44.000
[Guest]: filtered down through us because these were

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:46.000
[Guest]: things that were valued in that time

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:48.000
[Guest]: when they came here they brought this all the

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:50.000
[Guest]: minor courts as they integrated

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:52.000
[Guest]: wanted to absorb this culture and they did

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:54.000
[Guest]: whether it was the Rajasthani courts

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:56.000
[Guest]: Jaisalmer, Amir all these courts

00:47:56.000 --> 00:47:58.000
[Guest]: they took part of this culture and they

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:00.000
[Guest]: made it uniquely Indian

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:02.000
[Guest]: in that genius way that we have

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:04.000
[Guest]: but the root of it is

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:06.000
[Guest]: Timurid and it survived because it

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:08.000
[Guest]: was buoyant and it was vibrant

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:10.000
[Guest]: and it was something worth

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:12.000
[Amit Varma]: keeping. And what

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:14.000
[Amit Varma]: also kind of struck me you know while

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:16.000
[Amit Varma]: reading about Babur's adventures like

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:18.000
[Amit Varma]: you know after he lost Samarkand he was

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:20.000
[Amit Varma]: sort of travelling for a long time

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:22.000
[Amit Varma]: and then he finally goes to Kabul

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:24.000
[Amit Varma]: and he stays in Kabul for 20 years and then

00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:26.000
[Amit Varma]: he you know goes to Hindustan

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:28.000
[Amit Varma]: where for the first time he really a lot of the

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:30.000
[Amit Varma]: women just stay behind and it kind of

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:32.000
[Amit Varma]: struck me that in all of this constant travel

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:34.000
[Amit Varma]: the sense of rootedness that he

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.000
[Unknown]: gets is from these women

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:38.000
[Amit Varma]: who you know

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:40.000
[Amit Varma]: and they are not just wives and mistresses

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:42.000
[Amit Varma]: they are aunts and his mother

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:44.000
[Amit Varma]: was his mother part of it?

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:46.000
[Guest]: Yes yes of course

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:48.000
[Amit Varma]: Hamida Banu Vega

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:50.000
[Amit Varma]: At one point you said that is where the sense of home

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:52.000
[Amit Varma]: comes from for these constant travellers

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:54.000
[Amit Varma]: and then he goes to Agra

00:48:54.000 --> 00:48:56.000
[Amit Varma]: and you know

00:48:56.000 --> 00:48:58.000
[Amit Varma]: when he finally wins his battle against Lodhi

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:00.000
[Amit Varma]: and he is sacking Agra and he

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:02.000
[Amit Varma]: sends so many jewels and riches

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:04.000
[Amit Varma]: and all of that which you have described in detail

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:06.000
[Amit Varma]: specifically for the women back to

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:08.000
[Amit Varma]: Kabul and one of the sort of threads

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:10.000
[Amit Varma]: running through the stories

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:12.000
[Amit Varma]: of Babur Humayun and all the way to Akbar

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:14.000
[Amit Varma]: is the love and reverence they have

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:16.000
[Guest]: for these women

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:18.000
[Guest]: Yes and in fact this list that you are talking

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:20.000
[Guest]: about of jewels and clothes

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:22.000
[Guest]: and dancing girls and all this that he

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:24.000
[Guest]: sends back is only listed

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:26.000
[Guest]: by Gulbadan no other biographer writes

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:28.000
[Guest]: about this so this again

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:30.000
[Guest]: if we didn't have a woman's voice we would

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:32.000
[Guest]: not see this aspect of their culture

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:34.000
[Guest]: of how they showed appreciation

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:36.000
[Guest]: of how wealth was distributed

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:38.000
[Guest]: so she writes in great detail about who was given

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:40.000
[Guest]: what so yes they

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:42.000
[Guest]: revere these women these women are

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:44.000
[Guest]: very important to them because they are

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:46.000
[Guest]: carriers of their culture

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:48.000
[Guest]: they are carriers of their language

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:50.000
[Guest]: of the stories they tell each other

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:52.000
[Guest]: of the stories they will tell the children so that the

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:54.000
[Guest]: children know where they come from who these

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:56.000
[Guest]: Timurids are you know so

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:58.000
[Guest]: they are very very essential

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:00.000
[Guest]: to the creation of a Timurid

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:02.000
[Guest]: legacy in India and one of the

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:04.000
[Guest]: very first thing where the Babur after Panipat

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:06.000
[Guest]: he says my generals

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:08.000
[Guest]: even though these are battle hardened

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:10.000
[Guest]: great men who are used to all

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:12.000
[Guest]: kinds of tribulations in the

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:14.000
[Guest]: heat of Hindustan they were like ok we have

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:16.000
[Guest]: won this battle for you now we are heading back to

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:18.000
[Guest]: Kabul so he realizes what's happening

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:20.000
[Guest]: and he calls for the women because he knows that

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:22.000
[Guest]: it is the women which will anchor the men

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:24.000
[Guest]: to a country it is not even riches

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:26.000
[Guest]: it is not even the

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:28.000
[Guest]: idea of future grandeur

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:30.000
[Guest]: it is the women because they bring with them a way

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:32.000
[Guest]: of life and it is this way of

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:34.000
[Guest]: life that can only be transmitted

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:36.000
[Guest]: the men are too busy doing their

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:38.000
[Guest]: battles and their you know interactions

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:40.000
[Guest]: with the

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:42.000
[Guest]: aggrandizing their territories it is the

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:44.000
[Guest]: women who bring their culture Akbar

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:46.000
[Guest]: does the same thing when he becomes king

00:50:46.000 --> 00:50:48.000
[Guest]: so young and he starts

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:50.000
[Guest]: to found his empire one of the

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:52.000
[Guest]: first thing because at that point

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:54.000
[Guest]: Humayun died so early that he hadn't yet called

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:56.000
[Guest]: for his harem to come

00:50:56.000 --> 00:50:58.000
[Guest]: from Kabul so one of the first thing

00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:00.000
[Guest]: after he wins a few battles Akbar

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:02.000
[Guest]: similarly almost identically to Babur

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:04.000
[Guest]: realizes that his men will not stay

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:06.000
[Guest]: carry on like this because

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:08.000
[Guest]: you know they are feeling a little bit

00:51:08.000 --> 00:51:10.000
[Guest]: orphaned in India now

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:12.000
[Guest]: you know and they are attacked by all

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:14.000
[Guest]: kinds of people who are trying to make their own

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:16.000
[Guest]: claims for the throne and they are ready

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:18.000
[Guest]: to leave and he does the same thing he calls

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:20.000
[Guest]: for the women and he writes and he

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:22.000
[Guest]: says these women are required

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:24.000
[Guest]: to have the men stay and for the men

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:26.000
[Guest]: to feel that this is a place that they

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:28.000
[Guest]: can call home that this is a place that one

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:30.000
[Guest]: day can be theirs and can be

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:32.000
[Guest]: you know part of their life so it's

00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:34.000
[Guest]: very interesting and right till the later

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:36.000
[Guest]: stages the women are some of the last

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:38.000
[Guest]: to speak the Turkish language and

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:40.000
[Guest]: you know obviously your language is so

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:42.000
[Guest]: much part of your identity so

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:44.000
[Guest]: Gulbadan and Hamida Banu

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:46.000
[Guest]: all these women who spoke Turkish

00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:48.000
[Guest]: as they die out we slowly

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:50.000
[Guest]: see that Turkish you know completely

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:52.000
[Guest]: loses its hold over these over

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:54.000
[Guest]: the men over the Pasha and they say

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:56.000
[Guest]: Jahangir I think says proudly

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:58.000
[Guest]: I can speak a few lines of Turkish

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:00.000
[Guest]: but clearly by then it is only

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:02.000
[Guest]: you know a sort of a flourish but it

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:04.000
[Guest]: is not their mother tongue anymore

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:06.000
[Guest]: it is the women who carry language

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:08.000
[Guest]: and who carry that sort of

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:10.000
[Guest]: the culture of memories and

00:52:10.000 --> 00:52:12.000
[Amit Varma]: of stories. Yeah I mean home is

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:14.000
[Amit Varma]: where the women are and it also kind

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:16.000
[Amit Varma]: of strikes me while reading this book that you know looking

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:18.000
[Amit Varma]: back we know what happened again

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:20.000
[Amit Varma]: hindsight so you can you know we

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:22.000
[Unknown]: look as the Mughals okay they've been here for so many

00:52:22.000 --> 00:52:24.000
[Amit Varma]: hundred years and blah blah blah but if you think

00:52:24.000 --> 00:52:26.000
[Amit Varma]: about them at the time they've just

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:28.000
[Amit Varma]: landed up in this strange land they don't

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:30.000
[Amit Varma]: speak that language they have no roots

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:32.000
[Amit Varma]: there everyone is a foreigner

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:34.000
[Amit Varma]: and therefore suspicious and we

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:36.000
[Amit Varma]: think of the Mughal dynasty as a given and

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:38.000
[Amit Varma]: it's such a strong solid monolithic

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:40.000
[Amit Varma]: thing but after Humayun loses

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:42.000
[Amit Varma]: to Sher Shah Suri and he's just being

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:44.000
[Amit Varma]: chased all over the place you

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:46.000
[Amit Varma]: have absolutely I mean at that

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:48.000
[Amit Varma]: moment he has absolutely no idea how

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:50.000
[Guest]: he's going to end up. No not at all and in fact

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:52.000
[Guest]: at that time it seems like you know

00:52:52.000 --> 00:52:54.000
[Guest]: the Mughals are only perhaps

00:52:54.000 --> 00:52:56.000
[Guest]: you know an aberration of

00:52:56.000 --> 00:52:58.000
[Guest]: a few years a few decades maybe you know with

00:52:58.000 --> 00:53:00.000
[Guest]: Babur and that is all they will ever be

00:53:00.000 --> 00:53:02.000
[Guest]: because the Sher Shah Suri

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:04.000
[Guest]: is a very talented man and it looks like

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:06.000
[Guest]: you know he will prosper

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:08.000
[Guest]: but

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:10.000
[Guest]: so it is true

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:12.000
[Guest]: that these

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:14.000
[Guest]: women I think without their presence

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:16.000
[Guest]: one almost feels

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:18.000
[Guest]: that perhaps the men would have also

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:20.000
[Guest]: lost hope at some point you know

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:22.000
[Guest]: and maybe not found it worth

00:53:22.000 --> 00:53:24.000
[Guest]: their while because so many of their

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:26.000
[Guest]: generals were ready to leave at many

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:28.000
[Guest]: times you know of the empire

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:30.000
[Guest]: and it is only after Akbar really

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:32.000
[Guest]: that Akbar

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:34.000
[Guest]: begins to feel like a truly Hindustani

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:36.000
[Guest]: king you know his he spends

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:38.000
[Guest]: so much time with the locals from a very

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:40.000
[Guest]: young age he is always he has

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:42.000
[Guest]: this great ability to communicate with people

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:44.000
[Guest]: of all classes and he spends a

00:53:44.000 --> 00:53:46.000
[Guest]: lot of time with all his animal keepers

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:48.000
[Guest]: and he learns the language very quickly

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:50.000
[Guest]: and it is with Akbar that we really feel that

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:52.000
[Guest]: these kings are here to stay and they are Hindustani

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:54.000
[Guest]: kings now you know and that they have

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:56.000
[Guest]: brought in this culture but Akbar often

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:58.000
[Guest]: puts on this timid culture

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:00.000
[Guest]: for show to impress an ambassador

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:02.000
[Guest]: or to impress some other

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:04.000
[Guest]: visiting timid but it is not who

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:06.000
[Guest]: he is he feels comfortable in

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:08.000
[Guest]: the culture of the country and you know

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:10.000
[Guest]: in the people that surround him

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:12.000
[Amit Varma]: who are now Hindustani. The most

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:14.000
[Amit Varma]: fascinating character in your book I found was

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:16.000
[Unknown]: Gulbadan herself and you write

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:18.000
[Amit Varma]: about how you know she saw Babur writing

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:20.000
[Amit Varma]: the Baburnama and then perhaps

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:22.000
[Amit Varma]: that's how she got inspired to write it

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:24.000
[Amit Varma]: and it strikes me that

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:26.000
[Amit Varma]: it is only through Gulbadan in fact

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:28.000
[Amit Varma]: you're right I'll quote you it is

00:54:28.000 --> 00:54:30.000
[Amit Varma]: through Gulbadan's account and only

00:54:30.000 --> 00:54:32.000
[Amit Varma]: hers that we can see Babur as a loving

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:34.000
[Amit Varma]: father a tempestuous family man

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:36.000
[Amit Varma]: and a devoted husband stop

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:38.000
[Amit Varma]: quote and how different is

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:40.000
[Amit Varma]: her portrayal of those times from other

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:42.000
[Amit Varma]: you know contemporary accounts that you read

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:44.000
[Guest]: well it's completely

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:46.000
[Guest]: different you know because especially when men are

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:48.000
[Guest]: writing about somebody

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:50.000
[Guest]: like Babur then they will focus on his battles

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:52.000
[Guest]: on his charisma certainly

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:54.000
[Guest]: you know his magnetic ability

00:54:54.000 --> 00:54:56.000
[Guest]: to

00:54:56.000 --> 00:54:58.000
[Guest]: interact with other men because he had this

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:00.000
[Guest]: majlis of men that he was very comfortable with

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:02.000
[Guest]: so those men wrote about those gatherings

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:04.000
[Guest]: of men you know where they drank all night

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:06.000
[Guest]: and you know sang songs and

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:08.000
[Guest]: tried out different mixtures of

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:10.000
[Guest]: drugs and so on

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:12.000
[Guest]: so we have Babur the

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:14.000
[Guest]: amazing strategist because he was a

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:16.000
[Guest]: wonderful strategist and you know how many

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:18.000
[Guest]: battles he won the battle of Panipat

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:20.000
[Guest]: how it was he won

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:22.000
[Guest]: it amazingly against all odds

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:24.000
[Guest]: so we see only that side of it

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:26.000
[Guest]: which is wonderful but it is one side

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:28.000
[Guest]: of it with Gulbadan we see

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:30.000
[Guest]: how much he loves his family

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:32.000
[Guest]: how he prefers one wife over

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:34.000
[Guest]: another his first wife his main wife

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:36.000
[Guest]: he calls her by her name

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:38.000
[Guest]: which I find very moving because by the time of Akbar

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:40.000
[Guest]: you can no longer

00:55:40.000 --> 00:55:42.000
[Guest]: pronounce a woman's name

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:44.000
[Guest]: and so therefore a certain part of their

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:46.000
[Guest]: identity is lost a name is so important

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:48.000
[Guest]: isn't it the way in which you are called

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:50.000
[Guest]: if you are only called by a title that somehow

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:52.000
[Guest]: it is meant to aggrandize you but on a

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:54.000
[Guest]: human level it reduces you because you

00:55:54.000 --> 00:55:56.000
[Guest]: no longer have your own separate identity

00:55:56.000 --> 00:55:58.000
[Guest]: but Babur calls her Maham Begum

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:00.000
[Guest]: so he always calls her by her name

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:02.000
[Guest]: and Gulbadan writes that oh he calls out to Maham

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:04.000
[Guest]: and when she is coming from Kabul

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:06.000
[Guest]: after an absence of I think

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:08.000
[Guest]: a year and a half he pushes aside

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:10.000
[Guest]: his attendant he pushes aside his horse and goes

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:12.000
[Guest]: running you know so this image of

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:14.000
[Guest]: this amazing conqueror but he is running

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:16.000
[Guest]: to meet his wife whom he hasn't met for one and a half

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:18.000
[Guest]: years and he takes Gulbadan in his

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:20.000
[Guest]: arms also you know six year old daughter

00:56:20.000 --> 00:56:22.000
[Guest]: whom he hasn't seen and he makes her eat

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:24.000
[Guest]: does this wonderful feast which is prepared

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:26.000
[Guest]: so yes it is through Gulbadan that

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:28.000
[Guest]: we see a different aspect

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:30.000
[Guest]: of this man you know so that he is not just

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:32.000
[Guest]: one dimensional we see him more as a

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:34.000
[Guest]: complete human being so the accounts

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:36.000
[Guest]: of women in no way

00:56:36.000 --> 00:56:38.000
[Guest]: do they denigrate a man

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:40.000
[Guest]: on the contrary you know they give a more

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:42.000
[Guest]: complex and nuanced understanding of the men

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:44.000
[Guest]: too so to understand women's

00:56:44.000 --> 00:56:46.000
[Guest]: history to talk about them to explore them

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:48.000
[Guest]: is also to increase our understanding

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:50.000
[Guest]: of the men too it's not that it's in

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:52.000
[Guest]: any way making them less manly

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:54.000
[Amit Varma]: another of the interesting aspects of and

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:56.000
[Amit Varma]: this again goes back to the whole political economy

00:56:56.000 --> 00:56:58.000
[Amit Varma]: angle of these harems so to say

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:00.000
[Amit Varma]: is how all of these women

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:02.000
[Amit Varma]: especially the senior women like

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Khanzada and Dildar Begum

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:06.000
[Amit Varma]: are you know playing this part

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:08.000
[Amit Varma]: in almost

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:10.000
[Amit Varma]: ruffling feathers you know bringing

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:12.000
[Amit Varma]: sons together making peace

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:14.000
[Amit Varma]: between brothers you know Khanzada goes on

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:16.000
[Amit Varma]: a number of missions and in fact dies on one

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:18.000
[Guest]: of those so called diplomatic missions to bring

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:20.000
[Guest]: brothers together that's right

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:22.000
[Guest]: tell me a little bit about that so in fact

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:24.000
[Guest]: one of the missions that she sent

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:26.000
[Guest]: on Humayun had to

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:28.000
[Guest]: fight with all of his brothers at one point

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:30.000
[Guest]: of or another three of his brothers

00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:32.000
[Guest]: and the most resolute

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:34.000
[Guest]: of his brothers against him was Kamran

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:36.000
[Guest]: who never came round to him the other two did

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:38.000
[Guest]: so Kamran never came round to his side

00:57:38.000 --> 00:57:40.000
[Guest]: and things were pretty hairy for him

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:42.000
[Guest]: at some times you know because he was being

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:44.000
[Guest]: chased by the Afghans by the Lodis

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:46.000
[Guest]: by the local chieftains the Rajput

00:57:46.000 --> 00:57:48.000
[Guest]: chieftains and he can't even count on his own

00:57:48.000 --> 00:57:50.000
[Guest]: brothers you know so in desperation

00:57:50.000 --> 00:57:52.000
[Guest]: at one point you would think okay who is he

00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:54.000
[Guest]: going to send to parlay with Kamran

00:57:54.000 --> 00:57:56.000
[Guest]: maybe it is some you know

00:57:56.000 --> 00:57:58.000
[Guest]: grizzled warrior maybe some you know

00:57:58.000 --> 00:58:00.000
[Guest]: old man who holds a lot of respect

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:02.000
[Guest]: no he sends this elderly lady

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:04.000
[Guest]: Khansada Begum who is you know

00:58:04.000 --> 00:58:06.000
[Guest]: who doesn't have independent status

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:08.000
[Guest]: of her own it's not that she has a

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:10.000
[Guest]: famous husband or famous son you know as

00:58:10.000 --> 00:58:12.000
[Guest]: you know she was twice widowed and then married to

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:14.000
[Guest]: somebody not terribly

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:16.000
[Guest]: consequential but she

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:18.000
[Guest]: has this standing of her own

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:20.000
[Guest]: because they respect her so much you know because

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:22.000
[Guest]: she is a timid who is clearly

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:24.000
[Guest]: very intelligent they all look up to

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:26.000
[Guest]: her she is sensible and she is

00:58:26.000 --> 00:58:28.000
[Guest]: this woman who is sent on a very dangerous

00:58:28.000 --> 00:58:30.000
[Guest]: mission across icy passes

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:32.000
[Guest]: and mountains and you know she could have died

00:58:32.000 --> 00:58:34.000
[Guest]: at any moment and she goes to Kamran

00:58:34.000 --> 00:58:36.000
[Guest]: and she tells him do what Babur

00:58:36.000 --> 00:58:38.000
[Guest]: would have wanted you to do so

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:40.000
[Guest]: she stands in lieu of Babur

00:58:40.000 --> 00:58:42.000
[Guest]: the founder himself and says remember

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:44.000
[Guest]: what Babur would have wanted you to do

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:46.000
[Guest]: that Humayun is like your Patshah now he is

00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:48.000
[Guest]: like your elder brother he is like your king you must

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:50.000
[Guest]: obey him now

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:52.000
[Guest]: the fact that Kamran doesn't really do that is

00:58:52.000 --> 00:58:54.000
[Guest]: neither here nor there because he was intent

00:58:54.000 --> 00:58:56.000
[Guest]: on getting the throne for himself

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:58.000
[Guest]: but he listens to her with respect you know

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:00.000
[Guest]: and then he keeps her with him and says

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:02.000
[Guest]: you stay with me because you are

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:04.000
[Guest]: symbolically very important but the

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:06.000
[Guest]: fact that she is sent on these missions shows

00:59:06.000 --> 00:59:08.000
[Guest]: that when all else fails when there is nothing

00:59:08.000 --> 00:59:10.000
[Guest]: left they still believe in the

00:59:10.000 --> 00:59:12.000
[Guest]: power of somebody like Khanzada

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:14.000
[Guest]: on the power that she has through her charisma

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:16.000
[Guest]: of being a timid woman

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:18.000
[Guest]: you know independent of any man really

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:20.000
[Guest]: and I find that really just

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:22.000
[Amit Varma]: startling and amazing

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:24.000
[Guest]: just a moral authority she carries

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:26.000
[Amit Varma]: that's right

00:59:26.000 --> 00:59:28.000
[Amit Varma]: does it strike you sometimes when you are studying history or writing history

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:30.000
[Amit Varma]: how important and

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:32.000
[Amit Varma]: consequential happenstance can become

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:34.000
[Amit Varma]: like not just for example the happenstance of

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:36.000
[Amit Varma]: that we happen to find the only

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:38.000
[Amit Varma]: biography of Gulbadan but

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:40.000
[Amit Varma]: even happenstance in history for example

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:42.000
[Amit Varma]: you write about

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:44.000
[Amit Varma]: how Humayun falls in love with this young

00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:46.000
[Amit Varma]: girl called Hamida Banu Begum

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:48.000
[Amit Varma]: and she is really not interested

00:59:48.000 --> 00:59:50.000
[Amit Varma]: and one of his foster mothers

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:52.000
[Amit Varma]: Dildar Begum is then playing its part

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:54.000
[Amit Varma]: trying to get her to convince and saying

00:59:54.000 --> 00:59:56.000
[Amit Varma]: what better than you know marrying a

00:59:56.000 --> 00:59:58.000
[Amit Varma]: king and he is not really a king at the moment

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:00.000
[Unknown]: he is a fugitive he is kind of running around

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:02.000
[Unknown]: with this small retinue and she is like

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:04.000
[Unknown]: you know trying to politely turn

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:06.000
[Unknown]: it down and it's all very interesting but

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:08.000
[Amit Varma]: it actually happens

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:10.000
[Amit Varma]: and you know and from there

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:12.000
[Amit Varma]: even when they are sort of

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:14.000
[Amit Varma]: going back to the present day

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:16.000
[Unknown]: Afghanistan side and

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:18.000
[Amit Varma]: it's news that another of his brothers

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:20.000
[Amit Varma]: might kill him and Humayun and

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Hamida go off and they leave little baby

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:24.000
[Amit Varma]: Akbar with wet nurses

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:26.000
[Amit Varma]: and somehow he survives all of that and

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:28.000
[Amit Varma]: if these things don't happen we don't have Akbar

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:30.000
[Amit Varma]: we don't have I mean the

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:32.000
[Amit Varma]: history of the subcontinent is completely

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:34.000
[Guest]: different completely different of course

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:36.000
[Guest]: if you read again if you read Abu Al-Fazl

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:38.000
[Guest]: and the male biographers then you will be told

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:40.000
[Guest]: that this is all predetermined and this

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:42.000
[Guest]: was meant to be and it is because Akbar

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:44.000
[Guest]: is a semi-divine king and it is all

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:46.000
[Guest]: stars you know so they go back to astrology

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:48.000
[Guest]: and they say that

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:50.000
[Guest]: the stars were aligned in just such a manner

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:52.000
[Guest]: that this would happen but of course

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:54.000
[Guest]: we know that it is as you

01:00:54.000 --> 01:00:56.000
[Guest]: say happenstance and it is fortuitous

01:00:56.000 --> 01:00:58.000
[Guest]: incidents like this you know and

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:00.000
[Guest]: in fact the fact that Hamida Banu

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:02.000
[Guest]: went with Humayun for two years they were

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:04.000
[Guest]: in Persia and you know they were almost

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:06.000
[Guest]: like itinerant backpackers because

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:08.000
[Guest]: they had nothing much at all you know they

01:01:08.000 --> 01:01:10.000
[Guest]: had 40 total the retinue

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:12.000
[Guest]: when they went left India was 40

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:14.000
[Guest]: so that is not a very impressive cavalcade

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:16.000
[Guest]: you know when you are coming as the Badshah of

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:18.000
[Guest]: Hindustan and of course they are received

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:20.000
[Guest]: in Persia and

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:22.000
[Guest]: they are treated as kings

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:24.000
[Guest]: and queens but

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:26.000
[Guest]: the fact is that they spend most of those

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:28.000
[Guest]: two years just sightseeing

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:30.000
[Guest]: and they visit all these wonderful, Humayun is

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:32.000
[Guest]: an interesting character himself and

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:34.000
[Guest]: he visits all these interesting

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:36.000
[Guest]: you know sites and all this amazing

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:38.000
[Guest]: architecture, Persia is an amazing place

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:40.000
[Guest]: at that time

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:42.000
[Guest]: one of the you know cauldrons of

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:44.000
[Guest]: culture really in the world

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:46.000
[Guest]: and so they see all this amazing site

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:48.000
[Guest]: and Hamida Banu with him, they see carpets

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:50.000
[Guest]: they see architecture

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:52.000
[Guest]: they eat food which is amazing

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:54.000
[Guest]: also you know they talk about sharbat

01:01:54.000 --> 01:01:56.000
[Guest]: cooled with ice water and you know this amazing

01:01:56.000 --> 01:01:58.000
[Guest]: white linen and white bread which is made for

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:00.000
[Guest]: them and it is so evocative

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:02.000
[Guest]: and one wonders when they come back two years

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:04.000
[Guest]: later how much Hamida Banu

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:06.000
[Guest]: brings with her because she has seen all this

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:08.000
[Guest]: she has eaten all this, she has experienced all this

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:10.000
[Guest]: and when Gulbadan writes that

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:12.000
[Guest]: a new fashion of making tents

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:14.000
[Guest]: of arranging quarters

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:16.000
[Guest]: was introduced, then you think

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:18.000
[Guest]: okay maybe Hamida Banu Begum

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:20.000
[Guest]: introduced certain Persian

01:02:20.000 --> 01:02:22.000
[Guest]: ways into Hindustan

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:24.000
[Guest]: and that is the way through which

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:26.000
[Guest]: it came, it's not just Humayun

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:28.000
[Guest]: it's not just the Persian immigrants

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:30.000
[Guest]: who then followed, it is Hamida Banu herself

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:32.000
[Guest]: and in fact

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:34.000
[Guest]: one of the

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:36.000
[Guest]: questions I bring up is the whole

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:38.000
[Guest]: question of who built Humayun's tomb

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:42.000
[Guest]: for something which became such an important

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:44.000
[Guest]: mausoleum, the mausoleum of the

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:46.000
[Guest]: Mughals themselves, it was

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:48.000
[Guest]: very little written about in its own time

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:50.000
[Guest]: I think people were too busy establishing

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:52.000
[Guest]: the empire, Akbar was very young at that time

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:54.000
[Guest]: he was still fighting for the throne when Humayun

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:56.000
[Guest]: died and the

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:58.000
[Guest]: Humayun's tomb was only begun several years

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:00.000
[Guest]: after his death, much later

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:02.000
[Guest]: and Akbar then moved to Agra

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:04.000
[Guest]: and then Fatehpur Sikhi and that became

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:06.000
[Guest]: the focus of his attention, so

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:08.000
[Guest]: Humayun's tomb in Delhi was not much

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:10.000
[Guest]: written about, so there's quite a lot of

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:12.000
[Guest]: question mark about who built Humayun's

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:14.000
[Guest]: tomb, you know, and

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:16.000
[Guest]: contemporary writers say

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:18.000
[Guest]: that it was his widow, so his

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:20.000
[Guest]: widow being Bega Begum who's also another

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:22.000
[Guest]: very interesting woman

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:24.000
[Guest]: and I wonder if the very

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:26.000
[Guest]: shape of Humayun's tomb which shows so much

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:28.000
[Guest]: Persian influence, perhaps

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:30.000
[Guest]: some of it comes from the fact that Bega Begum

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:32.000
[Guest]: would have talked to Hamida Banu Begum

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:34.000
[Guest]: her wife who she was very friendly with, they had

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:36.000
[Guest]: a very good relationship according to

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:38.000
[Guest]: how Gulbuddin writes about it, they may

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:40.000
[Guest]: have compared notes, she may have talked about the

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:42.000
[Guest]: mausoleums that she visited in her two years

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:44.000
[Guest]: in Persia and some of them, of course this

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:46.000
[Guest]: is all far-fetched and this is again, you know

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:48.000
[Guest]: wondering, but it's a wondering

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:50.000
[Guest]: which is worth doing, that perhaps

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:52.000
[Guest]: they talked about it, she talked about these things

01:03:52.000 --> 01:03:54.000
[Guest]: and then along with the Persian architect, there was

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:56.000
[Guest]: a Persian architect, this wonderful

01:03:56.000 --> 01:03:58.000
[Guest]: tomb was built and Bega Begum

01:03:58.000 --> 01:04:00.000
[Guest]: then looked after it for the rest of her life

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:02.000
[Guest]: and yet certain people now

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:04.000
[Guest]: certain scholars will say that Akbar built it

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:06.000
[Guest]: I think what the question is

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:08.000
[Guest]: is who determines ownership

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:10.000
[Guest]: how do you determine ownership of a

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:12.000
[Guest]: thing, a monument? It may be

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:14.000
[Guest]: money, Akbar must have supplied most of the money

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:16.000
[Guest]: he was the emperor and he had a lot of money

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:18.000
[Guest]: certainly, but isn't it also

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:20.000
[Guest]: the person who has loved it

01:04:20.000 --> 01:04:22.000
[Guest]: who has loved it into being

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:24.000
[Guest]: who has brought in some of the ideas, who

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:26.000
[Guest]: spent the rest of her life looking after it

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:28.000
[Guest]: and who has devoted herself

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:30.000
[Guest]: to that tomb, so in my chapter

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:32.000
[Guest]: on that, I say, let us not

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:34.000
[Guest]: take away ownership, people in

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:36.000
[Guest]: that time said, Bega Begum built

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:38.000
[Guest]: Humayun's tomb, you see, so let us not

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:40.000
[Guest]: take it away so easily because

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:42.000
[Guest]: these examples are not lying thick on the ground

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:44.000
[Guest]: of women doing things, so we must hang on

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:46.000
[Guest]: to each instance that we have and fight

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:48.000
[Amit Varma]: for it. And it's very tempting for male historians

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:50.000
[Amit Varma]: to just imagine that if anything

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:52.000
[Amit Varma]: great exists, like a great monument

01:04:52.000 --> 01:04:54.000
[Unknown]: it's obviously a man

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:56.000
[Amit Varma]: and one of the concrete things

01:04:56.000 --> 01:04:58.000
[Amit Varma]: which did come

01:04:58.000 --> 01:05:00.000
[Amit Varma]: from Persia is of course

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:02.000
[Amit Varma]: the whole art of the Mughal miniature

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:04.000
[Amit Varma]: really originated there because

01:05:04.000 --> 01:05:06.000
[Amit Varma]: they got painters back from there

01:05:06.000 --> 01:05:08.000
[Amit Varma]: and they were completely enthralled

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:10.000
[Amit Varma]: by the work that happened there

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:12.000
[Amit Varma]: and that cultural influence came in

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:14.000
[Amit Varma]: from there. We'll take a quick commercial

