01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:23.000
[Amit Varma]: And I'm almost feeling embarrassed

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:25.000
[Amit Varma]: having to say the ladies and the lives of Babur

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:27.000
[Guest]: and Humayun, you know, making the same mistake

01:07:27.000 --> 01:07:29.000
[Guest]: that historians... Good, good.

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:31.000
[Guest]: Self-awareness is the beginning.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I guess.

01:07:33.000 --> 01:07:35.000
[Amit Varma]: Early on in your book, you say that

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:37.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, when you look at the women in this period,

01:07:37.000 --> 01:07:39.000
[Amit Varma]: it can sort of be divided

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:41.000
[Amit Varma]: into three phases. That with the

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:43.000
[Amit Varma]: early Mughals, you have the older

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:45.000
[Amit Varma]: matriarchs who are really powerful

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:47.000
[Amit Varma]: people like Khanzada and I guess Zildar

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:49.000
[Amit Varma]: and so on. And Akbar

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:51.000
[Amit Varma]: onwards, the focus shifts first

01:07:51.000 --> 01:07:53.000
[Amit Varma]: to foster mothers, I guess, in that

01:07:53.000 --> 01:07:55.000
[Amit Varma]: immediate period where he's settling down.

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And then to wives. Yes. And then

01:07:57.000 --> 01:07:59.000
[Amit Varma]: with the later Mughals, it shifts to

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:01.000
[Amit Varma]: like unmarried daughters. That's right.

01:08:01.000 --> 01:08:03.000
[Amit Varma]: And is it sort of just happenstance or are there

01:08:03.000 --> 01:08:05.000
[Amit Varma]: deeper reasons behind this kind of a

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:07.000
[Amit Varma]: shift and the kind of women

01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:09.000
[Guest]: who are becoming dominant? Well,

01:08:09.000 --> 01:08:11.000
[Guest]: I think initially the

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:13.000
[Guest]: matriarchs were important because

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:15.000
[Guest]: they were the ones carrying that culture.

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:17.000
[Guest]: So they were the ones who had the moral authority.

01:08:17.000 --> 01:08:19.000
[Guest]: They were the ones who had that clout. They were the

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:21.000
[Guest]: ones who had that influence, you know, and respect.

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:23.000
[Guest]: The younger women were not

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:25.000
[Guest]: at that point that needed,

01:08:25.000 --> 01:08:27.000
[Guest]: you know, you needed the older women who had that

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:29.000
[Guest]: authority with them, which the younger women

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:31.000
[Guest]: didn't have. And therefore, the

01:08:31.000 --> 01:08:33.000
[Guest]: Babur and Humayun were particularly

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:35.000
[Guest]: respectful of these older women.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:37.000
[Guest]: All the Mughals were right down the line,

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:39.000
[Guest]: but the ones who had that visibility,

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:41.000
[Guest]: let us say, are the older women.

01:08:41.000 --> 01:08:43.000
[Guest]: Because I think they, at a time of very

01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:45.000
[Guest]: great uncertainty, of vulnerability of the

01:08:45.000 --> 01:08:47.000
[Guest]: empire, they are the ones who brought

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:49.000
[Guest]: that sort of counterpart

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:51.000
[Guest]: and that weight and that culture

01:08:51.000 --> 01:08:53.000
[Guest]: with them. Then

01:08:53.000 --> 01:08:55.000
[Guest]: Akbar, in his early years,

01:08:55.000 --> 01:08:57.000
[Guest]: because as we know, he was abandoned as a

01:08:57.000 --> 01:08:59.000
[Guest]: baby, and I think probably that is one reason

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:01.000
[Guest]: for those few years before his parents

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:03.000
[Guest]: came back, but the entire time of 10 years

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:05.000
[Guest]: in Kabul, he was surrounded

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:07.000
[Guest]: by his foster families.

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:09.000
[Guest]: And I think that possibly shaped

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:11.000
[Guest]: him very deeply.

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:13.000
[Guest]: He may have somewhere

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:15.000
[Guest]: felt that whereas his parents had

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:17.000
[Guest]: abandoned him, his foster families

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:19.000
[Guest]: stood by him, protected him

01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:21.000
[Guest]: physically, from his uncle Kamran,

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:23.000
[Guest]: who was always a slightly volatile

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:25.000
[Guest]: character, from Askari,

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:27.000
[Guest]: and from all the dangers around

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:29.000
[Guest]: a child, a baby, you know.

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:31.000
[Guest]: So I have a feeling that these years shaped

01:09:31.000 --> 01:09:33.000
[Guest]: him so that he had this love,

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:35.000
[Guest]: this affection, and

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:37.000
[Guest]: this gratitude to his foster families

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:39.000
[Guest]: throughout his life, so that his

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:41.000
[Guest]: foster brothers could get

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:43.000
[Guest]: away almost with murder and he forgave

01:09:43.000 --> 01:09:45.000
[Guest]: them, like Aziz Koka could say all kinds

01:09:45.000 --> 01:09:47.000
[Guest]: of cheeky and disrespectful things to him in the

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:49.000
[Guest]: open court, and Akbar would

01:09:49.000 --> 01:09:51.000
[Guest]: mostly laugh it off or shrug it off, you know,

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:53.000
[Amit Varma]: make light of it. In fact, he very memorably

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:55.000
[Guest]: said that there is a river of milk between

01:09:55.000 --> 01:09:57.000
[Amit Varma]: us. That is right. He so poetically said that.

01:09:57.000 --> 01:09:59.000
[Guest]: Such a beautiful phrase. Such a beautiful phrase, exactly right.

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:01.000
[Guest]: And so, you know,

01:10:01.000 --> 01:10:03.000
[Guest]: he was very, very grateful

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:05.000
[Guest]: I think to his foster families and his foster

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:07.000
[Guest]: mothers, therefore. And the

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:09.000
[Guest]: one who

01:10:09.000 --> 01:10:11.000
[Guest]: was most ambitious, let us say,

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:13.000
[Guest]: was Mahamanga. There were

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:15.000
[Guest]: others that he loved perhaps more, like Jiji

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:17.000
[Guest]: Anga, Aziz Koka's mother,

01:10:17.000 --> 01:10:19.000
[Guest]: but she was not ambitious in that sense.

01:10:19.000 --> 01:10:21.000
[Guest]: She was always there with Akbar, but

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:23.000
[Guest]: I don't find any records of her

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:25.000
[Guest]: doing anything of her own

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:27.000
[Guest]: in terms of architecture or commissioning

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:29.000
[Guest]: anything, but Mahamanga was.

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:31.000
[Guest]: She was an ambitious woman, she was a talented woman,

01:10:31.000 --> 01:10:33.000
[Guest]: so was her son, but he was again very volatile,

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:35.000
[Guest]: Adham Khan. And

01:10:35.000 --> 01:10:37.000
[Guest]: Mahamanga, so therefore at the

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:39.000
[Guest]: time of the early years of

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:41.000
[Guest]: Akbar, when he hasn't yet come into his

01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:43.000
[Guest]: own, when he is in the force of nature that

01:10:43.000 --> 01:10:45.000
[Guest]: we later know him to be, Mahamanga

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:47.000
[Guest]: is very, very powerful and

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:49.000
[Guest]: it is written that she practically

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:51.000
[Guest]: ran the empire for those two years

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:53.000
[Guest]: until Adham Khan

01:10:53.000 --> 01:10:55.000
[Guest]: oversteps the boundaries and therefore

01:10:55.000 --> 01:10:57.000
[Guest]: Mahamanga also falls.

01:10:57.000 --> 01:10:59.000
[Guest]: So, we have that short period of time

01:10:59.000 --> 01:11:01.000
[Guest]: in which there are the foster mothers

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:03.000
[Guest]: and it is short, but it is not inconsequential

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:05.000
[Guest]: because she carries out many orders,

01:11:05.000 --> 01:11:07.000
[Guest]: she runs the empire and she builds

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:09.000
[Guest]: one of the first great mosques,

01:11:09.000 --> 01:11:11.000
[Guest]: Mughal mosques of Delhi, which is today

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:13.000
[Guest]: completely forgotten. It's the Kherul Manazil

01:11:13.000 --> 01:11:15.000
[Guest]: Madrasa and mosque complex

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:17.000
[Guest]: which is opposite Old Fort

01:11:17.000 --> 01:11:19.000
[Guest]: and today it is in ruins sadly,

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:21.000
[Guest]: but it is a wonderful testament of a

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:23.000
[Guest]: non-royal Mughal woman

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:25.000
[Guest]: and it is clearly written, there's a

01:11:25.000 --> 01:11:27.000
[Guest]: writing on it in Persian

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:29.000
[Guest]: saying that this has been commissioned by

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:31.000
[Guest]: Mahamanga. So, she's put her name to it.

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:33.000
[Guest]: You see her ambition, you see her desire

01:11:33.000 --> 01:11:35.000
[Guest]: for her name to continue

01:11:35.000 --> 01:11:37.000
[Guest]: in posterity. And so,

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:39.000
[Guest]: after these short years, once the

01:11:39.000 --> 01:11:41.000
[Guest]: matriarchs die out, they stay out

01:11:41.000 --> 01:11:43.000
[Guest]: for quite a long time, Hamida Banu and

01:11:43.000 --> 01:11:45.000
[Guest]: Gulbadan, Bega Begum dies

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:47.000
[Guest]: first, but there's Gulbadan and there's Hamida Banu,

01:11:47.000 --> 01:11:49.000
[Guest]: they continue. Because Hamida Banu

01:11:49.000 --> 01:11:51.000
[Guest]: was so young when she got

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:53.000
[Guest]: married and she had Akbar, she died

01:11:53.000 --> 01:11:55.000
[Guest]: only a couple of years before her son.

01:11:55.000 --> 01:11:57.000
[Guest]: So, almost his entire life, he

01:11:57.000 --> 01:11:59.000
[Guest]: had these matriarchs who remained very

01:11:59.000 --> 01:12:01.000
[Guest]: powerful and visible

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:03.000
[Guest]: despite Abu Al-Fazl's attempt

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:05.000
[Guest]: to make them invisible. So, Gulbadan

01:12:05.000 --> 01:12:07.000
[Guest]: goes on this wonderful all-women's hajj

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:09.000
[Guest]: which is a remarkable thing for a

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:11.000
[Guest]: 16th century Muslim woman to do. And

01:12:11.000 --> 01:12:13.000
[Guest]: she spends a full seven years

01:12:13.000 --> 01:12:15.000
[Guest]: before she comes back to Fatehpur Sikhi.

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:17.000
[Guest]: So, one imagines the kind of adventure that

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:19.000
[Guest]: she goes through and how much she must have

01:12:19.000 --> 01:12:21.000
[Guest]: enjoyed herself to have stayed away from

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:23.000
[Amit Varma]: this opulent court. And you described

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:25.000
[Amit Varma]: even when they came back, she didn't go directly

01:12:25.000 --> 01:12:27.000
[Amit Varma]: from the shore to the, you know, she's

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:29.000
[Guest]: going everywhere and really chilling with her.

01:12:29.000 --> 01:12:31.000
[Guest]: Exactly. You would think if she really wanted to get

01:12:31.000 --> 01:12:33.000
[Guest]: back, she'd rush back home. But she first goes

01:12:33.000 --> 01:12:35.000
[Guest]: to Ajmer to see the Dargah, you know, she does

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:37.000
[Guest]: all the other minor pilgrimages.

01:12:37.000 --> 01:12:39.000
[Guest]: So, she's clearly having the time of her

01:12:39.000 --> 01:12:41.000
[Guest]: life, you know. And what a pity that she

01:12:41.000 --> 01:12:43.000
[Guest]: hasn't written about that.

01:12:43.000 --> 01:12:45.000
[Guest]: So, yes. So, there are these

01:12:45.000 --> 01:12:47.000
[Guest]: matriarchs who remain influential

01:12:47.000 --> 01:12:49.000
[Guest]: almost till the end of Akbar's

01:12:49.000 --> 01:12:51.000
[Guest]: life. So, we don't hear

01:12:51.000 --> 01:12:53.000
[Guest]: a great deal about the other

01:12:53.000 --> 01:12:55.000
[Guest]: women at this time. It is only after he

01:12:55.000 --> 01:12:57.000
[Guest]: passes away that one hears more

01:12:57.000 --> 01:12:59.000
[Guest]: about the power of his mother,

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:01.000
[Guest]: Harkabai, the Rajput princess of

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:03.000
[Guest]: Ajmer, who is, of course, in popular

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:05.000
[Guest]: literature misrepresented as

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:07.000
[Guest]: Jodhabai in Jodha Akbar. That is completely

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:09.000
[Guest]: untrue. She was not from Jodhpur. She was

01:13:09.000 --> 01:13:11.000
[Guest]: from Ajmer, which became Jaipur later

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:13.000
[Guest]: on. So,

01:13:13.000 --> 01:13:15.000
[Guest]: it is only after Akbar passes away that

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:17.000
[Guest]: you see that Harkabai is a very

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:19.000
[Guest]: powerful, financially independent woman.

01:13:19.000 --> 01:13:21.000
[Guest]: She has her own trading ships. She's

01:13:21.000 --> 01:13:23.000
[Guest]: very interested in trade.

01:13:23.000 --> 01:13:25.000
[Guest]: In fact, it even brings her up against the Portuguese

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:27.000
[Guest]: who are a real menace and whom she loathes.

01:13:27.000 --> 01:13:29.000
[Guest]: And so did all the women. In fact, the

01:13:29.000 --> 01:13:31.000
[Guest]: harem was very anti the Jesuit

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:33.000
[Guest]: missionaries. They found them

01:13:33.000 --> 01:13:35.000
[Guest]: a nefarious and toxic influence

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:37.000
[Guest]: and they hated, obviously,

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:39.000
[Guest]: the things that they said against

01:13:39.000 --> 01:13:41.000
[Guest]: both the Muslims and the Hindus.

01:13:41.000 --> 01:13:43.000
[Guest]: In that way, they were quite democratic. They would criticize

01:13:43.000 --> 01:13:45.000
[Guest]: both the Hindus and the Muslims.

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:47.000
[Guest]: So, both Harkabai and her retinue of Rajput

01:13:47.000 --> 01:13:49.000
[Guest]: women hated them and so did the Muslim

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:51.000
[Guest]: ladies. They were like, who are these men

01:13:51.000 --> 01:13:53.000
[Guest]: telling us

01:13:53.000 --> 01:13:55.000
[Guest]: how to live our life?

01:13:55.000 --> 01:13:57.000
[Guest]: So, it is only after Akbar died that

01:13:57.000 --> 01:13:59.000
[Guest]: you see the power of Harkabai.

01:13:59.000 --> 01:14:01.000
[Guest]: So, she trades and she has

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:03.000
[Guest]: interactions with the Portuguese

01:14:03.000 --> 01:14:05.000
[Guest]: and she has even

01:14:05.000 --> 01:14:07.000
[Guest]: a proxy fight with them.

01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:09.000
[Guest]: But she's a powerful woman. We only

01:14:09.000 --> 01:14:11.000
[Guest]: see that later on, for that short period

01:14:11.000 --> 01:14:13.000
[Guest]: of time until she passes away.

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:15.000
[Guest]: And then the wives come into their own with

01:14:15.000 --> 01:14:17.000
[Guest]: Nur Jahan, of course, famously.

01:14:17.000 --> 01:14:19.000
[Guest]: And it is later, in the time of

01:14:19.000 --> 01:14:21.000
[Guest]: Shah Jahan and Aurangzeb, that the

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:23.000
[Guest]: daughters become more powerful.

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:25.000
[Guest]: And I think it's because the daughters

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:27.000
[Guest]: now are carrying that bloodline.

01:14:27.000 --> 01:14:29.000
[Guest]: They are the timid women because the wives are local

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:31.000
[Guest]: wives now. They are Hindustani wives, non-timid

01:14:31.000 --> 01:14:33.000
[Guest]: wives. So, they do not carry that

01:14:33.000 --> 01:14:35.000
[Guest]: charisma of the timid

01:14:35.000 --> 01:14:37.000
[Guest]: which is necessary to perpetuate this

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:39.000
[Guest]: legacy. So, it is the daughters who take on

01:14:39.000 --> 01:14:41.000
[Guest]: that role. Jahanara Begum is a timid

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:43.000
[Guest]: woman and she claims that legacy

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:45.000
[Guest]: very forcefully. And I found that is

01:14:45.000 --> 01:14:47.000
[Guest]: what attracted me to her.

01:14:47.000 --> 01:14:49.000
[Guest]: Just like the men did. In fact, almost

01:14:49.000 --> 01:14:51.000
[Guest]: more than the men did. She said, I am a timid

01:14:51.000 --> 01:14:53.000
[Guest]: woman. I will build these

01:14:53.000 --> 01:14:55.000
[Guest]: buildings. She built so many structures

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:57.000
[Guest]: in Old Delhi.

01:14:57.000 --> 01:14:59.000
[Guest]: She wrote biographies.

01:14:59.000 --> 01:15:01.000
[Guest]: She was a Sufi peer. She had

01:15:01.000 --> 01:15:03.000
[Guest]: a Sufi journey. She wrote about that in her

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:05.000
[Guest]: biography. And she does all this

01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:07.000
[Guest]: claiming that she is blessed

01:15:07.000 --> 01:15:09.000
[Guest]: and is perpetuating the timid lamp,

01:15:09.000 --> 01:15:11.000
[Guest]: the knowledge of the timid. So, that

01:15:11.000 --> 01:15:13.000
[Guest]: is very important. It is because of her bloodline

01:15:13.000 --> 01:15:15.000
[Guest]: that she is able to claim this

01:15:15.000 --> 01:15:17.000
[Guest]: sort of descendants and legacy.

01:15:17.000 --> 01:15:19.000
[Guest]: So, that is why the daughters then become

01:15:19.000 --> 01:15:21.000
[Guest]: important. As does Roshanara.

01:15:21.000 --> 01:15:23.000
[Guest]: But she is just...

01:15:23.000 --> 01:15:25.000
[Guest]: One of the Europeans, I forget, Bernier,

01:15:25.000 --> 01:15:27.000
[Guest]: somebody wrote acutely but cruelly

01:15:27.000 --> 01:15:29.000
[Guest]: that she is also very beautiful but

01:15:29.000 --> 01:15:31.000
[Guest]: less beautiful than Jahanara. She is also talented

01:15:31.000 --> 01:15:33.000
[Guest]: but less than Jahanara. So, she was always

01:15:33.000 --> 01:15:35.000
[Guest]: second best. But these

01:15:35.000 --> 01:15:37.000
[Guest]: women were powerful. They were incredibly

01:15:37.000 --> 01:15:39.000
[Guest]: wealthy. All the Europeans who wanted

01:15:39.000 --> 01:15:41.000
[Guest]: to trade at court had to

01:15:41.000 --> 01:15:43.000
[Guest]: parlay with them

01:15:43.000 --> 01:15:45.000
[Guest]: and had to interact with them and they

01:15:45.000 --> 01:15:47.000
[Guest]: ignored them at their own peril.

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:49.000
[Guest]: I think one of them, Thomas Rowe, first thought

01:15:49.000 --> 01:15:51.000
[Guest]: that he would do without Jahanara Begum

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:53.000
[Guest]: and it worked out

01:15:53.000 --> 01:15:55.000
[Guest]: very badly and he had to scramble later on

01:15:55.000 --> 01:15:57.000
[Guest]: to make up for that. So, these women,

01:15:57.000 --> 01:15:59.000
[Guest]: Noor Jahan, Jahanara and Roshanara

01:15:59.000 --> 01:16:01.000
[Guest]: were very influential later on.

01:16:01.000 --> 01:16:03.000
[Amit Varma]: One of the things that struck me about

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:05.000
[Amit Varma]: Akbar's times,

01:16:05.000 --> 01:16:07.000
[Amit Varma]: in fact, two of the fundamental shifts that happened

01:16:07.000 --> 01:16:09.000
[Amit Varma]: and one was sort of a cultural shift

01:16:09.000 --> 01:16:11.000
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that he was marrying a lot of

01:16:11.000 --> 01:16:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Rajput women in alliances

01:16:13.000 --> 01:16:15.000
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

01:16:15.000 --> 01:16:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And that had an influence. Like in just one

01:16:17.000 --> 01:16:19.000
[Amit Varma]: context, you write, quote,

01:16:19.000 --> 01:16:21.000
[Amit Varma]: In just a few years, this Rajasthani

01:16:21.000 --> 01:16:23.000
[Amit Varma]: style will irrevocably

01:16:23.000 --> 01:16:25.000
[Amit Varma]: influence Mughal court dress and etiquette.

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Tight jackets and tunics and diaphanous

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:29.000
[Amit Varma]: materials elaborately printed

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:31.000
[Amit Varma]: will replace the more pragmatic flowing

01:16:31.000 --> 01:16:33.000
[Amit Varma]: kabhas of the Mughal women.

01:16:33.000 --> 01:16:35.000
[Amit Varma]: But it's not just in dress.

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:37.000
[Amit Varma]: In every possible way,

01:16:37.000 --> 01:16:39.000
[Guest]: it had an influence on the court.

01:16:39.000 --> 01:16:41.000
[Guest]: It did. It had an influence

01:16:41.000 --> 01:16:43.000
[Guest]: which was, I think, both ways.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:45.000
[Guest]: More than we acknowledge.

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:47.000
[Guest]: The Rajputs

01:16:47.000 --> 01:16:49.000
[Guest]: obviously adopted a great deal

01:16:49.000 --> 01:16:51.000
[Guest]: from the Mughals, from their culture.

01:16:51.000 --> 01:16:53.000
[Guest]: The miniature paintings went to the minor courts

01:16:53.000 --> 01:16:55.000
[Guest]: of Rajasthan and they flourished

01:16:55.000 --> 01:16:57.000
[Guest]: when Akbar commissioned the

01:16:57.000 --> 01:16:59.000
[Guest]: Razam Namas, which was a translation of the Mahabharata.

01:16:59.000 --> 01:17:01.000
[Guest]: This extraordinary document which

01:17:01.000 --> 01:17:03.000
[Guest]: required Brahmin priests

01:17:03.000 --> 01:17:05.000
[Guest]: sitting together with Persian theologians

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:07.000
[Guest]: and writers and translators

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:09.000
[Guest]: and all this amazing intellectual work

01:17:09.000 --> 01:17:11.000
[Guest]: going on so that the Mahabharata, this

01:17:11.000 --> 01:17:13.000
[Guest]: amazing Sanskrit script was translated

01:17:13.000 --> 01:17:15.000
[Guest]: into Persian.

01:17:15.000 --> 01:17:17.000
[Guest]: When the Rajputs saw this, they also commissioned one.

01:17:17.000 --> 01:17:19.000
[Guest]: They said we will be no less and they commissioned one

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:21.000
[Guest]: which had twice the number of paintings that the Mughals had.

01:17:21.000 --> 01:17:23.000
[Guest]: So you see, they were very much influenced

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:25.000
[Guest]: as well and they took all these

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:27.000
[Guest]: elements back to their court, whether it was

01:17:27.000 --> 01:17:29.000
[Guest]: in architecture, the paintings

01:17:29.000 --> 01:17:31.000
[Guest]: and of course the Mughals were completely

01:17:31.000 --> 01:17:33.000
[Guest]: altered by the interaction with the Rajputs.

01:17:33.000 --> 01:17:35.000
[Guest]: Definitely in art,

01:17:35.000 --> 01:17:37.000
[Guest]: and you can see in Fatehpur Sikri

01:17:37.000 --> 01:17:39.000
[Guest]: this mixing of styles, Gujarati, Rajasthani,

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:41.000
[Guest]: you know, Timurid of course.

01:17:41.000 --> 01:17:43.000
[Guest]: It was very much because

01:17:43.000 --> 01:17:45.000
[Guest]: of Rajasthan, but the interesting thing

01:17:45.000 --> 01:17:47.000
[Guest]: that I have also

01:17:47.000 --> 01:17:49.000
[Guest]: talked about and I'm talking about more in my

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:51.000
[Guest]: next book is the way

01:17:51.000 --> 01:17:53.000
[Guest]: they were influenced in terms of the

01:17:53.000 --> 01:17:55.000
[Guest]: women's life and the purdah

01:17:55.000 --> 01:17:57.000
[Guest]: specifically. We normally tend to assume

01:17:57.000 --> 01:17:59.000
[Guest]: that the purdah came with the Mughals,

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:01.000
[Guest]: that they brought it with them from Central Asia

01:18:01.000 --> 01:18:03.000
[Guest]: into India and I'm wondering

01:18:03.000 --> 01:18:05.000
[Guest]: if it is not more a sort of

01:18:05.000 --> 01:18:07.000
[Guest]: a two-way thing

01:18:07.000 --> 01:18:09.000
[Guest]: that when they came in, they seemed to

01:18:09.000 --> 01:18:11.000
[Guest]: have, as I said, a very porous purdah

01:18:11.000 --> 01:18:13.000
[Guest]: indeed. Many of the women were visible, they had a very

01:18:13.000 --> 01:18:15.000
[Guest]: light purdah, they were on horseback, they travelled

01:18:15.000 --> 01:18:17.000
[Guest]: everywhere, they talked to the men openly,

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:19.000
[Guest]: you know, they interacted with them in mixed gatherings.

01:18:19.000 --> 01:18:21.000
[Guest]: But this purdah that happened

01:18:21.000 --> 01:18:23.000
[Guest]: happened more at Akbar's time

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:25.000
[Guest]: and we know that Rajasthani

01:18:25.000 --> 01:18:27.000
[Guest]: Rajput society at this time

01:18:27.000 --> 01:18:29.000
[Guest]: had a purdah system which

01:18:29.000 --> 01:18:31.000
[Guest]: was extremely intransigent

01:18:31.000 --> 01:18:33.000
[Guest]: and their women were very much cloistered

01:18:33.000 --> 01:18:35.000
[Guest]: in fact the higher up in the echelon

01:18:35.000 --> 01:18:37.000
[Guest]: they were, the higher were the walls

01:18:37.000 --> 01:18:39.000
[Guest]: physically of their, you know, of their zanana.

01:18:39.000 --> 01:18:41.000
[Guest]: So even light could not enter.

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:43.000
[Guest]: Their purdah

01:18:43.000 --> 01:18:45.000
[Guest]: was so restrictive that they were meant to cover

01:18:45.000 --> 01:18:47.000
[Guest]: their heads even in front of senior women.

01:18:47.000 --> 01:18:49.000
[Guest]: So their mothers-in-law, for many years a young

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:51.000
[Guest]: bride could not cover, uncover her face

01:18:51.000 --> 01:18:53.000
[Guest]: whereas the Mughals never had any such thing,

01:18:53.000 --> 01:18:55.000
[Guest]: they interacted freely with other women.

01:18:55.000 --> 01:18:57.000
[Guest]: So I am wondering whether

01:18:57.000 --> 01:18:59.000
[Guest]: this is not also something which the Rajputs

01:18:59.000 --> 01:19:01.000
[Guest]: brought with them which became

01:19:01.000 --> 01:19:03.000
[Guest]: something that Akbar then thought would be

01:19:03.000 --> 01:19:05.000
[Guest]: good to emulate because these are high caste

01:19:05.000 --> 01:19:07.000
[Guest]: Rajput men who are introducing this system

01:19:07.000 --> 01:19:09.000
[Guest]: therefore it is something that he

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:11.000
[Guest]: as a Mughal emperor should also bring

01:19:11.000 --> 01:19:13.000
[Guest]: into his harem, you know, as Patshah of India.

01:19:13.000 --> 01:19:15.000
[Guest]: And perhaps a two-way thing,

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:17.000
[Guest]: perhaps the Rajasthanis then saw

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:19.000
[Guest]: how the empire was

01:19:19.000 --> 01:19:21.000
[Guest]: forming, how the court was becoming more

01:19:21.000 --> 01:19:23.000
[Guest]: ossified and more stratified,

01:19:23.000 --> 01:19:25.000
[Guest]: how the harem was becoming tighter, the zanana

01:19:25.000 --> 01:19:27.000
[Guest]: was higher and they brought even more

01:19:27.000 --> 01:19:29.000
[Guest]: restriction to their women so that

01:19:29.000 --> 01:19:31.000
[Guest]: by the end of it both societies

01:19:31.000 --> 01:19:33.000
[Guest]: have their women tightly cloistered

01:19:33.000 --> 01:19:35.000
[Guest]: and invisible in a way.

01:19:35.000 --> 01:19:37.000
[Guest]: So yes, the interaction with

01:19:37.000 --> 01:19:39.000
[Guest]: Rajasthan, with the Rajput culture

01:19:39.000 --> 01:19:41.000
[Guest]: is something which I think has become

01:19:41.000 --> 01:19:43.000
[Guest]: so organic that it would be difficult

01:19:43.000 --> 01:19:45.000
[Guest]: to say where the Mughal starts and where the Rajput ends.

01:19:45.000 --> 01:19:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And what you also pointed out in your book,

01:19:47.000 --> 01:19:49.000
[Amit Varma]: the second big shift perhaps is that

01:19:49.000 --> 01:19:51.000
[Amit Varma]: now the zanana becomes something

01:19:51.000 --> 01:19:53.000
[Amit Varma]: sort of separate

01:19:53.000 --> 01:19:55.000
[Amit Varma]: where Akbar starts spending more and more time

01:19:55.000 --> 01:19:57.000
[Amit Varma]: with men whether they are, you know,

01:19:57.000 --> 01:19:59.000
[Unknown]: theologians or artists or whatever

01:19:59.000 --> 01:20:01.000
[Amit Varma]: and the zanana becomes a separate thing

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:03.000
[Amit Varma]: and it raises a management problem. Again, to quote

01:20:03.000 --> 01:20:05.000
[Amit Varma]: from your book, you write, quote

01:20:05.000 --> 01:20:07.000
[Amit Varma]: the very large number of women now in Akbar

01:20:07.000 --> 01:20:09.000
[Amit Varma]: zanana has brought up a very

01:20:09.000 --> 01:20:11.000
[Amit Varma]: vexatious question even for a great statesman

01:20:11.000 --> 01:20:13.000
[Amit Varma]: such as Akbar. This troublesome question

01:20:13.000 --> 01:20:15.000
[Amit Varma]: is though it is only through

01:20:15.000 --> 01:20:17.000
[Amit Varma]: order that the world becomes a meadow of

01:20:17.000 --> 01:20:19.000
[Amit Varma]: truth and reality, this order

01:20:19.000 --> 01:20:21.000
[Amit Varma]: yearningly aspired to by Abu al-Fazl

01:20:21.000 --> 01:20:23.000
[Amit Varma]: for Akbar is hard to maintain in the

01:20:23.000 --> 01:20:25.000
[Amit Varma]: raucous community of women, children,

01:20:25.000 --> 01:20:27.000
[Amit Varma]: staff, relatives, guards, tutors

01:20:27.000 --> 01:20:29.000
[Amit Varma]: and assorted entourage

01:20:29.000 --> 01:20:31.000
[Amit Varma]: that Akbar zanana has become.

01:20:31.000 --> 01:20:33.000
[Guest]: Stop quote.

01:20:33.000 --> 01:20:35.000
[Guest]: How does he handle this?

01:20:35.000 --> 01:20:37.000
[Guest]: Well, first we have to

01:20:37.000 --> 01:20:39.000
[Guest]: consider what Abu al-Fazl is saying.

01:20:39.000 --> 01:20:41.000
[Guest]: Abu al-Fazl states

01:20:41.000 --> 01:20:43.000
[Guest]: that Akbar has 5000 women

01:20:43.000 --> 01:20:45.000
[Guest]: in his zanana. Now anybody who has visited

01:20:45.000 --> 01:20:47.000
[Guest]: Fatehpur Sikri will know that this is a gross

01:20:47.000 --> 01:20:49.000
[Guest]: exaggeration. You would be

01:20:49.000 --> 01:20:51.000
[Guest]: absolutely like sardines in a can if there were

01:20:51.000 --> 01:20:53.000
[Guest]: 5000 women in what were

01:20:53.000 --> 01:20:55.000
[Guest]: pretty modest

01:20:55.000 --> 01:20:57.000
[Guest]: quarters if you're talking about

01:20:57.000 --> 01:20:59.000
[Guest]: a sum like 5000. He says

01:20:59.000 --> 01:21:01.000
[Guest]: 5000 to aggrandize Akbar.

01:21:01.000 --> 01:21:03.000
[Guest]: He says 5000 to show

01:21:03.000 --> 01:21:05.000
[Guest]: how mighty Akbar is, that he can

01:21:05.000 --> 01:21:07.000
[Guest]: provide for and protect 5000

01:21:07.000 --> 01:21:09.000
[Guest]: women, that he requires 5000 women

01:21:09.000 --> 01:21:11.000
[Guest]: around him in his zanana.

01:21:11.000 --> 01:21:13.000
[Guest]: So it is a gross exaggeration.

01:21:13.000 --> 01:21:15.000
[Guest]: The Europeans talk about

01:21:15.000 --> 01:21:17.000
[Guest]: 300 women. Even there we're not

01:21:17.000 --> 01:21:19.000
[Guest]: talking about 300 wives at all.

01:21:19.000 --> 01:21:21.000
[Guest]: So there's always this

01:21:21.000 --> 01:21:23.000
[Guest]: assumption that these 5000 women are

01:21:23.000 --> 01:21:25.000
[Guest]: sexually available to Akbar. They're his wives.

01:21:25.000 --> 01:21:27.000
[Guest]: This is complete nonsense.

01:21:27.000 --> 01:21:29.000
[Guest]: If you do the calculations, Akbar would

01:21:29.000 --> 01:21:31.000
[Guest]: have done nothing but spend time with his wives

01:21:31.000 --> 01:21:33.000
[Guest]: if he had 5000 women. How would he have

01:21:33.000 --> 01:21:35.000
[Guest]: founded this amazing empire?

01:21:35.000 --> 01:21:37.000
[Guest]: Firstly, one has to look at

01:21:37.000 --> 01:21:39.000
[Guest]: what Abu al-Fazl is saying.

01:21:39.000 --> 01:21:41.000
[Guest]: Even considering the fact that there were not

01:21:41.000 --> 01:21:43.000
[Guest]: 5000 women, there were a lot of women

01:21:43.000 --> 01:21:45.000
[Guest]: because now all these Rajasthani ladies

01:21:45.000 --> 01:21:47.000
[Guest]: brought their retinues

01:21:47.000 --> 01:21:49.000
[Guest]: with them. And this is one thing that the Rajputs

01:21:49.000 --> 01:21:51.000
[Guest]: did is that when they sent out their daughters,

01:21:51.000 --> 01:21:53.000
[Guest]: they didn't just send them alone to

01:21:53.000 --> 01:21:55.000
[Guest]: their in-laws. They sent them completely accompanied

01:21:55.000 --> 01:21:57.000
[Guest]: because they did not trust the food,

01:21:57.000 --> 01:21:59.000
[Guest]: what they would get in their in-law

01:21:59.000 --> 01:22:01.000
[Guest]: family. So they brought in all

01:22:01.000 --> 01:22:03.000
[Guest]: their infrastructure with them.

01:22:03.000 --> 01:22:05.000
[Guest]: Whether they were priests, whether they were

01:22:05.000 --> 01:22:07.000
[Guest]: masseuse, whether they were teachers, whether they were

01:22:07.000 --> 01:22:09.000
[Guest]: pandits, these were all women. Interesting to know

01:22:09.000 --> 01:22:11.000
[Guest]: the women were carrying on all these roles.

01:22:11.000 --> 01:22:13.000
[Guest]: So this structure that Abu al-Fazl

01:22:13.000 --> 01:22:15.000
[Guest]: tries to create as being

01:22:15.000 --> 01:22:17.000
[Guest]: extremely ordered must have been

01:22:17.000 --> 01:22:19.000
[Guest]: something which was quite rambunctious and out of

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:21.000
[Guest]: control in a way if he has to keep saying that it was

01:22:21.000 --> 01:22:23.000
[Guest]: a very chaste place and a very ordered place.

01:22:23.000 --> 01:22:25.000
[Guest]: But the fact is that it was managed.

01:22:25.000 --> 01:22:27.000
[Guest]: It was like a city in miniature.

01:22:27.000 --> 01:22:29.000
[Guest]: It was like a government in miniature. You had a daroga,

01:22:29.000 --> 01:22:31.000
[Guest]: you had somebody taking notes, somebody

01:22:31.000 --> 01:22:33.000
[Guest]: who took accounts, somebody who

01:22:33.000 --> 01:22:35.000
[Guest]: showed those accounts to the Patsha,

01:22:35.000 --> 01:22:37.000
[Guest]: who presented to the Patsha

01:22:37.000 --> 01:22:39.000
[Guest]: all the requirements of the women. The women

01:22:39.000 --> 01:22:41.000
[Guest]: would also make requests every day

01:22:41.000 --> 01:22:43.000
[Guest]: for charity for poor women

01:22:43.000 --> 01:22:45.000
[Guest]: they would support. Those requests

01:22:45.000 --> 01:22:47.000
[Guest]: were made before the emperor every afternoon.

01:22:47.000 --> 01:22:49.000
[Guest]: So there was this very complicated

01:22:49.000 --> 01:22:51.000
[Guest]: and intrinsic bureaucracy and

01:22:51.000 --> 01:22:53.000
[Guest]: life which was going on in the Zainana

01:22:53.000 --> 01:22:55.000
[Guest]: which was not at all

01:22:55.000 --> 01:22:57.000
[Guest]: the one that Abu al-Fazl was

01:22:57.000 --> 01:22:59.000
[Guest]: hoping to create. It was something

01:22:59.000 --> 01:23:01.000
[Guest]: that we have forgotten because of the sanitized way

01:23:01.000 --> 01:23:03.000
[Guest]: that he talks about it. But it was

01:23:03.000 --> 01:23:05.000
[Guest]: a very lively place. It was a place

01:23:05.000 --> 01:23:07.000
[Guest]: where a great deal

01:23:07.000 --> 01:23:09.000
[Guest]: of power was exercised by the women

01:23:09.000 --> 01:23:11.000
[Guest]: and where they managed in many

01:23:11.000 --> 01:23:13.000
[Guest]: ways to escape this veil

01:23:13.000 --> 01:23:15.000
[Guest]: in one way or the other, you know,

01:23:15.000 --> 01:23:17.000
[Guest]: despite the attempts by Abu al-Fazl

01:23:17.000 --> 01:23:19.000
[Amit Varma]: to keep them constrained.

01:23:19.000 --> 01:23:21.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, at one point you write after Gulbadan comes back

01:23:21.000 --> 01:23:23.000
[Amit Varma]: from the Hajj, you write, stop quote,

01:23:23.000 --> 01:23:25.000
[Amit Varma]: the Zainana at Fatehpur secreted Gulbadan

01:23:25.000 --> 01:23:27.000
[Amit Varma]: returns to in 1582 is very

01:23:27.000 --> 01:23:29.000
[Amit Varma]: different from the Haramana for wandering with Humayun.

01:23:29.000 --> 01:23:31.000
[Amit Varma]: The great tented mobile cities

01:23:31.000 --> 01:23:33.000
[Amit Varma]: have disappeared, replaced by the

01:23:33.000 --> 01:23:35.000
[Amit Varma]: sandstone and marble walls and palaces

01:23:35.000 --> 01:23:37.000
[Amit Varma]: of Akbar Zainana. Stop quote.

01:23:37.000 --> 01:23:39.000
[Amit Varma]: But what is happening here, interestingly,

01:23:39.000 --> 01:23:41.000
[Amit Varma]: is that even though these women are

01:23:41.000 --> 01:23:43.000
[Amit Varma]: largely being kept separate and the whole

01:23:43.000 --> 01:23:45.000
[Amit Varma]: management has changed that

01:23:45.000 --> 01:23:47.000
[Amit Varma]: the matriarchs that remain are still

01:23:47.000 --> 01:23:49.000
[Amit Varma]: very influential in politics

01:23:49.000 --> 01:23:51.000
[Amit Varma]: and political manners

01:23:51.000 --> 01:23:53.000
[Amit Varma]: matters, for example, how they help

01:23:53.000 --> 01:23:55.000
[Unknown]: Saleem, whom we later

01:23:55.000 --> 01:23:57.000
[Guest]: know as Jahangir come to power.

01:23:57.000 --> 01:23:59.000
[Guest]: Tell me a little bit. So it's

01:23:59.000 --> 01:24:01.000
[Guest]: interesting that though on the one

01:24:01.000 --> 01:24:03.000
[Guest]: hand we are told by many writers and

01:24:03.000 --> 01:24:05.000
[Guest]: many Europeans that this was a place of gossip

01:24:05.000 --> 01:24:07.000
[Guest]: and intrigue and backbiting and you know

01:24:07.000 --> 01:24:09.000
[Guest]: jealousies among the women.

01:24:09.000 --> 01:24:11.000
[Guest]: I find that actually they were very

01:24:11.000 --> 01:24:13.000
[Guest]: united in their cause, these women.

01:24:13.000 --> 01:24:15.000
[Guest]: And when they supported a prince, it was usually

01:24:15.000 --> 01:24:17.000
[Guest]: everyone together. When they

01:24:17.000 --> 01:24:19.000
[Guest]: tried to get somebody

01:24:19.000 --> 01:24:21.000
[Guest]: thrown out of court or out of

01:24:21.000 --> 01:24:23.000
[Guest]: favor, it was all together. Whether it was

01:24:23.000 --> 01:24:25.000
[Guest]: the Jesuit missionaries who eventually had to go

01:24:25.000 --> 01:24:27.000
[Guest]: and they attribute their fault

01:24:27.000 --> 01:24:29.000
[Guest]: to the fact that the wives

01:24:29.000 --> 01:24:31.000
[Guest]: and women of Akbar were against them.

01:24:31.000 --> 01:24:33.000
[Guest]: So they were very powerful and they

01:24:33.000 --> 01:24:35.000
[Guest]: seemed very united in their cause.

01:24:35.000 --> 01:24:37.000
[Guest]: And Saleem was a great example

01:24:37.000 --> 01:24:39.000
[Guest]: of that. He was a complicated

01:24:39.000 --> 01:24:41.000
[Guest]: prince who had a complicated

01:24:41.000 --> 01:24:43.000
[Guest]: relationship with a very

01:24:43.000 --> 01:24:45.000
[Guest]: powerful father. So this father-son

01:24:45.000 --> 01:24:47.000
[Guest]: dynamic was something which was difficult to

01:24:47.000 --> 01:24:49.000
[Guest]: navigate for him, you know. And I think

01:24:49.000 --> 01:24:51.000
[Guest]: he often relied on the support of the

01:24:51.000 --> 01:24:53.000
[Guest]: women. And at one point, I think in

01:24:53.000 --> 01:24:55.000
[Guest]: open court, I think it was Salima Sultan

01:24:55.000 --> 01:24:57.000
[Guest]: Begum from behind the jali, she says

01:24:57.000 --> 01:24:59.000
[Guest]: you know Pacha, we have something to say to you

01:24:59.000 --> 01:25:01.000
[Guest]: and if you don't come to us, we will

01:25:01.000 --> 01:25:03.000
[Guest]: come to you. So I found that really

01:25:03.000 --> 01:25:05.000
[Guest]: funny. I was like, this is a threat. They are saying

01:25:05.000 --> 01:25:07.000
[Guest]: that they are going to come out in open court

01:25:07.000 --> 01:25:09.000
[Guest]: and create a scene if he doesn't come to them

01:25:09.000 --> 01:25:11.000
[Guest]: and listen to their woes or whatever

01:25:11.000 --> 01:25:13.000
[Guest]: a farmaish they want to make.

01:25:13.000 --> 01:25:15.000
[Guest]: And he goes. So

01:25:15.000 --> 01:25:17.000
[Guest]: they were very united in their cause and

01:25:17.000 --> 01:25:19.000
[Guest]: when they supported a prince, princes

01:25:19.000 --> 01:25:21.000
[Guest]: really relied on this support

01:25:21.000 --> 01:25:23.000
[Guest]: to get further and to get

01:25:23.000 --> 01:25:25.000
[Guest]: gain of cause for whatever they

01:25:25.000 --> 01:25:27.000
[Amit Varma]: wanted to achieve. And in the case of Saleem

01:25:27.000 --> 01:25:29.000
[Amit Varma]: in fact, you know his estrangement

01:25:29.000 --> 01:25:31.000
[Amit Varma]: was so severe that when Akbar sent

01:25:31.000 --> 01:25:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Abu al-Fazl, he got Abu al-Fazl

01:25:33.000 --> 01:25:35.000
[Amit Varma]: beheaded, which would not have made

01:25:35.000 --> 01:25:37.000
[Amit Varma]: some of the women so unhappy, I imagine

01:25:37.000 --> 01:25:39.000
[Amit Varma]: going by the histories

01:25:39.000 --> 01:25:41.000
[Amit Varma]: that he eventually wrote.

01:25:41.000 --> 01:25:43.000
[Amit Varma]: But then Salima Sultan Begum

01:25:43.000 --> 01:25:45.000
[Amit Varma]: steps in and she helps her father and the

01:25:45.000 --> 01:25:47.000
[Guest]: son come together and then eventually

01:25:47.000 --> 01:25:49.000
[Guest]: there is a rapprochement despite the one beheaded

01:25:49.000 --> 01:25:51.000
[Guest]: friend of Akbar. Yes, one beheaded

01:25:51.000 --> 01:25:53.000
[Guest]: friend, exactly. And it is

01:25:53.000 --> 01:25:55.000
[Guest]: of course they wrote that we can only

01:25:55.000 --> 01:25:57.000
[Guest]: imagine Akbar's, you know, great

01:25:57.000 --> 01:25:59.000
[Guest]: disarray and distress at the death of

01:25:59.000 --> 01:26:01.000
[Guest]: his great friend. So, to have

01:26:01.000 --> 01:26:03.000
[Guest]: brought about this rapprochement when

01:26:03.000 --> 01:26:05.000
[Guest]: Saleem has crossed such a

01:26:05.000 --> 01:26:07.000
[Guest]: line and committed such a grave

01:26:07.000 --> 01:26:09.000
[Guest]: error shows the influence of the

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:11.000
[Guest]: women that they were, despite that

01:26:11.000 --> 01:26:13.000
[Guest]: and Salima Sultan Begum is sent out

01:26:13.000 --> 01:26:15.000
[Guest]: to do this job, which is interesting because

01:26:15.000 --> 01:26:17.000
[Guest]: on her own, well, Akbar

01:26:17.000 --> 01:26:19.000
[Guest]: marries her but it almost seems to be

01:26:19.000 --> 01:26:21.000
[Guest]: a marriage of convenience. They have no children

01:26:21.000 --> 01:26:23.000
[Guest]: together and she is older to Akbar so maybe

01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:25.000
[Guest]: he views her more as an older relative.

01:26:25.000 --> 01:26:27.000
[Guest]: But, so despite the fact that she has

01:26:27.000 --> 01:26:29.000
[Guest]: no son of her own, no, you know,

01:26:29.000 --> 01:26:31.000
[Guest]: independent status of her own,

01:26:31.000 --> 01:26:33.000
[Guest]: she has this respect and she is sent

01:26:33.000 --> 01:26:35.000
[Guest]: to bring Saleem back

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:37.000
[Guest]: to influence Saleem also because he is

01:26:37.000 --> 01:26:39.000
[Guest]: also of a mind to just create trouble

01:26:39.000 --> 01:26:41.000
[Guest]: and to create his own court and

01:26:41.000 --> 01:26:43.000
[Guest]: to challenge his father. She talks to him

01:26:43.000 --> 01:26:45.000
[Guest]: and she brings gifts from his father and says, look

01:26:45.000 --> 01:26:47.000
[Guest]: this elephant I am bringing from your

01:26:47.000 --> 01:26:49.000
[Guest]: father that means, he means well

01:26:49.000 --> 01:26:51.000
[Guest]: he is not out to harm you. And she

01:26:51.000 --> 01:26:53.000
[Guest]: brings him to court and finally there is a

01:26:53.000 --> 01:26:55.000
[Guest]: rapprochement between the two and Akbar does

01:26:55.000 --> 01:26:57.000
[Amit Varma]: forgive Saleem for this heinous crime.

01:26:57.000 --> 01:26:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And besides all the remarkable women

01:26:59.000 --> 01:27:01.000
[Amit Varma]: in your story, there is also a

01:27:01.000 --> 01:27:03.000
[Amit Varma]: remarkable ship, which of course is

01:27:03.000 --> 01:27:05.000
[Amit Varma]: Rahimi, which is

01:27:05.000 --> 01:27:07.000
[Amit Varma]: Harkabai's ship or Maryam Uzmani

01:27:07.000 --> 01:27:09.000
[Amit Varma]: as she was known. And I found this whole

01:27:09.000 --> 01:27:11.000
[Amit Varma]: episode with Maryam Uzmani

01:27:11.000 --> 01:27:13.000
[Amit Varma]: and Rahimi and what happens to Rahimi

01:27:13.000 --> 01:27:15.000
[Amit Varma]: very fascinating because this

01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:17.000
[Amit Varma]: is again one of those happenstance things that

01:27:17.000 --> 01:27:19.000
[Amit Varma]: it kind of almost causes

01:27:19.000 --> 01:27:21.000
[Amit Varma]: a decline in the fortunes of

01:27:21.000 --> 01:27:23.000
[Unknown]: Portuguese colonialism.

01:27:23.000 --> 01:27:25.000
[Amit Varma]: This is a fascinating episode and Rahimi

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:27.000
[Amit Varma]: of course is described in this

01:27:27.000 --> 01:27:29.000
[Amit Varma]: sentence that I found just

01:27:29.000 --> 01:27:31.000
[Amit Varma]: lovely, which was described

01:27:31.000 --> 01:27:33.000
[Amit Varma]: it as a Hindu Queen's Muslim ship

01:27:33.000 --> 01:27:35.000
[Amit Varma]: carrying hutch pilgrims in Christian

01:27:35.000 --> 01:27:37.000
[Amit Varma]: waters patrolled by the Portuguese

01:27:37.000 --> 01:27:39.000
[Guest]: armada. Stop Guru. Yes.

01:27:39.000 --> 01:27:41.000
[Guest]: Tell me what happened here. Well, you know

01:27:41.000 --> 01:27:43.000
[Guest]: it's amazing and it just shows the polyphony

01:27:43.000 --> 01:27:45.000
[Guest]: and you know the multiplicity

01:27:45.000 --> 01:27:47.000
[Guest]: of the court at this

01:27:47.000 --> 01:27:49.000
[Guest]: time is that, so as I said

01:27:49.000 --> 01:27:51.000
[Guest]: after Akbar passed away

01:27:51.000 --> 01:27:53.000
[Guest]: we see more visibly that Harkabai is

01:27:53.000 --> 01:27:55.000
[Guest]: a very powerful woman and she has

01:27:55.000 --> 01:27:57.000
[Guest]: a ship in her own name who sails under

01:27:57.000 --> 01:27:59.000
[Guest]: her colors, the Rahimi.

01:27:59.000 --> 01:28:01.000
[Guest]: So this is a hud ship

01:28:01.000 --> 01:28:03.000
[Guest]: but the hud ships at the same time also

01:28:03.000 --> 01:28:05.000
[Guest]: conducted trade.

01:28:05.000 --> 01:28:07.000
[Guest]: There was a lot of trade in the Indian

01:28:07.000 --> 01:28:09.000
[Guest]: Ocean between India and the Middle

01:28:09.000 --> 01:28:11.000
[Guest]: East and further still

01:28:11.000 --> 01:28:13.000
[Guest]: from way back and it was the Portuguese who

01:28:13.000 --> 01:28:15.000
[Guest]: started controlling this and they introduced

01:28:15.000 --> 01:28:17.000
[Guest]: piracy and rapacity and you know they were

01:28:17.000 --> 01:28:19.000
[Guest]: pretty brutal in their dealings with the Indian

01:28:19.000 --> 01:28:21.000
[Guest]: ships. So they were loathed

01:28:21.000 --> 01:28:23.000
[Guest]: by everybody. You know everybody was

01:28:23.000 --> 01:28:25.000
[Guest]: agreed that the Portuguese we need to find

01:28:25.000 --> 01:28:27.000
[Guest]: a way to get them out of Indian waters

01:28:27.000 --> 01:28:29.000
[Guest]: because they only create trouble and

01:28:29.000 --> 01:28:31.000
[Guest]: they also since their hutch pilgrims have been

01:28:31.000 --> 01:28:33.000
[Guest]: carried there they used to also look for any

01:28:33.000 --> 01:28:35.000
[Guest]: chance to trouble the

01:28:35.000 --> 01:28:37.000
[Guest]: pilgrims you know and to torture them if they could.

01:28:37.000 --> 01:28:39.000
[Guest]: So Harkabai has

01:28:39.000 --> 01:28:41.000
[Guest]: this ship called the Rahimi and

01:28:41.000 --> 01:28:43.000
[Guest]: the Portuguese have introduced this system

01:28:43.000 --> 01:28:45.000
[Guest]: because they do control the waters because of

01:28:45.000 --> 01:28:47.000
[Guest]: superior naval power and they've brought

01:28:47.000 --> 01:28:49.000
[Guest]: this system of the Kartaz which is

01:28:49.000 --> 01:28:51.000
[Guest]: a pass that you have to have obtained

01:28:51.000 --> 01:28:53.000
[Guest]: from the Portuguese authority to have your

01:28:53.000 --> 01:28:55.000
[Guest]: ship sail. Now the Mughals

01:28:55.000 --> 01:28:57.000
[Guest]: hate this because the Kartaz has a

01:28:57.000 --> 01:28:59.000
[Guest]: picture of the Holy Mary

01:28:59.000 --> 01:29:01.000
[Guest]: and they really hate the fact that

01:29:01.000 --> 01:29:03.000
[Guest]: their pilgrims they're going to Mecca

01:29:03.000 --> 01:29:05.000
[Guest]: having to carry this pass with you know Christian

01:29:05.000 --> 01:29:07.000
[Guest]: symbols on it. So it is in many ways

01:29:07.000 --> 01:29:09.000
[Guest]: you know a flexing of muscles

01:29:09.000 --> 01:29:11.000
[Guest]: and showing strength and who must

01:29:11.000 --> 01:29:13.000
[Guest]: obey which laws and

01:29:13.000 --> 01:29:15.000
[Guest]: so Harkabai detests the

01:29:15.000 --> 01:29:17.000
[Guest]: idea that she has to you know kowtow to them

01:29:17.000 --> 01:29:19.000
[Guest]: and obtain this pass but they do

01:29:19.000 --> 01:29:21.000
[Guest]: and despite that

01:29:21.000 --> 01:29:23.000
[Guest]: the ship is seized and

01:29:23.000 --> 01:29:25.000
[Guest]: Harkabai is really furious at this

01:29:25.000 --> 01:29:27.000
[Guest]: and she says we must

01:29:27.000 --> 01:29:29.000
[Guest]: stop all trade with the Portuguese if this is

01:29:29.000 --> 01:29:31.000
[Guest]: the way that they're going to treat our ships

01:29:31.000 --> 01:29:33.000
[Guest]: and until this point really

01:29:33.000 --> 01:29:35.000
[Guest]: none of the Mughals had really

01:29:35.000 --> 01:29:37.000
[Guest]: confronted the Portuguese. The Mughals

01:29:37.000 --> 01:29:39.000
[Guest]: their vision was more turned to

01:29:39.000 --> 01:29:41.000
[Guest]: the land. It was more to the agricultural

01:29:41.000 --> 01:29:43.000
[Guest]: hinterland where all the money was

01:29:43.000 --> 01:29:45.000
[Guest]: the produce was you know where the great harvests

01:29:45.000 --> 01:29:47.000
[Guest]: of India were. They were not looking

01:29:47.000 --> 01:29:49.000
[Guest]: so much outwards towards the

01:29:49.000 --> 01:29:51.000
[Guest]: seas. They did have a navy

01:29:51.000 --> 01:29:53.000
[Guest]: it was largely a river navy

01:29:53.000 --> 01:29:55.000
[Guest]: you know so they sailed the rivers

01:29:55.000 --> 01:29:57.000
[Guest]: not so much the high seas.

01:29:57.000 --> 01:29:59.000
[Guest]: So they had not really come into confrontation

01:29:59.000 --> 01:30:01.000
[Guest]: not that they particularly want to

01:30:01.000 --> 01:30:03.000
[Guest]: but when Harkabai made this demand

01:30:03.000 --> 01:30:05.000
[Guest]: it effectively, now she never did

01:30:05.000 --> 01:30:07.000
[Guest]: recover the Rahimi but it

01:30:07.000 --> 01:30:09.000
[Guest]: effectively brought to an end

01:30:09.000 --> 01:30:11.000
[Guest]: the great control that the Portuguese

01:30:11.000 --> 01:30:13.000
[Guest]: had over the Indian waters and the English

01:30:13.000 --> 01:30:15.000
[Guest]: are delighted because

01:30:15.000 --> 01:30:17.000
[Guest]: they know that if the Portuguese are out and they've been

01:30:17.000 --> 01:30:19.000
[Guest]: controlling the waters maybe it is the time of

01:30:19.000 --> 01:30:21.000
[Guest]: the English finally and they write

01:30:21.000 --> 01:30:23.000
[Guest]: with great delight and say the

01:30:23.000 --> 01:30:25.000
[Guest]: Queen Mother is furious at the Portuguese

01:30:25.000 --> 01:30:27.000
[Guest]: and this will spell the end

01:30:27.000 --> 01:30:29.000
[Guest]: and in a way it did and so

01:30:29.000 --> 01:30:31.000
[Guest]: happenstance again as you say

01:30:31.000 --> 01:30:33.000
[Guest]: brought about this

01:30:33.000 --> 01:30:35.000
[Guest]: this amazing

01:30:35.000 --> 01:30:37.000
[Guest]: you know change in the politics

01:30:37.000 --> 01:30:39.000
[Amit Varma]: of the waters. Do you sometimes get tempted

01:30:39.000 --> 01:30:41.000
[Amit Varma]: just to forget about history's history

01:30:41.000 --> 01:30:43.000
[Guest]: and write counterfactuals?

01:30:45.000 --> 01:30:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's not even go there.

01:30:47.000 --> 01:30:49.000
[Guest]: That would also take you back to literature right?

01:30:49.000 --> 01:30:51.000
[Guest]: That's right. Which you said was your first love.

01:30:53.000 --> 01:30:55.000
[Amit Varma]: The next character I want to talk about is

01:30:55.000 --> 01:30:57.000
[Amit Varma]: Noor Jahan and she is

01:30:57.000 --> 01:30:59.000
[Amit Varma]: really interesting because she has got

01:30:59.000 --> 01:31:01.000
[Amit Varma]: really humble beginnings. Yes. She

01:31:01.000 --> 01:31:03.000
[Amit Varma]: rises to great wealth even more than

01:31:03.000 --> 01:31:05.000
[Unknown]: the emperor himself perhaps as you point out.

01:31:05.000 --> 01:31:07.000
[Amit Varma]: Yes. But she has a kind of an

01:31:07.000 --> 01:31:09.000
[Guest]: enormous end. Yes.

01:31:09.000 --> 01:31:11.000
[Guest]: So Noor Jahan is a fascinating

01:31:11.000 --> 01:31:13.000
[Guest]: character you know again

01:31:13.000 --> 01:31:15.000
[Guest]: pretty poorly served by the

01:31:15.000 --> 01:31:17.000
[Guest]: Europeans who always

01:31:17.000 --> 01:31:19.000
[Guest]: imply that she holds the

01:31:19.000 --> 01:31:21.000
[Guest]: emperor in sexual thrall so

01:31:21.000 --> 01:31:23.000
[Guest]: it is a way a debasement of Jahangir

01:31:23.000 --> 01:31:25.000
[Guest]: also and it is

01:31:25.000 --> 01:31:27.000
[Guest]: you know they are showing her as this manipulative

01:31:27.000 --> 01:31:29.000
[Guest]: sort of

01:31:29.000 --> 01:31:31.000
[Guest]: virago type person you know which is doing her

01:31:31.000 --> 01:31:33.000
[Guest]: a great disservice. As you say she

01:31:33.000 --> 01:31:35.000
[Guest]: came as a refugee. Her family came as refugees

01:31:35.000 --> 01:31:37.000
[Guest]: from Persia and they

01:31:37.000 --> 01:31:39.000
[Guest]: came to Akbar's court and then they rose slowly

01:31:39.000 --> 01:31:41.000
[Guest]: through the ranks. They were all very talented

01:31:41.000 --> 01:31:43.000
[Guest]: whether it's her father who was prime minister, her

01:31:43.000 --> 01:31:45.000
[Guest]: brother who controlled, who was very very

01:31:45.000 --> 01:31:47.000
[Guest]: powerful, Noor Jahan herself.

01:31:47.000 --> 01:31:49.000
[Guest]: Not just powerful, very very

01:31:49.000 --> 01:31:51.000
[Guest]: talented people. They did things in all

01:31:51.000 --> 01:31:53.000
[Guest]: fields. Her mother developed attar of

01:31:53.000 --> 01:31:55.000
[Guest]: roses for example you know. She just

01:31:55.000 --> 01:31:57.000
[Guest]: collected the skum after boiling roses and

01:31:57.000 --> 01:31:59.000
[Guest]: found this amazing fragrance.

01:31:59.000 --> 01:32:01.000
[Guest]: So they were a talented family

01:32:01.000 --> 01:32:03.000
[Guest]: and she achieved a great deal

01:32:03.000 --> 01:32:05.000
[Guest]: which Rubilal talks with

01:32:05.000 --> 01:32:07.000
[Guest]: a great deal of authority. So I have not

01:32:07.000 --> 01:32:09.000
[Guest]: written a great deal on

01:32:09.000 --> 01:32:11.000
[Guest]: Noor Jahan because it is all there

01:32:11.000 --> 01:32:13.000
[Guest]: in Rubilal's amazing book Empress

01:32:13.000 --> 01:32:15.000
[Guest]: but what she says which is of interest to

01:32:15.000 --> 01:32:17.000
[Guest]: me is the fact that we have

01:32:17.000 --> 01:32:19.000
[Guest]: to see what Noor Jahan did

01:32:19.000 --> 01:32:21.000
[Guest]: and see it in context

01:32:21.000 --> 01:32:23.000
[Guest]: because in India we have a you know

01:32:23.000 --> 01:32:25.000
[Guest]: history is taught in a sort of bullet point form

01:32:25.000 --> 01:32:27.000
[Guest]: so we are told she shot lions,

01:32:27.000 --> 01:32:29.000
[Guest]: she minted coins, she did this that and the

01:32:29.000 --> 01:32:31.000
[Guest]: other. You learn all these four or five facts and you move

01:32:31.000 --> 01:32:33.000
[Guest]: on to the next thing. But what you have to

01:32:33.000 --> 01:32:35.000
[Guest]: realize is put in context

01:32:35.000 --> 01:32:37.000
[Guest]: who shoots lions? Only

01:32:37.000 --> 01:32:39.000
[Guest]: the Padshah. Nobody else is allowed to shoot

01:32:39.000 --> 01:32:41.000
[Guest]: lions. It is a royal prerogative.

01:32:41.000 --> 01:32:43.000
[Guest]: Who mints coins? Only the Padshah.

01:32:43.000 --> 01:32:45.000
[Guest]: The Jharoka Darshan. Who sits

01:32:45.000 --> 01:32:47.000
[Guest]: at the Jharoka and allows themselves

01:32:47.000 --> 01:32:49.000
[Guest]: to be painted and represented as

01:32:49.000 --> 01:32:51.000
[Guest]: sitting at the Jharoka? It is the

01:32:51.000 --> 01:32:53.000
[Guest]: emperor. So if you put all these

01:32:53.000 --> 01:32:55.000
[Guest]: points together that she does and she

01:32:55.000 --> 01:32:57.000
[Guest]: does do all these things and put it in the

01:32:57.000 --> 01:32:59.000
[Guest]: context of the time, it means as

01:32:59.000 --> 01:33:01.000
[Guest]: Shubilal has said that she is co-empress.

01:33:01.000 --> 01:33:03.000
[Guest]: She shares power

01:33:03.000 --> 01:33:05.000
[Guest]: equally with Jahangir who shares that

01:33:05.000 --> 01:33:07.000
[Guest]: power with her. He is not doing it because he is

01:33:07.000 --> 01:33:09.000
[Guest]: debased or because he is in the throes

01:33:09.000 --> 01:33:11.000
[Guest]: of alcohol or anything else.

01:33:11.000 --> 01:33:13.000
[Guest]: He does it because he is happy to share

01:33:13.000 --> 01:33:15.000
[Guest]: power with a very talented woman

01:33:15.000 --> 01:33:17.000
[Guest]: at a time when he is poorly, his health

01:33:17.000 --> 01:33:19.000
[Guest]: is failing and this woman

01:33:19.000 --> 01:33:21.000
[Guest]: has the vision and the

01:33:21.000 --> 01:33:23.000
[Guest]: aesthetic vision to carry his

01:33:23.000 --> 01:33:25.000
[Guest]: legacy forward which she does

01:33:25.000 --> 01:33:27.000
[Guest]: you know when we look at the tomb that she

01:33:27.000 --> 01:33:29.000
[Guest]: builds for Itmad-ud-Daulah's tomb

01:33:29.000 --> 01:33:31.000
[Guest]: outside Agra. If you look at that

01:33:31.000 --> 01:33:33.000
[Guest]: tomb, it is the culmination

01:33:33.000 --> 01:33:35.000
[Guest]: for me. That's why I have focused more on Itmad-ud-Daulah's

01:33:35.000 --> 01:33:37.000
[Guest]: tomb and less the other aspects which

01:33:37.000 --> 01:33:39.000
[Guest]: Shubilal has covered so well.

01:33:39.000 --> 01:33:41.000
[Guest]: Itmad-ud-Daulah's tomb is the culmination

01:33:41.000 --> 01:33:43.000
[Guest]: of Noor Jahan's talent and we look

01:33:43.000 --> 01:33:45.000
[Guest]: at that building built years

01:33:45.000 --> 01:33:47.000
[Guest]: before the Taj Mahal. It is in pure

01:33:47.000 --> 01:33:49.000
[Guest]: white marble which had never been done before

01:33:49.000 --> 01:33:51.000
[Guest]: and which Shah Jahan did because he saw

01:33:51.000 --> 01:33:53.000
[Guest]: Itmad-ud-Daulah's tomb. It has got inlay

01:33:53.000 --> 01:33:55.000
[Guest]: work which had never been done before which was later

01:33:55.000 --> 01:33:57.000
[Guest]: copied in the Taj Mahal. So it is

01:33:57.000 --> 01:33:59.000
[Guest]: a trailblazing monument. It is a

01:33:59.000 --> 01:34:01.000
[Guest]: beautiful, exquisite monument

01:34:01.000 --> 01:34:03.000
[Guest]: and if you look at, so she builds this for her parents.

01:34:03.000 --> 01:34:05.000
[Guest]: She is very dedicated to her parents

01:34:05.000 --> 01:34:07.000
[Guest]: who are both, as I said, very talented people.

01:34:07.000 --> 01:34:09.000
[Guest]: When they die, she is heartbroken

01:34:09.000 --> 01:34:11.000
[Guest]: and they die within three months of each other

01:34:11.000 --> 01:34:13.000
[Guest]: which I also find very moving.

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:15.000
[Guest]: The wife dies

01:34:15.000 --> 01:34:17.000
[Guest]: and Jahangir writes in his biography

01:34:17.000 --> 01:34:19.000
[Guest]: that you know the poor man, Itmad-ud-Daulah

01:34:19.000 --> 01:34:21.000
[Guest]: is heartbroken. I am trying to cheer him up

01:34:21.000 --> 01:34:23.000
[Guest]: but I fear for his life and within three

01:34:23.000 --> 01:34:25.000
[Guest]: months of his wife's death, he passes away

01:34:25.000 --> 01:34:27.000
[Guest]: too. He is so, you know

01:34:27.000 --> 01:34:29.000
[Guest]: he and his wife are so close

01:34:29.000 --> 01:34:31.000
[Guest]: and then Nur Jahan builds this

01:34:31.000 --> 01:34:33.000
[Guest]: beautiful tomb for them. At the same

01:34:33.000 --> 01:34:35.000
[Guest]: time, Jahangir

01:34:35.000 --> 01:34:37.000
[Guest]: is building a tomb for his mother, you know

01:34:37.000 --> 01:34:39.000
[Guest]: not long after. Maryam

01:34:39.000 --> 01:34:41.000
[Guest]: Uzzomani's tomb which you can see today also

01:34:41.000 --> 01:34:43.000
[Guest]: outside Agra and it is a

01:34:43.000 --> 01:34:45.000
[Guest]: thing of very little beauty

01:34:45.000 --> 01:34:47.000
[Guest]: and very little grace and it is actually

01:34:47.000 --> 01:34:49.000
[Guest]: a reconfigured Lodhi

01:34:49.000 --> 01:34:51.000
[Guest]: Biradri. So he has just taken an existing

01:34:51.000 --> 01:34:53.000
[Guest]: structure, added two, three things to it

01:34:53.000 --> 01:34:55.000
[Guest]: and said I will bury my mother here.

01:34:55.000 --> 01:34:57.000
[Guest]: So I talked about this once, you know

01:34:57.000 --> 01:34:59.000
[Guest]: at a talk I was giving and I was saying

01:34:59.000 --> 01:35:01.000
[Guest]: I think the lesson to be learnt here is that if you are

01:35:01.000 --> 01:35:03.000
[Guest]: planning to build a mausoleum for yourself

01:35:03.000 --> 01:35:05.000
[Guest]: give the task to your daughter not to

01:35:05.000 --> 01:35:07.000
[Guest]: your son, you know because they take more

01:35:07.000 --> 01:35:09.000
[Guest]: care with things like legacy and

01:35:09.000 --> 01:35:11.000
[Guest]: memory and you know eternal

01:35:11.000 --> 01:35:13.000
[Amit Varma]: sort of. Which some would say applies to more

01:35:13.000 --> 01:35:15.000
[Guest]: things than just mausoleums.

01:35:15.000 --> 01:35:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Digressing slightly, you know you said

01:35:17.000 --> 01:35:19.000
[Amit Varma]: you have grown up in Delhi and you are surrounded by all these

01:35:19.000 --> 01:35:21.000
[Amit Varma]: great historical monuments and buildings

01:35:21.000 --> 01:35:23.000
[Amit Varma]: and tombs and so on. Do you look

01:35:23.000 --> 01:35:25.000
[Guest]: at them differently now? I do.

01:35:25.000 --> 01:35:27.000
[Guest]: I do, I do. That's a very

01:35:27.000 --> 01:35:29.000
[Guest]: pertinent point that you have raised and I do

01:35:29.000 --> 01:35:31.000
[Guest]: look at them very differently

01:35:31.000 --> 01:35:33.000
[Guest]: and it's sad that we don't all do that

01:35:33.000 --> 01:35:35.000
[Guest]: because we are surrounded by such treasures

01:35:35.000 --> 01:35:37.000
[Guest]: in Delhi and many many other

01:35:37.000 --> 01:35:39.000
[Amit Varma]: cities which we take for granted

01:35:39.000 --> 01:35:41.000
[Guest]: all the time. Not only do we take

01:35:41.000 --> 01:35:43.000
[Guest]: it for granted, we let them fall to ruin

01:35:43.000 --> 01:35:45.000
[Guest]: to disrepair

01:35:45.000 --> 01:35:47.000
[Guest]: and there are so many good people trying to

01:35:47.000 --> 01:35:49.000
[Guest]: work against that and trying

01:35:49.000 --> 01:35:51.000
[Guest]: to get us more aware of these amazing things

01:35:51.000 --> 01:35:53.000
[Guest]: that we have just in our life

01:35:53.000 --> 01:35:55.000
[Guest]: around us. If you compare with other

01:35:55.000 --> 01:35:57.000
[Guest]: cities who don't have that

01:35:57.000 --> 01:35:59.000
[Guest]: you know you feel bereft without all

01:35:59.000 --> 01:36:01.000
[Guest]: this history. Here we take it for granted but it is

01:36:01.000 --> 01:36:03.000
[Guest]: such a wonderful thing to have.

01:36:03.000 --> 01:36:05.000
[Guest]: Now when I look at them, I look at the stones

01:36:05.000 --> 01:36:07.000
[Guest]: and I see what they have to say

01:36:07.000 --> 01:36:09.000
[Guest]: I know I can figure out what influence

01:36:09.000 --> 01:36:11.000
[Guest]: is there, who came later, what they

01:36:11.000 --> 01:36:13.000
[Guest]: tried to change. You can see

01:36:13.000 --> 01:36:15.000
[Guest]: a Mughal building with a bit of a temple statue

01:36:15.000 --> 01:36:17.000
[Guest]: element in it, you know that some temple

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:19.000
[Guest]: must have been broken and this

01:36:19.000 --> 01:36:21.000
[Guest]: bit was taken because this was the

01:36:21.000 --> 01:36:23.000
[Guest]: pragmatic reality. We used

01:36:23.000 --> 01:36:25.000
[Guest]: materials whether one way or the other. You found

01:36:25.000 --> 01:36:27.000
[Guest]: materials lying around, you used it

01:36:27.000 --> 01:36:29.000
[Guest]: but if you are not told these things

01:36:29.000 --> 01:36:31.000
[Guest]: and you don't have the eyes to see it

01:36:31.000 --> 01:36:33.000
[Guest]: then you know it just gets wasted in a way

01:36:33.000 --> 01:36:35.000
[Amit Varma]: and it's such a shame.

01:36:35.000 --> 01:36:37.000
[Guest]: So do you go often to... I do.

01:36:37.000 --> 01:36:39.000
[Guest]: So I go for a lot of heritage walks

01:36:39.000 --> 01:36:41.000
[Guest]: part of my research

01:36:41.000 --> 01:36:43.000
[Guest]: I call it part of my research though I love it immensely

01:36:43.000 --> 01:36:45.000
[Guest]: is going for these walks because

01:36:45.000 --> 01:36:47.000
[Guest]: we haven't talked a great deal about the

01:36:47.000 --> 01:36:49.000
[Guest]: research process but there is the primary sources

01:36:49.000 --> 01:36:51.000
[Guest]: there is the written material but there is also

01:36:51.000 --> 01:36:53.000
[Guest]: this intangible thing around us

01:36:53.000 --> 01:36:55.000
[Guest]: which is these heritage walks

01:36:55.000 --> 01:36:57.000
[Guest]: where these people who are not

01:36:57.000 --> 01:36:59.000
[Guest]: sometimes historians but sometimes amateurs

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:01.000
[Guest]: and enthusiasts, they are able to create

01:37:01.000 --> 01:37:03.000
[Guest]: a sense of those times when you go on

01:37:03.000 --> 01:37:05.000
[Guest]: these walks with them. They'll tell you

01:37:05.000 --> 01:37:07.000
[Guest]: what music was playing perhaps

01:37:07.000 --> 01:37:09.000
[Guest]: or what pan you were supposed to have

01:37:09.000 --> 01:37:11.000
[Guest]: at this location or whether there was a well

01:37:11.000 --> 01:37:13.000
[Guest]: there so you heard the trickling water

01:37:13.000 --> 01:37:15.000
[Guest]: so these people are also part of my research

01:37:15.000 --> 01:37:17.000
[Guest]: you know and I get a great deal of

01:37:17.000 --> 01:37:19.000
[Guest]: knowledge from going on these historical

01:37:19.000 --> 01:37:21.000
[Guest]: walks. So going on these walks has

01:37:21.000 --> 01:37:23.000
[Guest]: really opened my eyes to a lot of

01:37:23.000 --> 01:37:25.000
[Guest]: these monuments that are just lying around

01:37:25.000 --> 01:37:27.000
[Amit Varma]: you know. So much wealth

01:37:27.000 --> 01:37:29.000
[Amit Varma]: all around us, all my Bombay friends who

01:37:29.000 --> 01:37:31.000
[Amit Varma]: mock Delhi for the pollution

01:37:31.000 --> 01:37:33.000
[Guest]: and the people that is a lot more than that.

01:37:33.000 --> 01:37:35.000
[Amit Varma]: Oh please.

01:37:35.000 --> 01:37:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk about a

01:37:37.000 --> 01:37:39.000
[Amit Varma]: character you've written about more than just

01:37:39.000 --> 01:37:41.000
[Amit Varma]: in this book which is Jahanara

01:37:41.000 --> 01:37:43.000
[Unknown]: who is sort of the daughter of

01:37:43.000 --> 01:37:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Shah Jahan and she is unmarried

01:37:45.000 --> 01:37:47.000
[Amit Varma]: and you know she is a Padshah Begum

01:37:47.000 --> 01:37:49.000
[Amit Varma]: she is known as Begum Sahab

01:37:49.000 --> 01:37:51.000
[Amit Varma]: and her history

01:37:51.000 --> 01:37:53.000
[Amit Varma]: is kind of tragic and almost

01:37:53.000 --> 01:37:55.000
[Amit Varma]: a counterpoint to her younger sister Roshanara

01:37:55.000 --> 01:37:57.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:37:57.000 --> 01:37:59.000
[Guest]: You know I'll challenge you on that Amit

01:37:59.000 --> 01:38:01.000
[Guest]: and say that

01:38:01.000 --> 01:38:03.000
[Guest]: I think it is later people who have

01:38:03.000 --> 01:38:05.000
[Guest]: inferred that it was tragic

01:38:05.000 --> 01:38:07.000
[Guest]: perhaps because she was unmarried

01:38:07.000 --> 01:38:09.000
[Guest]: I wonder if she didn't actually prefer

01:38:09.000 --> 01:38:11.000
[Guest]: it that way because she was

01:38:11.000 --> 01:38:13.000
[Guest]: Shah Jahan's favourite daughter, eldest daughter

01:38:13.000 --> 01:38:15.000
[Guest]: also. She was 17 when Mumtaz Mahal

01:38:15.000 --> 01:38:17.000
[Guest]: died and half of Mumtaz

01:38:17.000 --> 01:38:19.000
[Guest]: Mahal's wealth which was a substantial

01:38:19.000 --> 01:38:21.000
[Guest]: amount, half of it went to Jahanara

01:38:21.000 --> 01:38:23.000
[Guest]: Begum. So you can see

01:38:23.000 --> 01:38:25.000
[Guest]: the way in the

01:38:25.000 --> 01:38:27.000
[Guest]: matriarchies carry on this

01:38:27.000 --> 01:38:29.000
[Guest]: tradition of giving wealth to their daughters

01:38:29.000 --> 01:38:31.000
[Guest]: so she has this enormous wealth at the age of 17

01:38:31.000 --> 01:38:33.000
[Guest]: already and she only accumulates

01:38:33.000 --> 01:38:35.000
[Guest]: wealth because she becomes more and more

01:38:35.000 --> 01:38:37.000
[Guest]: powerful. Shah Jahan

01:38:37.000 --> 01:38:39.000
[Guest]: gives her villagers in her name, he gives her

01:38:39.000 --> 01:38:41.000
[Guest]: trading ship, all the noblemen keep

01:38:41.000 --> 01:38:43.000
[Guest]: gifting her jewels and then she becomes an immensely

01:38:43.000 --> 01:38:45.000
[Guest]: powerful woman. Wealthy

01:38:45.000 --> 01:38:47.000
[Guest]: and powerful and she has the talent and ambition

01:38:47.000 --> 01:38:49.000
[Guest]: to do something with it. And I wonder

01:38:49.000 --> 01:38:51.000
[Guest]: if she was married to somebody

01:38:51.000 --> 01:38:53.000
[Guest]: it would be an inconsequential man because all

01:38:53.000 --> 01:38:55.000
[Guest]: who do we have left?

01:38:55.000 --> 01:38:57.000
[Guest]: In the wars of succession all the uncles have been

01:38:57.000 --> 01:38:59.000
[Guest]: killed off, the cousins have been killed off

01:38:59.000 --> 01:39:01.000
[Guest]: no powerful timid men remain

01:39:01.000 --> 01:39:03.000
[Guest]: for her to exist. Who would she have married?

01:39:03.000 --> 01:39:05.000
[Guest]: What kind of life would she have had? She would have had to

01:39:05.000 --> 01:39:07.000
[Guest]: bow out of the Mughal court

01:39:07.000 --> 01:39:09.000
[Guest]: which her younger sisters did, the ones who

01:39:09.000 --> 01:39:11.000
[Guest]: married, they bow out of Mughal history

01:39:11.000 --> 01:39:13.000
[Guest]: we don't hear about them ever again.

01:39:13.000 --> 01:39:15.000
[Guest]: I think Jahanara with her ambition

01:39:15.000 --> 01:39:17.000
[Guest]: was very happy to be the

01:39:17.000 --> 01:39:19.000
[Guest]: unmarried daughter of the greatest

01:39:19.000 --> 01:39:21.000
[Guest]: emperor on earth at that time.

01:39:21.000 --> 01:39:23.000
[Guest]: You must remember that we put this in context

01:39:23.000 --> 01:39:25.000
[Guest]: we must put it in global context. This was

01:39:25.000 --> 01:39:27.000
[Guest]: the most powerful and financially

01:39:27.000 --> 01:39:29.000
[Amit Varma]: wealthy empire on earth.

01:39:29.000 --> 01:39:31.000
[Amit Varma]: So she was basically like Ivanka Trump

01:39:31.000 --> 01:39:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Oh dear, where have we come to?

01:39:33.000 --> 01:39:35.000
[Amit Varma]: I shouldn't have said that.

01:39:35.000 --> 01:39:37.000
[Guest]: So you know

01:39:37.000 --> 01:39:39.000
[Guest]: I don't think she was that unhappy

01:39:39.000 --> 01:39:41.000
[Guest]: she had personal tragedies

01:39:41.000 --> 01:39:43.000
[Guest]: which of us doesn't. Her beloved

01:39:43.000 --> 01:39:45.000
[Guest]: Dara Shikoh, her brother

01:39:45.000 --> 01:39:47.000
[Guest]: is of course killed by Aurangzeb. She loses

01:39:47.000 --> 01:39:49.000
[Guest]: in that sense because she supported

01:39:49.000 --> 01:39:51.000
[Guest]: Dara Shikoh so she lost that battle

01:39:51.000 --> 01:39:53.000
[Guest]: but she won the war because Aurangzeb

01:39:53.000 --> 01:39:55.000
[Guest]: after the death of Shah Jahan brings her

01:39:55.000 --> 01:39:57.000
[Guest]: back to court, reinstates her as

01:39:57.000 --> 01:39:59.000
[Guest]: Padshah Begum. Not only that

01:39:59.000 --> 01:40:01.000
[Guest]: he allows her a home

01:40:01.000 --> 01:40:03.000
[Guest]: outside of the Zanana

01:40:03.000 --> 01:40:05.000
[Guest]: of the Red Fort. So she has an independent

01:40:05.000 --> 01:40:07.000
[Guest]: luxurious lifestyle where

01:40:07.000 --> 01:40:09.000
[Guest]: she can now create a court

01:40:09.000 --> 01:40:11.000
[Guest]: of music. So she starts to patronize

01:40:11.000 --> 01:40:13.000
[Guest]: musicians and poets. So

01:40:13.000 --> 01:40:15.000
[Guest]: in the end of her life this is what she has.

01:40:15.000 --> 01:40:17.000
[Guest]: So I don't think she is such

01:40:17.000 --> 01:40:19.000
[Guest]: an unhappy woman at the end of the day after all.

01:40:19.000 --> 01:40:21.000
[Amit Varma]: But in this activity, in living

01:40:21.000 --> 01:40:23.000
[Amit Varma]: separately, in building this house of music

01:40:23.000 --> 01:40:25.000
[Amit Varma]: she is in a microcosm doing

01:40:25.000 --> 01:40:27.000
[Amit Varma]: what could have happened if her brother

01:40:27.000 --> 01:40:29.000
[Guest]: Dara Shikoh had actually...

01:40:29.000 --> 01:40:31.000
[Guest]: Well, you know Dara Shikoh is one of the great

01:40:31.000 --> 01:40:33.000
[Guest]: what ifs of history, right?

01:40:33.000 --> 01:40:35.000
[Guest]: But to be very honest

01:40:35.000 --> 01:40:37.000
[Guest]: he was not a very competent ruler.

01:40:37.000 --> 01:40:39.000
[Guest]: I don't think he would have made a very competent ruler

01:40:39.000 --> 01:40:41.000
[Guest]: though we are instinctively drawn

01:40:41.000 --> 01:40:43.000
[Guest]: to him because of his history

01:40:43.000 --> 01:40:45.000
[Guest]: because of his interest in the

01:40:45.000 --> 01:40:47.000
[Guest]: Indian literature and his

01:40:47.000 --> 01:40:49.000
[Guest]: translating all those documents

01:40:49.000 --> 01:40:51.000
[Guest]: and him wanting to understand

01:40:51.000 --> 01:40:53.000
[Guest]: Indian, Hindustani literature better.

01:40:53.000 --> 01:40:55.000
[Guest]: So we want the

01:40:55.000 --> 01:40:57.000
[Guest]: goofy prince to have been king

01:40:57.000 --> 01:40:59.000
[Guest]: and to have created something wonderful.

01:40:59.000 --> 01:41:01.000
[Guest]: But I am sorry to say that he was

01:41:01.000 --> 01:41:03.000
[Guest]: a bit of a weakling, a bit

01:41:03.000 --> 01:41:05.000
[Guest]: of a vain man who had a tendency to

01:41:05.000 --> 01:41:07.000
[Guest]: listen to the sycophants around him

01:41:07.000 --> 01:41:09.000
[Guest]: who believed all that, who had

01:41:09.000 --> 01:41:11.000
[Guest]: a rather inflated idea of what he could do

01:41:11.000 --> 01:41:13.000
[Guest]: and could not do it. When push came to

01:41:13.000 --> 01:41:15.000
[Guest]: shove he could not fight his brother. He

01:41:15.000 --> 01:41:17.000
[Guest]: lost every battle against Aurangzeb.

01:41:17.000 --> 01:41:19.000
[Guest]: So if he had won somehow

01:41:19.000 --> 01:41:21.000
[Guest]: or the other, I am not sure the empire

01:41:21.000 --> 01:41:23.000
[Amit Varma]: would have progressed the way it did.

01:41:23.000 --> 01:41:25.000
[Amit Varma]: You know the reason they were fighting in the first

01:41:25.000 --> 01:41:27.000
[Amit Varma]: place is of course the Timurid line of succession

01:41:27.000 --> 01:41:29.000
[Amit Varma]: where it's not necessarily

01:41:29.000 --> 01:41:31.000
[Amit Varma]: the eldest son who ascends to the throne

01:41:31.000 --> 01:41:33.000
[Unknown]: but it's a meritocracy, you

01:41:33.000 --> 01:41:35.000
[Amit Varma]: fight for it and whoever is left standing at the end

01:41:35.000 --> 01:41:37.000
[Amit Varma]: of it and I don't know if that's a feature or a bug

01:41:37.000 --> 01:41:39.000
[Amit Varma]: because the good part of it is that

01:41:39.000 --> 01:41:41.000
[Amit Varma]: the able ruler will eventually

01:41:41.000 --> 01:41:43.000
[Amit Varma]: in theory get there but the bad part

01:41:43.000 --> 01:41:45.000
[Amit Varma]: of it is that you have all this politics

01:41:45.000 --> 01:41:47.000
[Unknown]: and intrigue and mistrust

01:41:47.000 --> 01:41:49.000
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

01:41:49.000 --> 01:41:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And once Aurangzeb comes on the scene

01:41:51.000 --> 01:41:53.000
[Amit Varma]: even though he

01:41:53.000 --> 01:41:55.000
[Amit Varma]: rehabilitates Jahanara and all of that

01:41:55.000 --> 01:41:57.000
[Amit Varma]: women start being

01:41:57.000 --> 01:41:59.000
[Guest]: a little less consequential.

01:41:59.000 --> 01:42:01.000
[Guest]: Yes, even Jahanara Begum

01:42:01.000 --> 01:42:03.000
[Guest]: we hear much less of her

01:42:03.000 --> 01:42:05.000
[Guest]: she is Patsha Begum

01:42:05.000 --> 01:42:07.000
[Guest]: but I was not able to find

01:42:07.000 --> 01:42:09.000
[Guest]: very much about her

01:42:09.000 --> 01:42:11.000
[Guest]: about what she had accomplished post the

01:42:11.000 --> 01:42:13.000
[Guest]: death of Shah Jahan apart from the fact that

01:42:13.000 --> 01:42:15.000
[Guest]: she arranges for some grand weddings

01:42:15.000 --> 01:42:17.000
[Guest]: which was very much a role that the women carried out

01:42:17.000 --> 01:42:19.000
[Guest]: grand weddings for her nieces.

01:42:19.000 --> 01:42:21.000
[Guest]: So she continued that nurturing

01:42:21.000 --> 01:42:23.000
[Guest]: of the women

01:42:23.000 --> 01:42:25.000
[Guest]: the line of the women and looking after

01:42:25.000 --> 01:42:27.000
[Guest]: the marriages

01:42:27.000 --> 01:42:29.000
[Guest]: so she did do that and as I said she had

01:42:29.000 --> 01:42:31.000
[Guest]: a home of culture, of music and poetry

01:42:31.000 --> 01:42:33.000
[Guest]: but all the great buildings

01:42:33.000 --> 01:42:35.000
[Guest]: have now died up. There is none of this

01:42:35.000 --> 01:42:37.000
[Guest]: commissioning of amazing grand projects

01:42:37.000 --> 01:42:39.000
[Guest]: and Aurangzeb's daughters

01:42:39.000 --> 01:42:41.000
[Guest]: also, we must also

01:42:41.000 --> 01:42:43.000
[Guest]: remember that for most of their life

01:42:43.000 --> 01:42:45.000
[Guest]: Aurangzeb is in the Deccan so it's a very different

01:42:45.000 --> 01:42:47.000
[Guest]: atmosphere. It is not

01:42:47.000 --> 01:42:49.000
[Guest]: the court of Delhi

01:42:49.000 --> 01:42:51.000
[Guest]: which has been emptied now

01:42:51.000 --> 01:42:53.000
[Guest]: out of its great musicians, its great

01:42:53.000 --> 01:42:55.000
[Guest]: architects and its great

01:42:55.000 --> 01:42:57.000
[Guest]: gentlemen, they have all gone away

01:42:57.000 --> 01:42:59.000
[Guest]: so it is a very different court

01:42:59.000 --> 01:43:01.000
[Guest]: and definitely it is not a court in which

01:43:01.000 --> 01:43:03.000
[Guest]: the women are much in the limelight

01:43:03.000 --> 01:43:05.000
[Guest]: I think I am not an expert on

01:43:05.000 --> 01:43:07.000
[Guest]: Aurangzeb but it is my

01:43:07.000 --> 01:43:09.000
[Guest]: feeling that later on he has been

01:43:09.000 --> 01:43:11.000
[Guest]: he is so suspicious of all those around him

01:43:11.000 --> 01:43:13.000
[Guest]: because he has been betrayed

01:43:13.000 --> 01:43:15.000
[Guest]: this happens all the time, one daughter

01:43:15.000 --> 01:43:17.000
[Guest]: would support another brother thinking

01:43:17.000 --> 01:43:19.000
[Guest]: that Aurangzeb will surely now

01:43:19.000 --> 01:43:21.000
[Guest]: pass away, he lives to the age of 90

01:43:21.000 --> 01:43:23.000
[Guest]: but all along people think ok at 50

01:43:23.000 --> 01:43:25.000
[Guest]: he will die, at 60 he will die, at 70

01:43:25.000 --> 01:43:27.000
[Guest]: so the daughters support other brothers

01:43:27.000 --> 01:43:29.000
[Guest]: in their bid for the throne. Aurangzeb

01:43:29.000 --> 01:43:31.000
[Guest]: finds out about this and imprisons them

01:43:31.000 --> 01:43:33.000
[Guest]: so he is shackled

01:43:33.000 --> 01:43:35.000
[Guest]: by this great suspicion

01:43:35.000 --> 01:43:37.000
[Guest]: of all those around him and he doesn't let

01:43:37.000 --> 01:43:39.000
[Guest]: anybody else shine in the light the way

01:43:39.000 --> 01:43:41.000
[Amit Varma]: Jahanara did. So in a sense they are all

01:43:41.000 --> 01:43:43.000
[Amit Varma]: also in a manner imprisoned by

01:43:43.000 --> 01:43:45.000
[Amit Varma]: this great opportunity that the Timurid

01:43:45.000 --> 01:43:47.000
[Amit Varma]: line of succession also is.

01:43:47.000 --> 01:43:49.000
[Guest]: Yes, the women

01:43:49.000 --> 01:43:51.000
[Guest]: definitely were also

01:43:51.000 --> 01:43:53.000
[Guest]: because in a way

01:43:53.000 --> 01:43:55.000
[Guest]: they die out, they are not allowed

01:43:55.000 --> 01:43:57.000
[Guest]: they don't marry, they aren't Timurid

01:43:57.000 --> 01:43:59.000
[Guest]: contenders so they can't marry anymore

01:43:59.000 --> 01:44:01.000
[Guest]: and so the women

01:44:01.000 --> 01:44:03.000
[Guest]: after Aurangzeb, it would be

01:44:03.000 --> 01:44:05.000
[Guest]: interesting to write a Daughters of the Sun part 2

01:44:05.000 --> 01:44:07.000
[Guest]: because after that you find

01:44:07.000 --> 01:44:09.000
[Guest]: a very different sort of woman coming to the

01:44:09.000 --> 01:44:11.000
[Guest]: limelight, it is no longer these Timurid

01:44:11.000 --> 01:44:13.000
[Guest]: royal women, it is

01:44:13.000 --> 01:44:15.000
[Guest]: lower caste women who get married, concubines

01:44:15.000 --> 01:44:17.000
[Guest]: who rise up because they are no longer

01:44:17.000 --> 01:44:19.000
[Guest]: any more Timurid women so it goes

01:44:19.000 --> 01:44:21.000
[Guest]: in a different direction post Aurangzeb

01:44:21.000 --> 01:44:23.000
[Guest]: which is also interesting but yes the Timurids

01:44:23.000 --> 01:44:25.000
[Guest]: that hold that they have over these women

01:44:25.000 --> 01:44:27.000
[Guest]: actually ended up in a certain way

01:44:27.000 --> 01:44:29.000
[Amit Varma]: in them dying out.

01:44:29.000 --> 01:44:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And speaking of those books waiting to be written

01:44:31.000 --> 01:44:33.000
[Amit Varma]: do you find that what

01:44:33.000 --> 01:44:35.000
[Amit Varma]: you are a part of in a small way

01:44:35.000 --> 01:44:37.000
[Amit Varma]: which is this changing of this gaze

01:44:37.000 --> 01:44:39.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, going away

01:44:39.000 --> 01:44:41.000
[Amit Varma]: from the traditional gaze, going away from the

01:44:41.000 --> 01:44:43.000
[Amit Varma]: male gaze, looking at it, looking at

01:44:43.000 --> 01:44:45.000
[Amit Varma]: history differently, looking at heroism

01:44:45.000 --> 01:44:47.000
[Amit Varma]: differently, looking at the role that

01:44:47.000 --> 01:44:49.000
[Amit Varma]: women played in politics and all of it differently

01:44:49.000 --> 01:44:51.000
[Amit Varma]: do you find

01:44:51.000 --> 01:44:53.000
[Amit Varma]: that you are like one of a handful

01:44:53.000 --> 01:44:55.000
[Amit Varma]: of voices in the wilderness or the way history

01:44:55.000 --> 01:44:57.000
[Amit Varma]: is being practiced itself is gradually

01:44:57.000 --> 01:44:59.000
[Guest]: changing?

01:44:59.000 --> 01:45:01.000
[Guest]: I hope that it's changing Amit

01:45:01.000 --> 01:45:03.000
[Guest]: it's definitely being practiced differently

01:45:03.000 --> 01:45:05.000
[Guest]: at least with narrative history

01:45:05.000 --> 01:45:07.000
[Guest]: I find that in the past few

01:45:07.000 --> 01:45:09.000
[Guest]: years there have been a slew of books

01:45:09.000 --> 01:45:11.000
[Guest]: mine is just one amongst many

01:45:11.000 --> 01:45:13.000
[Guest]: books, amazing books have been written whether

01:45:13.000 --> 01:45:15.000
[Guest]: Parvati Sharma's Jahangir, you know

01:45:15.000 --> 01:45:17.000
[Guest]: Manu Pillai who's been writing, Rana Safdie who's been

01:45:17.000 --> 01:45:19.000
[Guest]: writing, Rubilal

01:45:19.000 --> 01:45:21.000
[Guest]: there are a number of books which are pitched

01:45:21.000 --> 01:45:23.000
[Guest]: at the layperson so that's

01:45:23.000 --> 01:45:25.000
[Guest]: a wonderful new thing. These are, early on we had

01:45:25.000 --> 01:45:27.000
[Guest]: we've always had great history writers but

01:45:27.000 --> 01:45:29.000
[Guest]: they've been academics and they've been pitched

01:45:29.000 --> 01:45:31.000
[Guest]: at other academics you know so it hasn't

01:45:31.000 --> 01:45:33.000
[Guest]: filtered down to the layperson

01:45:33.000 --> 01:45:35.000
[Guest]: to the degree that I find now

01:45:35.000 --> 01:45:37.000
[Guest]: it seems to be doing

01:45:37.000 --> 01:45:39.000
[Guest]: whether at the academic and scholarly level

01:45:39.000 --> 01:45:41.000
[Guest]: it is also going in a certain direction, I hope so

01:45:41.000 --> 01:45:43.000
[Guest]: with people like Rubilal doing

01:45:43.000 --> 01:45:45.000
[Guest]: the work she's doing, I hope so

01:45:45.000 --> 01:45:47.000
[Guest]: you know I hope that the scholars

01:45:47.000 --> 01:45:49.000
[Guest]: certainly people like the art historians

01:45:49.000 --> 01:45:51.000
[Guest]: are setting the history world on

01:45:51.000 --> 01:45:53.000
[Guest]: fire and we haven't talked so much

01:45:53.000 --> 01:45:55.000
[Guest]: about miniatures but art history is something

01:45:55.000 --> 01:45:57.000
[Guest]: that I use a lot when I'm researching

01:45:57.000 --> 01:45:59.000
[Guest]: because you know we always

01:45:59.000 --> 01:46:01.000
[Guest]: think that this physical evidence is static

01:46:01.000 --> 01:46:03.000
[Guest]: that it's there and you can look at it

01:46:03.000 --> 01:46:05.000
[Guest]: but it's always been the same, that's not true

01:46:05.000 --> 01:46:07.000
[Guest]: and art historians

01:46:07.000 --> 01:46:09.000
[Guest]: are at the vanguard of this change

01:46:09.000 --> 01:46:11.000
[Guest]: because they are looking at these same miniatures

01:46:11.000 --> 01:46:13.000
[Guest]: from say 500 years ago, 400 years ago

01:46:13.000 --> 01:46:15.000
[Guest]: and they're reinterpreting them

01:46:15.000 --> 01:46:17.000
[Guest]: in completely new ways, completely

01:46:17.000 --> 01:46:19.000
[Guest]: novel ways which is changing then the way somebody

01:46:19.000 --> 01:46:21.000
[Guest]: like I would write about history

01:46:21.000 --> 01:46:23.000
[Guest]: so for example there's a miniature from the time

01:46:23.000 --> 01:46:25.000
[Guest]: of Humayun which used to be called

01:46:25.000 --> 01:46:27.000
[Guest]: Humayun and his brothers

01:46:27.000 --> 01:46:29.000
[Guest]: just a very general one, if you look at it

01:46:29.000 --> 01:46:31.000
[Guest]: it looks like a painting of somebody

01:46:31.000 --> 01:46:33.000
[Guest]: you know who has taken a lot of

01:46:33.000 --> 01:46:35.000
[Guest]: hallucinatory drugs

01:46:35.000 --> 01:46:37.000
[Guest]: because it's full of colors and wild colors

01:46:37.000 --> 01:46:39.000
[Guest]: and there are lots of figures

01:46:39.000 --> 01:46:41.000
[Guest]: but art historians, I think it is

01:46:41.000 --> 01:46:43.000
[Guest]: Dr. Laura Parodi has had a close look

01:46:43.000 --> 01:46:45.000
[Guest]: at this painting which is of Humayun

01:46:45.000 --> 01:46:47.000
[Guest]: and somebody who looks like his brother

01:46:47.000 --> 01:46:49.000
[Guest]: Hindal next to him and

01:46:49.000 --> 01:46:51.000
[Guest]: other gentlemen also but groups

01:46:51.000 --> 01:46:53.000
[Guest]: of women as well and she has looked

01:46:53.000 --> 01:46:55.000
[Guest]: at these groups of women and she has individually

01:46:55.000 --> 01:46:57.000
[Guest]: identified them and said

01:46:57.000 --> 01:46:59.000
[Guest]: that one group of women is clearly

01:46:59.000 --> 01:47:01.000
[Guest]: Hamida Banu Begum, Gulbadan

01:47:01.000 --> 01:47:03.000
[Guest]: Begum, I think Bega Begum

01:47:03.000 --> 01:47:05.000
[Guest]: and a fourth sister and another

01:47:05.000 --> 01:47:07.000
[Guest]: set of women is the milk mothers, perhaps

01:47:07.000 --> 01:47:09.000
[Guest]: Mahamanga and Jidiyanga

01:47:09.000 --> 01:47:11.000
[Guest]: so now we are looking at this

01:47:11.000 --> 01:47:13.000
[Guest]: in a completely different light, this is not Humayun

01:47:13.000 --> 01:47:15.000
[Guest]: and his brothers, this is a place

01:47:15.000 --> 01:47:17.000
[Guest]: where women were very very important

01:47:17.000 --> 01:47:19.000
[Guest]: and they have said this is probably

01:47:19.000 --> 01:47:21.000
[Guest]: a place associated with fertility

01:47:21.000 --> 01:47:23.000
[Guest]: rights, therefore it is probably the

01:47:23.000 --> 01:47:25.000
[Guest]: circumcision ceremony of Akbar

01:47:25.000 --> 01:47:27.000
[Guest]: so it is telling us a great deal about

01:47:27.000 --> 01:47:29.000
[Guest]: what happened during circumcision ceremonies, how

01:47:29.000 --> 01:47:31.000
[Guest]: important the women were, how important

01:47:31.000 --> 01:47:33.000
[Guest]: fertility rights were, which was something that we had

01:47:33.000 --> 01:47:35.000
[Guest]: not talked about at all before

01:47:35.000 --> 01:47:37.000
[Guest]: and will completely now change the way that I

01:47:37.000 --> 01:47:39.000
[Guest]: will write about episodes like

01:47:39.000 --> 01:47:41.000
[Guest]: this. So yes

01:47:41.000 --> 01:47:43.000
[Guest]: art historians are definitely

01:47:43.000 --> 01:47:45.000
[Guest]: pushing those boundaries and

01:47:45.000 --> 01:47:47.000
[Guest]: bringing in new ways, new interpretations

01:47:47.000 --> 01:47:49.000
[Amit Varma]: all the time. This sounds really fascinating

01:47:49.000 --> 01:47:51.000
[Amit Varma]: though a young millennial today

01:47:51.000 --> 01:47:53.000
[Amit Varma]: would think oh it's like Facebook tagging, you go

01:47:53.000 --> 01:47:55.000
[Amit Varma]: back to the past and you take a miniature

01:47:55.000 --> 01:47:57.000
[Amit Varma]: and you tag everybody and you give

01:47:57.000 --> 01:47:59.000
[Unknown]: the location and all that. Exactly

01:47:59.000 --> 01:48:01.000
[Amit Varma]: kind of like that. So you know

01:48:01.000 --> 01:48:03.000
[Amit Varma]: my listeners keep asking me on social media

01:48:03.000 --> 01:48:05.000
[Amit Varma]: that you talk to such interesting guests, why don't you

01:48:05.000 --> 01:48:07.000
[Amit Varma]: get some book recommendations for us

01:48:07.000 --> 01:48:09.000
[Amit Varma]: because we want to read more on this subject

01:48:09.000 --> 01:48:11.000
[Amit Varma]: so you know for example art history

01:48:11.000 --> 01:48:13.000
[Amit Varma]: what do you recommend people read

01:48:13.000 --> 01:48:15.000
[Amit Varma]: or even just history in general

01:48:15.000 --> 01:48:17.000
[Amit Varma]: what are the books in the last few years

01:48:17.000 --> 01:48:19.000
[Guest]: which you just thought everybody must read

01:48:19.000 --> 01:48:21.000
[Guest]: I think for anybody

01:48:21.000 --> 01:48:23.000
[Guest]: who is interested in gendered history

01:48:23.000 --> 01:48:25.000
[Guest]: even Empress you know

01:48:25.000 --> 01:48:27.000
[Guest]: the biography of Noor Jehan will change

01:48:27.000 --> 01:48:29.000
[Guest]: the way you look at Noor Jehan. Rubilal

01:48:29.000 --> 01:48:31.000
[Guest]: Rubilal will change the way you look at Jahangir

01:48:31.000 --> 01:48:33.000
[Guest]: you know. So that's an important

01:48:33.000 --> 01:48:35.000
[Guest]: book. I very much

01:48:35.000 --> 01:48:37.000
[Guest]: enjoyed Rebel Sultans by you know

01:48:37.000 --> 01:48:39.000
[Guest]: Manu.

01:48:39.000 --> 01:48:41.000
[Guest]: What else would I recommend? You know I read some pretty

01:48:41.000 --> 01:48:43.000
[Guest]: dry stuff so I don't know if I would recommend it

01:48:43.000 --> 01:48:45.000
[Guest]: to all your listeners

01:48:45.000 --> 01:48:47.000
[Guest]: but anything that's coming out of

01:48:47.000 --> 01:48:49.000
[Guest]: on you know any of these coffee table books

01:48:49.000 --> 01:48:51.000
[Guest]: on the art history, on miniatures

01:48:51.000 --> 01:48:53.000
[Guest]: is changing all the time so it's

01:48:53.000 --> 01:48:55.000
[Guest]: absolutely fascinating even for a lay person

01:48:55.000 --> 01:48:57.000
[Guest]: to read because A you have the

01:48:57.000 --> 01:48:59.000
[Guest]: images which sometimes seem

01:48:59.000 --> 01:49:01.000
[Guest]: dull and repetitive if you just look at it

01:49:01.000 --> 01:49:03.000
[Guest]: you know without the knowledge behind it

01:49:03.000 --> 01:49:05.000
[Guest]: but when you are told certain details

01:49:05.000 --> 01:49:07.000
[Guest]: you know about the

01:49:07.000 --> 01:49:09.000
[Guest]: miniatures then you look at it

01:49:09.000 --> 01:49:11.000
[Guest]: completely differently. For example there's a

01:49:11.000 --> 01:49:13.000
[Guest]: painting which is used

01:49:13.000 --> 01:49:15.000
[Guest]: constantly called Birth of a Prince

01:49:15.000 --> 01:49:17.000
[Guest]: it's probably the birth of Salim

01:49:17.000 --> 01:49:19.000
[Guest]: the future Jahangir and

01:49:19.000 --> 01:49:21.000
[Guest]: when you look and I've looked at it many times and I've used

01:49:21.000 --> 01:49:23.000
[Guest]: it in my books, in the middle is the mother

01:49:23.000 --> 01:49:25.000
[Guest]: and all around her are what are

01:49:25.000 --> 01:49:27.000
[Guest]: timorous looking women and some

01:49:27.000 --> 01:49:29.000
[Guest]: Rajasthani looking women but she

01:49:29.000 --> 01:49:31.000
[Guest]: herself is dusky you know

01:49:31.000 --> 01:49:33.000
[Guest]: and she's clearly Rajasthani and this is her

01:49:33.000 --> 01:49:35.000
[Guest]: Kabai herself and I think

01:49:35.000 --> 01:49:37.000
[Guest]: you know my god the makers of Jodha Akbar

01:49:37.000 --> 01:49:39.000
[Guest]: should have looked at this before casting Aishwarya Rai

01:49:39.000 --> 01:49:41.000
[Guest]: because she looks nothing like this you know

01:49:41.000 --> 01:49:43.000
[Guest]: so books on art

01:49:43.000 --> 01:49:45.000
[Guest]: history today are amazing

01:49:45.000 --> 01:49:47.000
[Guest]: and they will open your eyes to something

01:49:47.000 --> 01:49:49.000
[Guest]: completely novel and a new way of seeing the past

01:49:49.000 --> 01:49:51.000
[Amit Varma]: It's really exciting I'm going to go to

01:49:51.000 --> 01:49:53.000
[Guest]: Amazon right after this. Can we now ask

01:49:53.000 --> 01:49:55.000
[Guest]: what are you working on now?

01:49:55.000 --> 01:49:57.000
[Guest]: So now I'm still in the Mughal period

01:49:57.000 --> 01:49:59.000
[Guest]: and I'm writing

01:49:59.000 --> 01:50:01.000
[Guest]: a history of Akbar, a biography

01:50:01.000 --> 01:50:03.000
[Guest]: of Akbar and

01:50:03.000 --> 01:50:05.000
[Guest]: it's very exciting for me because

01:50:05.000 --> 01:50:07.000
[Guest]: so far I've only seen Akbar really

01:50:07.000 --> 01:50:09.000
[Guest]: through his women so now I'm seeing

01:50:09.000 --> 01:50:11.000
[Guest]: Akbar but with his women

01:50:11.000 --> 01:50:13.000
[Guest]: alongside him because I think they're often written

01:50:13.000 --> 01:50:15.000
[Guest]: out of histories of Akbar

01:50:15.000 --> 01:50:17.000
[Guest]: you know it has as we have been

01:50:17.000 --> 01:50:19.000
[Guest]: discussing this entire time

01:50:19.000 --> 01:50:21.000
[Guest]: scholars tend to scrunch up

01:50:21.000 --> 01:50:23.000
[Guest]: the history of Mughal women into one chapter

01:50:23.000 --> 01:50:25.000
[Guest]: so you have 200 years of existence

01:50:25.000 --> 01:50:27.000
[Guest]: changing, dynamic existence

01:50:27.000 --> 01:50:29.000
[Guest]: scrunched up into one way

01:50:29.000 --> 01:50:31.000
[Guest]: of being as if there is a one way in

01:50:31.000 --> 01:50:33.000
[Guest]: 200 years things won't change you know as if food

01:50:33.000 --> 01:50:35.000
[Guest]: won't change, etiquette won't change

01:50:35.000 --> 01:50:37.000
[Guest]: so with Akbar I'm hoping to

01:50:37.000 --> 01:50:39.000
[Guest]: show not just his

01:50:39.000 --> 01:50:41.000
[Guest]: life but how from his very birth

01:50:41.000 --> 01:50:43.000
[Guest]: from the time of you know his milk mothers

01:50:43.000 --> 01:50:45.000
[Guest]: how all these women entered his life

01:50:45.000 --> 01:50:47.000
[Guest]: changed him, influenced him

01:50:47.000 --> 01:50:49.000
[Guest]: how he changed them like the

01:50:49.000 --> 01:50:51.000
[Guest]: Rajput women and how

01:50:51.000 --> 01:50:53.000
[Guest]: Akbar and build a I hope

01:50:53.000 --> 01:50:55.000
